abstract: Our philosophical neighbors of the Tribune commence, in yesterday's issue, an article evidently designed as a severe rebuke to this journal for not supporting "a regular, nominee," in the following mysterious words: "CUVIER was once shown for scruting a dictionary definition running thus: "Crab, n., a...
lead_paragraph: Our philosophical neighbors of the Tribune commence, in yesterday's issue, an article evidently designed as a severe rebuke to this journal for not supporting "a regular, nominee," in the following mysterious words: "CUVIER was once shown for scruting a dictionary definition running thus: "Crab, n., a fish, of red color, that goes backward.'" On this luminous text our neighbors preach a sermon of ten heads, each main branch of the discourse divided into as many considerations as the ordinary crab has legs. To our great regret, however, we are nowhere informed who it was that asked CUVIER to do the "scruting" in the case, nor is the dictionary named in which appeared the definition making this "scruting" necessary.

abstract: As the days of Judge RUSSELL'S power draw near their unlamented close, the soul of that functionary would seem to embrace larger ideas of philanthropy a wider and more significant view of those qualities for which Mercy" has been praised . No longer send-...
lead_paragraph: As the days of Judge RUSSELL'S power draw near their unlamented close, the soul of that functionary would seem to embrace larger ideas of philanthropy a wider and more significant view of those qualities for which Mercy" has been praised . No longer sending men to State Prison for forty years on a charge of stealing sixpence, he now delights to open the doors of prisons and bid the guilty cast off their chains. It is very true that this desire does not as yet appear to have taken general hold of his mind -- the recipients of such bounty thus far being all voters of the right political stripe and holding rank amongst our "ruling classes," either from the force of their individual muscle or from the number of voters their voices are thought capable of controlling.

abstract: Robert Latta vs. The Cargo of the Bark Hermitage.--NELSON, C. J.--The libel was filed in this case in rem against the cargo of the vessel, to recover freight under a charter party.
lead_paragraph: Robert Latta vs. The Cargo of the Bark Hermitage. -- NELSON, C.J. -- The libel was filed in this case in rem against the cargo of the vessel, to recover freight under a charter party. This charter party was entered into between the libelant and Messrs. Abranches, Almeida & Co., merchants, for the employment of the vessel from the port of New-York to the West Coast of Africa, on a trading voyage and back to New-York, with the privilege of continuing the voyage for a year. The owner engaged to keep the vessel well fitted, tight and staunch, and provided with every requisite necessary for such trading voyage, excepting captain, crew and provisions, and that the whole vessel (with the exception of the cabin, the deck, and necessary room for the accommodation of the crew and storage of sails and cables) should be at the sole use and disposal of the charterers; and that no goods or merchandise should be laden on board otherwise than from them; and the owner also bound himself to receive on board the vessel, during the voyage, all such lawful goods and merchandise as the charterers might think proper to ship.

abstract: It was erroneously announced that Gov. CURTIN, of Pennsylvania, would address the Republicans of this City in the City Hall Park last evening. Many Republicans and other citizens visited the appointed place, only to be disappointed. The TIMES office was besieged with inquirers on the subject. Mr. CURTIN was not apprized of any preparations for him to speak. He will probably address the Republicans of New-York at Palace Garden, and, in the course of the week say a cheering word for the cause in New-Jersey.

abstract: There is a wonderful vivifying power in light. We speak not of the "glorious luminary" -- but of blazing tar-barrels, waving torches, and Wide-Awake lamps. All varieties of these inducements to popular assemblage were exhibited last night throughout the City. They nowhere shed a fiercer glare than in the Fifth Congressional District -- a District where the candidates at one time defied all ordinary attempts at enumeration, but have now decreased to the comprehensible number of five or six. One of these is Mr. JOHN DUFFY, whilom. Consul at Galway under the Pierce regime, now a citizen of the District which he aspires to represent in Washington, as the advocate of the Workingman's rights, and the unflinching supporter of the "Union, the Constitution and the Laws."

abstract: We would call attention to the report of certain opinions delivered yesterday by the United States District-Attorney, on the indictment of the captain and mate of the slaver Erie, in the Circuit Court of the United States, Judge NELSON presiding, and apparently acquiescing in the District-Attorney's views. The Erie, it will be remembered, was boarded by an American war-steamer on the Coast of Africa, and on raising the hatches nine hundred unhappy negroes were found stowed away in her hold. A clearer case could not well be conceived by the common mind, both prisoners being on board of her at the time of capture, and apparently serving in the capacities of captain and mate.

abstract: EMANCIPATION IN THE DUTCH WEST INDIES. -- The bill for the abolition of Slavery in the Dutch West Indies has been laid before the Chambers, accompanied with statements of the arguments in its favor. The Government conceives that it is difficult, if not impossible, to rally differing opinions so as to form a sufficient majority. The Minister for the Colonies have always had, and still has, the strongest desire to arrive at slave emancipation as early as possible, and with as little danger as practicable. The measure is necessary, he says, as well for the interest of the colonies as that of the mother-country, and therefore he will be rejoiced if it should fall to his lot to contribute in any great degree to its success. The Government also ardently desires that the emancipation should be promptly effected; and the Minister declares his solemn intention of lending thereto his serious attention. The bill is drawn up in conformity to various suggestions that had been thrown out in the Chambers. The cost of emancipation is estimated at 13,859,280 florins, independently of 2,000,000 for the encouragement of immigration.

abstract: Within a few days Capt. WALLING, of the Detective Police, has been in the receipt of information which satisfied him beyond a doubt that an extensive business in the way of altering bank-notes was conducted at the house No. 41 King-street, occupied in part by two brothers, both young men, named ANDREW and SAMUEL ROBERTS. He accordingly obtained a warrant authorizing a search of the premises and placed it in the hands of Officers BENNETT, MCDOUGAL and WILSON, who on Tuesday afternoon executed the commission with which they were intrusted. Having entered the house, Officer BENNETT determined upon taking a position in the rear yard to prevent the egress of any person in that direction, and turning the knob of the door which he supposed led to the yard, he was surprised to find that it opened into an extension-room where ANDREW ROBERTS had been apparently at that very moment engaged in the manufacture of the worthless bills. His arrest was immediately effected, and a search of the apartment resulted in the discovery of several packages of counterfeit notes, mostly of the denomination of tens, upon Southern banks, in various stages of manufacture. In addition to the bills, two copper-plates were found, with engravings upon them corresponding to impressions upon some af the unfinished notes, which were still damp and had evidently been recently taken from one of two presses, used for printing bank-notes, which also were found in the room. The notes, plates and other implements were seized, and, with the prisoner, taken to head-quarters, after which the other suspected forger, SAMUEL ROBERTS, was apprehended at a saloon called the Oyster Bay, at the corner of Spring and Mercer streets, of which he is said to be the propietor. A further search of the house in King-street was then prosecuted, and more of the counterfeits were obtained, as well as four Savings' Bank books, in the name of ANDREW ROBERTS, representing sums, the aggregate of which amounted to between $5,000 and $6,000, and other valuable property. It is supposed that the prisoners have been engaged for many years in the pursuit of altering genuine bills of broken banks to supply the demand of professional operators for forged papers of this description, and the notes seized bear testimony to the fact that they were altered by a skillful hand. Upon counting the paper it was found that it represented nearly $4,000, most of which required only a few touches of the manufacturer to make it ready for use. The prisoners were, yesterday afternoon, taken before Justice QUACKENBUSH for examination, on the charge preferred against them, and pending the result of the hearing they were committed to prison.

lead_paragraph: The steamship Fulton, from Southampton on the 17th ult., arrived at this port last evening with advices already briefly telegraphed from Cape Race. The authority for the report that the Russian and Prussian Ambassadors at Turin had protested against the invasion of Neapolitan territory by Sardinia, is the official journal published at Munich. King VICTOR EMANUEL had issued a proclamation to the people of Italy from Ancona, in which he virtually assumes the position of King and Ruler of Italy. Count CAVOUR had delivered a most important speech in the Sardinian Chambers on the leading topics of the day. The differences with GARIBALDI and the Roman and Venetian questions were the subjects enlarged upon.

abstract: About 11 o'clock, on Tuesday night, BILLY MULLIGAN made a savage assault upon his old enemy, FRANK MCCABE, whom he encounterad at the corner of Broadway and Prince streets, and both men having been arrested, were taken to the Eighth Ward Station-house, where they were locked up -- the former on a charge of disorderly conduct, and the latter as the complainant in the case. The prisoners, however, had not been long in custody before City Judge RUSSELL, in response to a request of their associates, went to the Station-house and released them upon bail, in the sum of $500 each, furnished for their appearance at 10 o'clock yesterday morning, before Justice QUACKENBUSH. At the appointed hour MULLIGAN kept his faith, and presented himself at the Police Court, but MCCABE did not appear. The affidavit of the policeman who made the arrests was, however, deemed sufficient to warrant the magistrate in requiring the accused to give bail for trial on the charge, and the sum of $500 having been fixed upon, a surety was found and he was discharged. Judge RUSSELL has thrice during the present week opened Court at the same Station-house, and discharged prisoners under similar circumstances.

abstract: The Charleston Mercury bitterly laments the apathy of the South for lending no encouragement to newspaper enterprise. It draws in this matter, as it might draw in others, a strong contrast between the energy and activity displayed at the North and the sluggishness manifested at the South, and complains that even a journal conducted with such marked ability as the Mercury finds few supporters.
lead_paragraph: The Charleston Mercury bitterly laments the apathy of the South for lending no encouragement to newspaper enterprise. It draws in this matter, as it might draw in others, a strong contrast between the energy and activity displayed at the North and the sluggishness manifested at the South, and complains that even a journal conducted with such marked ability as the Mercury finds few supporters. We might explain this by the absence of that great middle class which cannot exist in a country where the population is divided into lords of the soil and serfs; for it is this same middle class which gives the most valuable support to Northern journals. Without such a class it would be impossible for one of our newspapers to live at the price at which it is published. But we let the Mercury give utterance to its own over-truthful remarks upon a subject so suggestive:

lead_paragraph: POLITICAL. The Breckinridge Democracy held a mass meeting in City Hall Square last night, to listen to an address from JAS. T. BRADY, Esq. Not less than five thousand people were present, and the greatest enthusiasm prevailed. Ex-Alderman WILSON, of the Eighth Ward, presided.....The Banner Republican Club, of the Third Assembly District, held a public meeting last night in the Fulton-street Wigwam, which was well filled. abstract: The eastern, and western extremities of the Territory of Kansas present just now the most remarkable divergencies of condition and of prospect. The letters and newspapers from Arrapahoe County (in which is Pike's Peak) come to us weekly freighted with exciting intelligence of golden discoveries, big nuggets, rich "leads" and rapid fortunes;...
lead_paragraph: The eastern and western extremities of the Territory of Kansas present just now the most remarkable divergencies of condition and of prospect. The letters and newspapers from Arrapahoe County (in which is Pike's Peak) come to us weekly freighted with exciting intelligence of golden discoveries, big nuggets, rich "leads" and rapid fortunes; those from Lynn, Lykins, Shawnee and other Counties are filled with tales of poverty, of famine, and, in at least one instance, of actual starvation. The wail of want from the dwellers on the Plains that skirt the Neosho and the Kaw joins with the shout of the gold-digger amid the gulches and canons of the Rocky Mountain's, and send hitherward an united echo at once sad and terrible. Throughout the greater part of the Territory an unparalleled drouth has destroyed all the crops, and now Winter and Famine stare the hapless pioneers in the face. Already it is announced that a great part of the population are fleeing or have already fled from their famine-smitten cabins, their parched fields and withered crops. For a hundred and fifty miles west of the Missouri every highway is crowded with wagons filled with men, women and children, fleeing as if Death were in the rear; while, for those left behind, only the saddest prospects are before them. The bold freemen who but four years ago cowed the red-shirted ruffians of the border, now quail before a thin spectre round whose lean haunches is buckled no bowie-knife or revolver, but against whom the stoutest courage avails not in the fight.

abstract: At a solemn moment for the national history and for the destinies of the country I address my word to you, people of Southern Italy, who, having in my name changed the State, send me deputations of every class of citizens, magistrates and representatives of your municipal bodies, asking to be restored to order, blessed with freedom, and united with my kingdom. I will tell you by what thought I am guided, and what is my consciousness of the duties which a man placed by Providence on an Italian throne ought to fulfill.

abstract: FATAL ACCIDENT TO A PUBLIC SCHOOL PUPIL. -- On Tuesday afternoon, a little girl named ANTONIA ROHREY, attending Public School No. 5, in Fourth-street, while descending the stairs leading to the street, slipped, and fell almost from the top to the bottom. She struck the back of her head with considerable violence, but at the time it was believed that she was not seriously injured. Soon, however, after her return to her aunt's residence, at No. 58 Avenue B, she became insensible, and died in the course of the night. Coroner SCHIRMER yesterday held an inquest upon the body, and a verdict was rendered to the effect that the fall had occasioned her death.

abstract: It is questionable if a bevy of more beautiful girls or a band of brighter-looking boys were ever got together than were last night assembled in the Northwest Reformed Dutch Church, to celebrate the Two Hundred and Twenty-seventh Anniversary of the School. The body of the church was filled with proud parents, and gratified uncles and aunts, and sympathizing brothers and sisters. One hundred and fifty...
lead_paragraph: It is questionable if a bevy of more beautiful girls or a band of brighter-looking boys were ever got together than were last night assembled in the Northwest Reformed Dutch Church, to celebrate the Two Hundred and Twenty-seventh Anniversary of the School. The body of the church was filled with proud parents, and gratified uncles and aunts, and sympathizing brothers and sisters. One hundred and fifty men and matrons to be, occupied the platform, the boys dressed in the trimmest of roundabouts and the girls in the purest of white dresses. At one end of the church stretched the appropriate inscription, "Prayer and Effort," and over the stage, "Nisi Dominus Fruitra." It was a goodly sight to see.

abstract: The friends of the Union in the South are forgetting past differences, and joining hand in hand to defeat BRECKINRIDGE, the candidate of the Disunionists. We confess that the stand taken by the supporters of BELL and DOUGLAS in the slaveholding States, commands our cordial respect. They fight under every...
lead_paragraph: The friends of the Union in the South are forgetting past differences, and joining hand in hand to defeat BRECKINRIDGE, the candidate of the Disunionists. We confess that the stand taken by the supporters of BELL and DOUGLAS in the slaveholding States, commands our cordial respect. They fight under every disadvantage of position, with the patronage of the Federal and State Governments against them, and with all the passions, and the apparent, though not the real interests of the slaveholding classes arrayed on the side of their opponents, yet they fight bravely and manfully, and entertain strong hopes of victory. They fight for the Union and the Constitution, and scorn the traitorous thought of dissolving the Union because their party may sustain defeat in the Presidential contest.

abstract: Pastor Riemus, the Cuban, who was arrested last Tuesday on a charge of having robbed his late employers, Messrs. Carbajose, Ybaraybal & Co., merchants at Havana, of $20,000, was yesterday taken before Justice WELSH for examination. The agent of the firm, by whom the accused was pursued to this City, was unable to swear to the identity of any of the money which has been rescued, and the prisoner was discharged from custody. A short time afterwards, however, Riemus was rearrested in a civil suit commenced against him, and his bail in the case was fixed at $20,000. Not being able to give a surety for that amount he was placed in the Eldridge-street prison. Officer Niven has succeeded in recovering within a fraction of the entire amount alleged to have been stolen.

abstract: In some of the Districts voters may find themselves subjected to much inconvenience if they are not early at the polls. Yesterday morning, for instance, over 900 names had been registered in the Third District of the Eighteenth Ward. It is evident that such a number of votes as this can only be polled by industrious work all day long, and those who desire to avail themselves of the right of suffrage should remember that a crowd around the polling places in the afternoon, is only to be avoided by attending to their duty early in the morning. Doubtless there are other Districts in the City to which the same caution would apply.

abstract: -- A distinguished clergyman of Brooklyn, whose reputation for benevolence is as great as that for eloquence, received, a few days since, a letter from a responsible Southern gentlemen, stating that he had thirty-five slaves whose market value was $30,000, but which he would sell to this clergyman for $20,000, pocketing the loss cheerfully. Circumstances render an early sale to some one or at public auction, imperative, and rather than have his servants parted and their family ties destroyed, he would make the necessary sacrifice by selling them cheap to any party desiring to make them free.

abstract: Another case of proscription in Virginia has just come to our notice. A resident of this City, born and brought up in that State, ventured a few days since to visit his relations who still reside in Norfolk County. He left this City on the 11th, and soon after his arrival in Norfolk went back in the country about 18 miles, -- near a small place known as Deer Creek. The excitement regarding the recent insurrections in that vicinity had hardly subsided, and as the gentleman expressed, "they were flogging negroes and the devil was to pay generally." He kept his counsel, however, and supposed that he would be allowed to visit his relations in peace as he has done for the last eight or ten years; but the very day after his arrival he heard that some one had announced the advent of an Abolitionist. A few hours afterwards, as he was out of doors conversing with a friend, an individual whom he took to be a genuine fire-eater, approached him and blusteringly demanded whether he were not there "electioneering for LINCOLN. If you are," he proceeded, "you had better make yourself scarce, for no Northerner who cannot prove that he is sound on the Slavery question can stay here a day, -- no, nor two hours, for that matter." As our friend had been careful not to express any opinions likely to involve him in difficulty, he might have interposed an emphatic denial to the first of the charges brought against him; but he preferred to keep quiet. Under the circumstances he deemed it expedient to materially curtail his visit, and returned some days earlier than he had intended. He escaped without being subjected to further insult or threats of violence, and while avowing that his experience has made him a more earnest Republican than he ever dreamed he could be, expresses the hope that this incident may open the eyes of others to the necessity of adding a few more votes to Mr. LINCOLN's majority in this State. We have the name of this latest victim to Virginian intolerance.

abstract: If We are to accept the extremely positive but equally uncircumstantial assertion of a Sunday morning telegram sent from Liverpool to Queenstown, the Warsaw Con- ference has borne its first fruits; and the magnificent speech in which the
lead_paragraph: If we are to accept the extremely positive but equally uncircumstantial assertion of a Sunday morning telegram sent from Liverpool to Queenstown, the Warsaw Conference has borne its first fruits; and the magnificent speech in which the Count DE CAVOUR has just laid down the grand basis of Italian development has been met by the interruption of diplomatic relations between the Courts of Russia and Sardinia. So far as the immediate policy of VICTOR EMANUEL is concerned, a step of this kind can hardly be thought likely seriously to interfere with the now inevitable effort of the King of Italy to make his great title a reality and the people who put their faith and hope in him a nation of united freemen. Russian embassies have been withdrawn, ere this, from other Courts on the like provocation, without formidably shaking the fabric of social or political order by their defection. Constitutional Spain continued to exist very comfortably for nearly a quarter of a century without the benignant presence of a Muscovite envoy in the corridors and the galleries of the Escurial. And it is much more than probable that ALEXANDER II., if he has thus committed himself against the current of the times, will see good reason to repent of the weakness which has bent him from the wise policy of his Premier, GORTSCHAKOFF, long before the Italian monarchy will find itself incomplete without the ornamental presence of his representative near the person of the Italian King.

abstract: THE FUSION TORCHLIGHT PROCESSION.--The long talked-of Fusion torchlight procession came off last evening, but it hardly came up to the expectations of its originators. By actual count, at two different points, one person counted 1,300, and the other 1,400.
lead_paragraph: THE FUSION TORCHLIGHT PROCESSION.-- The long talked-of Fusion torchlight procession came off last evening, but it hardly came up to the expectations of its originators. By actual count, at two different points, one person counted 1,300, and the other 1,400. The procession was just fifteen minutes passing the City Hall. The line was formed at 7 1/2 o'clock, and passed through DeKalb and Fulton avenues, Joralemon-street, Court-street, Atlantic-street, Clinton-street, Fulton-street, Myrtle-avenue, in the Western District, and through some of the principal avenues in the Eastern District. Besides the Brooklyn clubs, there were Fusion organizations from New-York, New-Jersey, Bay Ridge, East New-York and Greenpoint. About one-half of the men on foot carried either lanterns or torches. There were a few transparencies, (none of a local character were allowed,) three boats and a number of flags, composed the display.

abstract: The capture of the late WILLIAM WALKKR by a British man-of-war has afforded an opportunity to the London Times to have another fling at the United States, and to accuse us of being unable to keep the police of our own seas. Unfortunately the accusation is borne.
lead_paragraph: The capture of the late WILLIAM WALKKR by a British man-of-war has afforded an opportunity to the London Times to have another fling at the United States, and to accuse us of being unable to keep the police of our own seas. Unfortunately the accusation is borne out by facts, and particularly by Mr. SANDFORD's letter to Gen. CASS, published, in yesterday's TIMES. Every American citizen who has interests at stake in foreign countries knows perfectly well that they receive but slender protection from the United States Government; and Mr. SANDFORD, who has just returned from Panama, furnishes us with a fresh example immediately in point. That Isthmus is the most important highway of travel between the Atlantic and Pacific States. It is estimated that fifty thousand American citizens, six hundred tons of United States mails, a hundred millions of American bullion, and many millions of dollars' worth of American merchandise are annually conveyed across this transit; -- yet when an outbreak like that of 1856, was recently threatened by the savages that infest the isthmus, protection for the lives and property of American citizens could only be obtained at a heavy cost to the Railroad Company.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. "Der Freischutz" was sung at the Academy, on Wednesday, to a swarm of Swabians, Bavarians, Prussians and other Teutons, by the strictly German Company of the Formes-Fabbri dynasty. It was more aptly put upon the stage than the "Iluguenots," and much more aptly cast.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- "Der Freischutz" was sung at the Academy, on Wednesday, to a swarm of Swabians, Bavarians, Prussians and other Teutons, by the strictly German Company of the Formes-Fabbri dynasty. It was more aptly put upon the stage than the "Huguenots," and much more aptly cast. FORMES revels in this opera in one of the most dramatic, fantastic and forcible of roles, and he threw himself into it on Wednesday with a true Teutonic joy. Almost as much should be said for his tenore STIGELLI; and had Mme. FABBRI been more familiar with the score of her own character, as much might, also, have been said for her. The symphonic and choral effects were fairly given, and this opera of delicious inspirations was, on the whole, not unbecomingly interpreted. To-night we have the whole Company thoroughly at home in "Martha."

abstract: By the arrival of the steamship Bohemian off Father Point, and the Europa off Cape Race, we receive four days later news from Europe. The most important intelligence is that the Russian Embassy has quitted Turin. No particulars are
lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the steamship Bohemian off Father Point, and the Europa off Cape Race, we receive four days later news from Europe. The most important intelligence is that the Russian Embassy has quitted Turin. No particulars are given; but the diplomatic rupture is probably caused by the invasion of Neapolitan territory by Sardinia. There was also a report that the Sardinian Ambassador at St. Petersburg had received his passports. The departure of the Papal Nuncio from Paris is also announced, and the event is looked upon as the forerunner of the Pope's quitting Rome. In other respects Italian affairs remained generally unchanged. A corps d'armee of 15,000 Piedmontese is said to have reached Naples. According to the Paris Patrie, GARIBALDI, as soon as the annexation of the Two Sicilies to Sardinia has been proclaimed, will resign all political authority and assume the title and duties of the Commander-in-Chief of the land and sea forces of Southern Italy. Queen VICTORIA and her suite had returned to England from Germany.

abstract: In amicable contiguity to the scene of the Williamson and Wood ratification meetings in the Third Congressional District, the friends of JOHN C. MATHER for Congressional Representative of that District, met last evening in the vicinity of the principal Fifth Ward liberty pole. As much light as possible was thrown
lead_paragraph: In amicable contiguity to the scene of the Williamson and Wood ratification meetings in the Third Congressional District, the friends of JOHN C. MATHER for Congressional Representative of that District, met last evening in the vicinity of the principal Fifth Ward liberty pole. As much light as possible was thrown upon the subject by the presence of a thousand torches and transparencies, and the continual display of pyrotechnics. The gathering rivaled the Republican demonstration, recently held at the same place, in numbers, and the Wood ratification in point of respectability. The stand was brilliantly set off with Chinese lanterns, torches, fireworks and banners, and during the evening the scene was enlivened by the arrival of the Clubs from different parts of the District.

abstract: -- About eighteen years ago, JOHN QUINCY ADAMS presented a petition to the House of Representatives, praying for a peaceable dissolution of the Union, and proposed its reference to a Special Committee, with instructions to report against the object of the petitioners. This petition was received by the South with a storm of indignant denunciation, and HENRY A. WISE was foremost in insisting upon the censure of the venerable patriot and friend of Union, for, simply, out of mere reverence for the right of petition, offering such an insult, as he regarded it, to the Nation. This occurred at a time when Slavery was excluded from nearly all the Territories of the Union by act of Congress, and when not even Mr. WISE proposed or dreamed of repeal. The same Mr. WISE now insists that the Union shall be dissolved because a man is about to be elected to the Presidency who insists that that act of Slavery restriction was constitutional.

The game, according to announcement, was between DUDLEY KAVANAGH, the winner of the prize cue, and Mr. PHELAN. The room was crowded with gentlemen and ladies.
lead_paragraph: THE BILLIARD TOURNMENT -- MR. PHELAN THE VICTOR. -- The last game of the Billiard Tournment was played yesterday at the Billiard Rooms, Fourteenth-street, Union-square. The game, according to announcement, was between DUDLEY KAVANAGH, the winner of the prize cue, and Mr. PHELAN. The room was crowded with gentlemen and ladies. Messrs. PHELAN and KAVAGNAGH were warmly applauded upon entering the arena, and also at times during the game. Great interest was shown by the audience during the fluctuations in the game, which for the first two hundred points was greatly in favor of KAVAGNAH, PHELAN seeming out of practice. As the game progressed, both came out within a few points of each other on completing each hundred, up to the sixth hundred, when PHELAN took a decided lead and kept it, winning the game by 60 points, out of a total of 750. In his play Mr. PHELAN showed some splendid combinations, by which he made most difficult caroms after taking four or five cushions. His ability to nurse the balls, and when they had separated, of bringing them together again was astonishing in many instances. KAVANAGH made a fine display also, in every point of the science of billiards. Thirty innings were played, averaging 25 points. PHELAN's highest runs over 40, of which there were several, were 61, 46, 75, 54, 60, 68, 51 and 58. -- Total, 750. KAVANAGH run 49, 148, 43. -- Total, 690. The prize cue will be presented to Mr. KAVANAGH at 2 o'clock to-day, by Mr. PHELAN, at his rooms, corner of Tenth-street and Broadway.

abstract: One of the latest watchwords of  revolution issued by the Secession Party, is the exclusion from the polls of colored voters; at the omission of their ballots from the count. Judges and Inspectors, who are sworn to compliance with the instructions of the Election law are exhorted to commit this snug tit-bit of Union-saving perjury. Why not?
lead_paragraph: -- One of the latest watchwords of revolution, issued by the Secession Party, is the exclusion from the polls of colored voters; or the omission of their ballots from the count. Judges and Inspectors, who are sworn to compliance with the instructions of the Election law are exhorted to commit this snug tit-bit of Union-saving perjury. Why not? Has not the United States Supreme Court decided that negroes are not citizens of the United States; and what right, we are asked, has an individual State to qualify negroes as voters, that would not extend equally to "dumb brutes" -- oxen, asses, or dogs? The only reply is, that the entire subject of the electoral franchise and its basis, has been left by the Constitution to the several States. Each State has to say who shall vote for Presidents, just as it says who shall vote for Governors, or other local officers; it is one of those reserved powers of which so much is just now heard from the other side of Mason's and Dixon's Line. Should, therefore, the extreme case of the quadrupeds be urged seriously, it would be sufficient perhaps to say, the whole matter belongs to the individual State; and, it would certainly not be for a party, who, upon a question of State rights, is actually dissolving the Union, to press the matter further. But the Constitution offers something more than negative testimony in the case. At the South these very negroes are notoriously classed with the brutes; are described by political orators and authorities as subject to the same conditions, and exposed to transfer and treatment as brute property; and yet they are permitted by the Constitution to have great and mischievous weight in the control of the Federal Government. That equality of States, so constantly appealed to, would seem, therefore, to demand, logically, that the "brutes" who are good enough to send members to Congress from the South, are good enough at the North to take part in the choice of a President -- a view that will probably be reduced to practice on Tuesday next.

Messrs. CALLICOT, DARCY; and
lead_paragraph: The contest for Assemblymen, in Kings County, acquires especial interest from the circumstance that the Democratic Party has, in three of the Districts, renominated members who last Winter distinguished themselves by their fidelity to all the profligate measures that distinguished the session. Messrs. CALLICOT, DARCY; and JONES, were found voting steadily for the gridiron abominations until they were sent to the Governor. After their return with a veto, Mr. CALLICOT was the only one of the three who had grace to abandon his needless support of the bills, and vote with Mr. FISHER, the Republican member from the County, who consistently opposed them throughout. Messrs. JONES and DARCY were more faithful to their millionaire proprietors. And whenever occasion offered for the steadfast and earnest promotion of corruption, did these three worthies coherently addict themselves to that duty, and win golden opinions, if no other, for their unfaltering consistency.

abstract: A corre-  spondent of the Norfolk Argus, sends from Austin, Texas, interesting news of the Order of the Golden Circle. He tells us the active  field operations of the band have been post- poned until after the election, at the request of "several Southern Governors;" and that
lead_paragraph: -- A correspondent of the Norfolk Argus, sends from Austin, Texas, interesting news of the Order of the Golden Circle. He tells us the active field operations of the band have been post- poned until after the election, at the request of "several Southern Governors;" and that if Mr. LINCOLN be elected, the Order will be subject to the commands of those Governors; whereas, if he be not elected, the Mexican campaign will open with "large pecuniary assistance from several of the Southern States." The services of the organization are evidently therefore to be transferred from the southwestern to the northern frontier of these States in the event of disunion. But the most striking item of intelligence refers to the Governor of Texas. The writer says: "Gen. HOUSTON, with whom Gen. BICKLEY and myself had a conference this morning, not only assured us, but he promised the people of San Antonio, last week, in a public speech, that he should again take the field and cross the Rio Grande with the largest possible force of Texans and other volunteers, if Spain made a hostile demonstration against Vera Cruz."

abstract: Ludwig Kelling, who was apprehended last Saturday on a charge of having attempted to cut the throat of Wm. Konig, a grocer in Houston-street, of whom he was jealous, escaped from the prison at Jefferson Market on Wednesday afternoon, and so far he has not been found. He availed himself of the opportunity for flight which was afforded by the engagement of the keeper in transferring prisoners from the cells to the cart provided for their conveyance to the Tombs, and it is thought that a mason named Conway, who was making repairs to the prison, aided him in escaping. Conway was arrested and committed for examination in the matter.

abstract: -- Dr. WILLIAM D. EGAN died at Chicago, Ill., on the 28th. He was born in the County of Kerry, Ireland, emigrated to this country when a very young man, and after a pedagogical career in the Canadas, in this City, and in Virginia, commenced the practice of his profession in Mississippi, in the year 1832. After brief residence there, he penetrated to Chicago, and by successful operations in real estate accumulated great wealth, which he used generously in promoting the interests of the place of his residence. Dr. Egan was elected Recorder of Cook County in 1843, which office he held for four years; in 1852 he was sent to the State Legislature from the Chicago District, and four years ago he was a prominent candidate for the nomination of Lieut.-Govemor of Illinois.

abstract: -- Even amid the excitement of the great Presidential election the New-York Courier and Enquirer preserves its refined interest in the calmer aspects of social history, and watches over the aesthetics of mankind. It has just put aside LINCOLN and Disunion for an hour, to inform us all that nothing can be more indecorous than for a Prince who has dined with a Governor to send any token of his grateful good-will to a Governor's wife. To the ordinary mind, it may not appear, in the very throes and crisis of our national affairs, to be a matter of much significance whether His Royal Highness, the Prince of Wales, did or did not send a diamond necklace to "Mrs. Governor MORGAN" of New-York. To the more enlightened Courier and Enquirer, the question appears second only in significance to the mystery of that other diamond necklace which the unlucky Cardinal Prince DE ROHAN fancied himself to be giving, once upon a time, to the Queen MARIA ANTOINETTE of France. Our polished cotemporary accordingly devotes half a column of space to show that the rash creatures who have dared to charge the heir of England with offering brilliants to the Queen-Regnant of Albany, have impugned the character of ALBERT EDWARD "as a gentleman," and proved themselves to be as ignorant of civilized propriety as so many Kaffirs. That no doubt may remain on this subject, says the Courier to the world, "a friend of ours once dined with the Queen," and coming away thankful for his dinner and his wines, never dreamt of sending the Queen so much as a blue glass breastpin. This settles the controversy. Of course no Prince could ever think of doing what was not done by a "friend of the Courier and Enquirer." The circumstances are so exactly parallel that there can he no doubt of the "right thing" in each case. One only cloud, therefore, now rests over this brilliant vision of Editors, Princes, Queens, dinners and diamonds. It is the heartrending thought that we are left to the cruel mercy of conjecture in respect to the name of the "friend who once dined" with her most gracious Majesty of Great Britain. What can it possibly be?

abstract: The efforts of Southern politicians to coerce the judgment of Northern men by threats of dissolving the Union, and the subsequent  passage of non-intercourse resolutions, in case the Republican Party should be successful at the polls next Tuesday, must certainly be
lead_paragraph: The efforts of Southern politicians to co-erce the judgment of Northern men by threats of dissolving the Union, and the subsequent passage of non-intercourse resolutions, in case the Republican Party should be successful at the polls next Tuesday, must certainly be based on very false and degrading estimates of the manhood and morals which have control of public action in the Free States. For only too much of the contempt in which it is held by Southern leaders, the North has to blame its own previous and most pernicious folly in the selection of unworthy representatives. We have invited the contempt of the South for years by sending politicians of the invertebrate class to represent us at Washington -- men who had not moral courage enough to stand up in the dignity of their constituencies and speak out the honest sentiments of those who sent them. It is for these offences -- in great part the sins of our fathers -- that we, their children, are now compelled to endure the daily insult of secession threats. This is our appointed penance for so long having allowed a class of supple and time-serving place-hunters to misrepresent our opinions and cast suspicions on our manhood, in both Houses of Congress, and all the other branches of public life having access to the Southern ear.

lead_paragraph: On Monday night the grocery and liquor store No. 238 Division-street was burned down, and certain circumstances in connection with the occurrence led to the arrest of SIMON KATZ, owner of the premises, his nephew, LOUIS KATZ, a boy of sixteen, and a young man named JACOB DAVID, on suspicion of having set the place on fire, Mr. A.E. BAKER, the Fire Marshal, has since been investigating the case, and the lad KATZ yesterday made a full confession of the guilt of himself and uncle, but exonerated the prisoner DAVID of participation in the offence. From this evidence a charge of arson in the highest degree will probably result, as the crime was committed when a family named DALTON were asleep in the rooms directly over the store, and Mrs. DALTON was almost suffocated before she escaped from the building. abstract: A terrible accident has just occurred here. The boiler of the factory of DAW & BROTHERS, makers of the wood-works of carriages, exploded, tearing away a portion of the building and badly injuring several persons. One, a boy, named JOHN KANE, will die from a fracture of the skull. Two others, G.G. BALDWIN and GEORGE DEWOLF, were badly scalded. Another boy, named JOHNSON, was badly injured. Another boy, named RICE, is supposed to be buried under the ruins. The cause of the explosion is unknown. The canal and railroad track are covered with the ruins.

The denizens of Wallstreet and vicinity; yesterday afternoon, were the victims of a hoax which, if the number of those taken in is a fair index, was one of the greatest magnitude. About noon small squads of people were seen collecting about Trinity Church and looking at the spire to discover the whereabouts of an eagle which it was said, was perched on a projection near the dial.
lead_paragraph: THE EAGLE HOAX. The denizens of Wallstreet and vicinity; yesterday afternoon, were the victims of a hoax which, if the number of those taken in is a fair index, was one of the greatest magnitude. About noon small squads of people were seen collecting about Trinity Church and looking at the spire to discover the whereabouts of an eagle which it was said, was perched on a projection near the dial. The crowds increased constantly for two or three hours, and at 3 1/2 o'clock in the afternoon, quite a number were still looking for the bird. Some said it was an eagle, others an owl, all agreed it was a wonderful bird of some kind. Thousands of people saw it, and no doubt many a family circle was interested last evening by the recital of the wonderful sight. But if another examination is made this morning it will be found that the only material from which the audacious biped was manufactured was an architectural ornament and an excited imagination.

abstract: The vexed and veteran question of the Postoffice seems on the verge of settlement. The deeds and vouchers of title of the Dutch Church property have passed the scrutiny of the Attorney-General, and been found in all respects valid; and, but for the additional formality exacted by the act of Congress, that the transfer be sanctioned by the State Legislature, there is nothing to prevent the immediate preparations for building.
lead_paragraph: The vexed and veteran question of the Postoffice seems on the verge of settlement. The deeds and vouchers of title of the Dutch Church property have passed the scrutiny of the Attorney-General, and been found in all respects valid; and, but for the additional formality exacted by the act of Congress, that the transfer be sanctioned by the State Legislature, there is nothing to prevent the immediate preparations for building. Perhaps, indeed, this Legislative assent will be regarded as so much a matter of course, that operations will be commenced in anticipation of it. If so, it is quite time that the public should have information upon two or three points of direct bearing upon the general interest and convenience; and in regard to which the authorities in charge of the business are thought to be unduly taciturn. For it may not be too violent a stretch of Democratic doctrine, to consider public opinion as a very safe judge of what is best adapted to popular wants, and what is really promotive of popular convenience: a position submitted with more than ordinary diffidence in the present case, seeing that in the choice of a site, the idea of respecting the wishes of Democratic majorities has been superciliously disregarded; and the office is to be permanently placed where nine-tenths of the community do not want it. With so marked a proof that the masses are deemed by these parties incapable of exerting a sound discretion in matters relating to themselves, it may be, in fact, impertinent to propound one or two inquiries, such as these:

abstract: The project of Alderman PLATT has come to an untimely end. Having passed the august assembly which that gentleman illustrates, it had an equally speedy transit through the Board of Councilmen, and only needed the assent of the executive officer of the county, Sheriff KELLY, to become a week's law of the town.
lead_paragraph: The project of Alderman PLATT has come to an untimely end. Having passed the august assembly which that gentleman illustrates, it had an equally speedy transit through the Board of Councilmen, and only needed the assent of the executive officer of the county, Sheriff KELLY, to become a week's law of the town. But Sheriff KELLY declines the office tendered him, and vetoes the measure. It might have been a snug thing and a pleasant to have obliged ten or twelve thousand muscular friends by paying them five dollars each for doing, and authorizing them to do, what would otherwise have been unrewarded and illegal, namely, the punching of innumerable Republican heads, the terrifying of timid Republican voters, and the triumphant defeat of the Wide-Awakes. But the Sheriff has looked up the statutes, and found that his posse can only be mustered in the presence of actual riot or insurrection; in short, that he has no warrant for levying war in time of peace; and that the shoulder-hitters would be as completely unsheltered by the forms of law, if deputized by him, as if they entered the conflict without such authentication. So they are left to the latter alternative, with its beggarly pay.

abstract: It has usually been the custom on the evening of election day, for citizens who have found it impossible to get standing-room at the newspaper offices, to congregate at Police Head-quarters in hopes of learning the result of the canvass, but as no measures have heretofore been taken for the collection of the returns on the part of the Police authorities, the information obtained from this source has not been very satisfactory. For the advantage of the public in this respect a plan has recently been devised for promptly obtaining the result of the canvass of each ticket, and the information will be transmitted from each Station-house by telegraph to the Central Office, whence the intelligence will be disseminated to all parts of the City. A general order in reference to the matter, the substance of which is as follows, was yesterday issued by Superintendent KENNEDY: The police telegraph instruments, after sundown of Nov. 6, inst., will be used exclusively in transmitting election returns, making exceptions only in case of the occurrence of any serious disturbance requiring aid, giving the locality of a fire, and informing of the detention of lost children. No communication must be made from one Station-house to another during the period of the transmission of the returns, unless by order from the Central Office. The captains are ordered so to dispose the members of their command as to insure the transmission of the result of the canvass of each ticket at the various election districts in each precinct to the several Station-houses, whence the information is to be sent immediately to the Central Office. No questions, however, relative to the progress of the canvass will be answered at the Central office, but as soon as the canvass of each ticket is completed the result will be telegraphed by general alarm to each Station-house for the convenience of citizens residing in the vicinity. One sergeant will be specially detailed to operate the telegraph instrument at each Station-house from sunset to 12 o'clock P.M., when he will be relieved by another, who will continue the duty until the canvass shall have been finished.

SEWARD, at Palace Garden, last evening, was listened to by as many thousands as could get within sound of his voice, while innumerable thousands of Republicans in different parts of the grounds, unable to get within ear-shot of him, were listening to other orators, who addressed them from platforms erected in the open sir. lead_paragraph: The address of Hon. WM.H. SEWARD, at Palace Garden, last evening, was listened to by as many thousands as could get within sound of his voice, while innumerable thousands of Republicans in different parts of the grounds, unable to get within ear-shot of him, were listening to other orators, who addressed them from platforms erected in the open sir. Mr. SEWARD, when he presented himself in the hall, was received with the most enthusiastic demonstrations. He spoke for an hour and a half, presenting with remarkable succinctness the issues of the day. He commented upon the prosperity of New-York City and the Free States as compared with that of New-Orleans and the Slave States; ascribed it to the influence of free Institutions; gave his reasons for asserting that the Republican Party stands precisely where the Fathers of the Republic stood; and declared that it was his belief that the threats of a dissolution of the Union would cease when LINCOLN was elected. After the speech Republican songs were sung, and the meeting adjourned. During the evening the Wide-Awakes paraded in great force, looking exceedingly well.

abstract: That was a happy thought of Mr. BOTTS when he denounced the idea of the South deserting the Union on account of the election of Mr. LINCOLN, as "base, cowardly and unmanly." It is to run away, he says, "not only before we are whipped, but before we are even struck a blow." The Government of the Union owns.
lead_paragraph: That was a happy thought of Mr. BOTTS when he denounced the idea of the South deserting the Union on account of the election of Mr. LINCOLN, as "base, cowardly and unmanly." It is to run away, he says, "not only before we are whipped, but before we are even struck a blow." The Government of the Union owns hundreds of millions of public lands, to say nothing of the millions which have been invested in the public buildings at Washington, in the naval ships, in the forts and arsenals, and in the Custom-houses and Post-offices. The people of the several States are joint tenants of this vast property; and the proposition of the disunionists is for the South to abandon it all, to turn it all over to the States which adhere to the Union, from sheer cowardice -- from the apprehension that the Republican President may, in the face of his pledges, invade Southern rights.

abstract: Such an exuberance of enthusiasm as welcomed Mr. SEWARD at Palace Garden last evening has rarely, if ever, been equaled by the reception of any public man in this City. The large hall was densely crowded at least half an hour before the time announced for the meeting to commence; and, when me assemblage was called to order -- like the crush at Queen Katharine's coronation -- there was hardly room to wedge, in another finger. Seats were ignored as the pressure from the rear and the sides increased, until the undulating surface of sweltering heads resembled a vast measure crammed with well-ripened fruit. abstract: On Thursday evening the two Boards of Aldermen and Councilmen concurred in a resolution authorizing the Sheriff to appoint as many Special Deputies as he should think proper to protect the rights of voters at the polls. Sheriff KELLY, however, by advice of his Counsel will not appoint any Special Deputies for any such purpose. The amendment to the Metropolitan Police act passed this year deprived him of all power to make deputies, except in case of insurrection or rebellion, that power being devolved upon the Commissioners of Police. Mayor WOOD has not yet signed the aforesaid resolution, but will give it his mature consideration.

abstract: It will please our readers to know that the health of Rev. JOSEPH SCUDDER is so far restored as to enable him to preach once more with something of his usual power. A service of about eight years in India, under an unfavorable climate, rendered his return to the United States necessary.
lead_paragraph: It will please our readers to know that the health of Rev. JOSEPH SCUDDER is so far restored as to enable him to preach once more with something of his usual power. A service of about eight years in India, under an unfavorable climate, rendered his return to the United States necessary. He remained in Englandand France three months, where he consulted high medical authorities respecting the nature and treatment of his disorder. At present he is staying at West Farms, Westchester County, where, with judicious care, we trust his energies will be recruited. He is to preach next Sabbath in Dr. ELMENDORF's church, Brooklyn. If earnestness of manner, and power in delineating with graphic fervor the theme of discourse, are desirable in a preacher, then will it be easily confessed that in these particulars few preachers equal Mr. SCUDDER. -- Christian Intelligencer, Nov. 1.

abstract: Brooklyn experienced a novel sensation last evening -- produced by an unusual display of the Wide-Awakes. Accustomed as her people have been to the parade of small bands of these auxiliary political organizations, they were nevertheless taken by surprise, and more than gratified at the success which attended this effort, and they made a full night of it. The procession was organized by the Grand Marshal, Col. JESSE C. SMITH, on Fourth and Grand streets, at about 8 o'clock, and arrived at its destination probably at about 3 o'clock; this morning. If its size should be judged by the same rule used by the Express in estimating the fusion procession of Thursday evening, there must have been at least 25,000 men in line. Persons at different points, however, were able to count from 1,900 to 2,500, and every man was in full uniform. Marching in pretty close order, frequently presenting a front of 18 files, the time occupied in passing a given point was 20 minutes. The windows of public and private buildings, notwithstanding the unseasonable hour, everywhere on the route of the procession, and the sidewalks on either side, were filled with people, and many houses were brilliantly illuminated. One of the most prominent of these was the house of Mr. CROWLEY, on Bedford-avenue. The Wide-Awakes were in the best of spirits, and were everywhere most heartily welcomed, the sterner sex manifesting their good will by frequently cheering, and the softer sex expressing their sentiments by waving their handkerchiefs. The line was interspersed with transparencies, principally illuminating the names of the different candidates for office, American flags, several banners, -- but there were none of the least objectionable character. There were twenty-three clubs in all, and their excellent bearing was the theme of all observers, and would have reflected credit even upon a regular military organization.

abstract: The Herald for Disunion.  The Herald of Wednesday has a strong article in favor of the secession of the Southern States, in the event of Mr. LINCOLN'S election. The treasonable manifesto of the Herald is founded on the text furnished by the census of Delaware.
lead_paragraph: We learn through a private channel that the attempt to raise a Company of "Minute Men" at Richmond, Va.,) originated in .a quarter which, so far from entitling the movement to respect, has brought it into general contempt. A friend writes us that "All sensible men are quietly laughing at the matter. Virginia is prepared unanimously to resist any invasion of her rights, but her people are not disposed to organize an armed resistance to men of straw, that every popinjay politician or disappointed demagogue may set up as a target. The present movement is in reality too contemptible, when its origin is known, for notice; but before this reaches you its author may telegraph to the Herald that Virginia is arming for resistance. In fact, some ambitious tailor has ornamented his windows with the terrible South Carolina cockade; and the trio of traitors of the New-York Press will no doubt soon announce this fact with all the alarming portents of capitals. The most burning disgrace that, in my opinion, can now be inflicted on the State of New-York, would be the election of the Fusion ticket, based as if is upon the assumed cowardice and corruptibility of the people."

abstract: On Saturday night, soon after the withdrawal of JOHN C. MATHER, the Tammany Hall candidate for Congress in the Third Congressional District, the Tammany Convention met and nominated Mr. JOHN Y. SAVAGE. Mr. SAVAGE has long been a prominent member of the Tammany branch of the Democracy of this City, and is popular with Tammany men. He was a delegate to the Charleston and Baltimore Democratic National Convention, in both of which he was an ardent supporter of Senator DOUGLAS. He is by trade, a jeweler and watchmaker, and does business in Greenwich-street.

abstract: -- There is one artist in New-York preeminently deserving patronage, who has given us some of the finest cast caricatures of the day, but who does not meet from the public that recognition which is so universally extended him by his brother artists and the art-world generally. We refer to ROGERS, and we are led to this remark by the view of his first ideal work, entitled "The Fairy Whisper." A boy has thrown himself on a bank of flowers, with all the graceful abandon of childhood. The softest of breezes seems to blow the hair from his young brow, and to undulate almost imperceptibly through the flowers around. A fairy, one of those mystic messengers of the flower nature, is whispering some sweet dream to his child heart. The flowers he just plucked are falling from his dimpled fingers, and, with eager parted lips, he listens to the wonderful voice of nature -- his soul entirely absorbed -- every faculty concentrated into expectation. This is excellently expressed in his earnest face, whose expression, radiant with all the intensity of a rare poetic intelligence, still remains exquisitely childlike. A subscription list has been opened for the sale of this work at the Crayon Gallery.

lead_paragraph: The leaders of the Democracy believe, or affect to believe, that the triumph of the Republican Party in the elections of to-morrow will be followed by the dissolution of the American Union. They accordingly charge it upon the Republicans that they, and only they, are to be held responsible for this fearful and imminent catastrophe. Like the timid Lord Mayor of London in the time of the Gordon riots, who complained to the affrighted Catholics that "if they would only have been Protestants the mob wouldn't have burnt their houses," these excellent patriots profess that if the Republican Party would only have ceased to be Republican the Union would be safe.

abstract: The Albany papers detail the particulars of a shooting affray which transpired in that city on Friday last, and which resulted in JOHN PERCY, a lawyer, being fatally wounded by a pistol in the hands of JOHN CHANFIELD, who keeps a porter-house and oyster-saloon at No. 833 Broadway, between North Lansing and DeWitt streets.
lead_paragraph: The Albany papers detail the particulars of a shooting affray which transpired in that city on Friday last, and which resulted in JOHN PERCY, a lawyer, being fatally wounded by a pistol in the hands of JOHN CHANFIELD, who keeps a porter-house and oyster-saloon at No. 833 Broadway, between North Lansing and DeWitt streets. Law-suits, in which these two parties had been engaged -- PERCY as counsel for others -- terminated adversely to CRANFIELD, and he had been ejected from his saloon several times in accordance with a writ of execution which had been obtained against him, but succeeded each time in again obtaining possession. PERCY found him there on Friday morning, notwithstanding he had put him out only the night previous, and nailed up the door. The following ante-mortem deposition by PERCY, who was accompanied to the saloon by JAMES HARRIS, his brother-in-law, details the circumstances of this visit:

abstract: "South-street," who keeps a bulletin of the movements of slavers, and reports them through the Evening Post, gives the following statements: The Louisa, (reported heretofore as having gone on a slave cruise,) has returned from St. Jago de Cuba, and will probably fit out directly from this port. The Erie, Weather Guage, Kate, J.J. Cobb and Thomas Achorn are all in custody of the United States authorities. At Norfolk, Va., there are the Triton and Storm King under seizure. The Falmouth has sailed for Havana, after "changing hands" in the customary way. The Kate's party, it is hinted, know all about the Falmouth. The Cygnet and William are still at Mobile. Capt. BOWEN, who landed 1,300 slaves from the Sultana, reported to have been the Mohawk, has managed to get out of this port as master and part owner of the ship Nightengale. The other owner is a Portuguese merchant, doing business in this City. The vessel has since arrived at Liverpool, (a roundabout way to the Coast of Africa,) and if she takes a cargo, she will carry 2,000 slaves to Cuba. A small brig, formerly schooner rigged, lately sailed from a Southern port for the Coast and a slave cargo. The slaver Wanderer cleared from Havana on the 1st of October, but on the 27th still remained at that port. The City of Norfolk, steamer, has been towed into Havana; the brig Nancy has sailed from the same port for a cargo; the Ardennes was still there, and the schooner Byron, captured by a Spanish war-steamer, was carried in there, having 371 souls on board. The slaver Lyon, owned by a Spaniard in New-York, has been sold there. Cuban partion have ordered a propeller from New-York to undertake the same enterprise in which the City of Norfolk so nearly succeeded. The proclamation of the Captain-General of Cuba is pronounced a "stool pigeon affair."

abstract: Senator SEWARD, in his speech on Friday night, declared the whole aim and duty of the Republican Party to be, to leave Slavery just where it is. They do not seek to abolish or disturb it; but they do propose to prevent its extension or increase.
lead_paragraph: Senator SEWARD, in his speech on Friday night, declared the whole aim and duty of the Republican Party to be, to leave Slavery just where it is. They do not seek to abolish or disturb it; but they do propose to prevent its extension or increase. It is not easy to see what objection any rational man can make to such a policy. The whole disturbance which prevails through the country has been caused by the efforts of the South to increase Slavery. They have pursued this policy steadily for some years past, covering its purpose by charging its opponents with designing to interfere with it where it now exists.

abstract: The Southern Illinois (M.E.) Conference was lately in session at Bunker Hill, Illinois. During one of the meetings, the hanging of Rev. Mr. BEWLEY, by a Pro-Slavery mob in Texas, was announced. A series of resolutions was adopted denouncing the outrage in the most foreible terms. Besides this, the Committee on Slavery reported a series of resolutions.
lead_paragraph: The Southern Illinois (M.E.) Conference was lately in session at Bunker Hill, Illinois. During one of the meetings, the hanging of Rev. Mr. BEWLEY, by a Pro-Slavery mob in Texas, was announced. A series of resolutions was adopted denouncing the outrage in the most foreible terms. Besides this, the Committee on Slavery reported a series of resolutions rejoicing in the fact that, from the commencement of its existence, the Methodist Church had occupied decidedly Anti-Slavery ground; avowing a determination to refrain from participation in all opposition to Slavery which is not of a peaceful and legal character, and soliciting the friends of Methodism everywhere "to frown upon all attempts for the forcible dissolution of the relation of master and slave, which, by the sanction of municipal law, exists in the Slaveholding States of this Confederacy;" affirming the right of the "brethren everywhere, freely and peacefully, to discuss the evils of Slavery; and insisting that such discussion cannot, under any circumstances whatever, constitute the least infringement upon the natural or vested rights of any portion of the citizens of our country."

abstract: Having carefully examined the whole ground, we feel safe in stating that the vote which will be polled to-morrow, in favor of LINCOLN and HAMLIN, will astonish all those who have relied upon previous computations of Democratic strength. We believe that the Republicans will poll for their general ticket not less than thirty-five thousand votes, while the Democrats and Fusion men will fall somewhat short of fifty-five thousand. This calculation is based on a careful estimate of the names polled on the Registry books, and the number of polling-places in this City.

lead_paragraph: By the steamship Prince Albert, whose arrival at St. Johns is elsewhere announced, we receive two days later advices from Europe. They are not of an important character. The meeting at War- saw of the Emperors of Austria and Russia and the Prince Regent of Prussia had taken place, but nothing had transpired as to the Conferences. It is said that the title of Prince and the rank of General would be offered by VICTOR EMANUEL to GARIBALDI. The text of the Prussia dispatch relative to the invasion of the Papal States by Sardinia has been published. It refuses to accept Count DE CAVOUR's justification.

abstract: DESTRUCTION OF A PAPER MILL BY FIRE. At about 5 o'clock on Saturday evening, and while the storm was at its height, a fire broke out in the buildings occupied by Messrs. HAMILTON  DONNELSON, at the corner of Carroll and Nevins streets, and the entire establishment, including buildings, machinery and stock were destroyed.
lead_paragraph: DESTRUCTION OF A PAPER MILL BY FIRE. At about 5 o'clock on Saturday evening, and while the storm was at its height, a fire broke out in the buildings occupied by Messrs. HAMILTON DONNELSON, at the corner of Carroll and Nevins streets, and the entire establishment, including buildings, machinery and stock were destroyed. The buildings occupied by this Company were three in number, all constructed with wood. One was 30 by 50 feet, three stories high; another was 30 by 100 feet, 25 feet high, and the third was 30 by 40 feet, 25 feet high. The total loss is estimated at $55,000, which amount is covered by insurance in different New-York and Brooklyn offices. The fire is said to have been caused by spontaneous combustion. The firemen turned out with their accustomed promptness, and were able to prevent the fire from spreading to adjoining property.

abstract: Plymouth Church was, at an early hour last evening, crowded, packed and filled to overflowing with people, drawn by the various motives of worship, curiosity or habit. The church is always well filled; but the audience last evening exceeded any we hate ever before witnessed in that or any other temple of the Lord.
lead_paragraph: Plymouth Church was, at an early hour last evening, crowded, packed and filled to overflowing with people, drawn by the various motives of worship, curiosity or habit. The church is always well filled; but the audience last evening exceeded any we hate ever before witnessed in that or any other temple of the Lord. Far out upon the sidewalk, blocking up the passage, and attracting continual additions was a pushing, wriggling, tip-toeing crush of humanity vainly endeavoring to gain admittance within the already repleted building, while the outside supports of the windows and the several side entrances to the church were impenetrably lined with eager gazers, who, though they could not hear a word, were, at least, better off than their neighbors who could neither hear nor see.

lead_paragraph: -EZRA BRAINERD was hung at Three Rivers, C.W., on the 25th inst., for having murdered his mother some months since. Since his conviction strong efforts have been made to have him pardoned on the ground of insanity, and wretched dogerel which he has had published in a paper at Three Rivers would seem to indicate that he was far from being in his right mind. A correspondent of the Montreal Gazette sketches the closing scene of Ms life. He writes: "Shortly before 11 o'clock a door leading to the convict's cell was closed and the hangman proceeded to pinion his victim in the dimly-lighted dungeon, screened by the closed door from the looks of the people in the jail hall. The constables who accompanied him state that while being pinioned BRAINERD requested Sheriff OGDEN to convey his body after execution to Melbourne in the Townships for burial, and that the twenty dollars in gold among his effects be appropriated for the purpose. The Sheriff promised to comply with his request. He also said to the hangman, "You are pinching me, you are beginning to murder me too soon." The convict pinioned, a rope was placed round his waist and the party led by the Sheriff proceeded up the two flights of stairs to the room leading to the drop. BRAINERD walked up the steps coolly and more unconcernedly than any of the spectators. In the room the executioner took his hand off BRAINERD's neck and drew back the bolts of the door, outside which was the drop. As he did so the crowd, which now amounted to about 2,000, and in which many women were to be seen, simultaneously exclaimed, "Le voila, le voila," and swayed to and fro for a few moments, eagerly looking up at BRAINERD, who stood calmly gazing out into the rain. The hangman stepped out on the drop and pulled down the noose, Rev. Mr. CARON said, "BRAINERD, humble yourself, repent; in ten minutes you will be no more, and facing your Creator." Words to this effect he repeated twice, but still BRAINERD made no sign, and looked down at the crowd. Precisely at 11, the preparations completed, BRAINERD was led out on the drop, and the executioner placed the noose around his neck, having previously partly drawn the black cap down over his face and removed his hat. BRAINERD saying that the wind would blow it off. He stood facing cast, and exclaimed, in low tones, to the people outside, "Strangers, they are going to commit murder. I am innocent."

abstract: A chess match has been arranged between the York and Brooklyn Clubs, and instead of the customary consultation games, the contest will be carried on in the following manner. lead_paragraph: FALCONER THE STREET PREACHER AGAIN. EDWARD FALCONER, the temperance lecturer and open air preacher, who has been apprehended almost every Sabbath during the past six months, for violating the City ordinance which prohibits street preaching with- out a license, as usual fell into the hands of the police yesterday. He was taken before Justice WELSH, at the Tombs, where a charge was preferred against him, the complainant being one of the officers of the Broadway Squad, who stated that he had found the prisoner addressing a crowd in the City Hall Park. The magistrate said that the offence which FALCONER had committed was merely a misdemeanor, for which it was illegal to make an arrest on Sunday. He therefore discharged the accused, and told the policeman that he could obtain a warrant for his rearrest on the same charge any week day that he might choose to ask for it.

abstract: The divisions among the Anti-Republicans of the Eighth Congressional District having been settled by the withdrawal of the rival candidates, and the nomination of ISAAC C. DELAPLAINE to represent the Dis trict in the next Congress, a meeting was held on Saturday evening, at the corner of Broadway and Thirtysecond-street, to ratify the nomination.
lead_paragraph: The divisions among the Anti-Republicans of the Eighth Congressional District having been settled by the withdrawal of the rival candidates, and the nomination of ISAAC C. DELAPLAINE to represent the Dis trict in the next Congress, a meeting was held on Saturday evening, at the corner of Broadway and Thirtysecond-street, to ratify the nomination. It was designed to hold the meeting in the open air, and a stand had been erected in the above locality for that purpose, but owing to the violent rain the meeting was held in a hall near by, where it was organized by the election of BRADISH JOHNSON, Esq., as President, and a number of Vice-Presidents from each of the Wards comprised in the District. Mr. JOHNSON, on taking the Chair, said that he was born in Louisiana, but he stood there as a national man, knowing no North, no South, but only the whole country, one and indivisible. The South had always stood by the Union, and he believed she would stand by it now, but it must be such a Union as our fathers framed, with all its guarantees and conditions; a Union founded on the equal rights of all the sovereign States, and not a Union dependent upon the caprice of a sectional majority. After alluding, in glowing terms, to the brotherly feeling that animated the North and South during the Revolution, and to the common hardships, dangers and trials through which they passed in that struggle for independence, he expected his hearers to preserve intact that glorious Union, cemented by the blood of their fathers, and to transmit unimpaired, to their descendants, the precious legacy bequeathed to them. This could only be done by acting justly towards the whole country, and by honorably carrying out the terms and the spirit of the compact entered into by the Fathers of the Republic.

abstract: The undersigned believing that the election of LINCOLN is the only means of preventing the transference of the present contest for the Presidency to the Halls of Congress, where it would be certain to renew, in an intensified form, the disgraceful and threatening scenes of last Winter, and thus subject our Government to more fearful peril than any it has hitherto encountered; and believing that the unscrupulous efforts now making by leading partis ans of the present Administration and their organs to affect the popular vote by threats and other appliances, calculated to destroy confidence, paralyze business and depreciate the value of property, deserve the indignant rebuke of every good citizen, cordially invite merchants and all others entertaining similar views, to meet on the steps of the Merchants' Exchange, this Monday afternoon, at 3 o'clock, to join in the public expression of their sentiments.

lead_paragraph: The curtain fell on Friday evening on the short but profitable season of Mr. FORMES, and on Monday, the 12th, the little ULLMAN, like a giant refreshed by sleep, and all that style of thing, assumes, once more, command. This time an undivided command, Mr. STRAKOSCH having entirely severed his connection with the Academy. Mr. ULLMAN will open under the most brilliant auspices. Mr. STRAKOSCH and Miss PATTI are about to join the MUZIO-COLSON forces in the West. M. MARETZEK has abandoned his idea of a musical invasion of Mexico, and will conduct the orchestra under Mr. ULLMAN. Messrs. JOEL and LEVI have retired from operatic engineering, and are about to proceed to Havana on a jewelry excursion. Their secession has thrown over the Academy a momentary gloom. Mr. JACOBSON confines himself for a time to the management of a large and costly wardrobe.

abstract: The Fusion ratification meeting of the Seventh Congressional District, at Pvthagorus Hall, on Saturday evening, did not proceed as those who called it had anticipated. Quite a number of those who were present seemed very much dissatisfied with the nomination of Hon. ELIJAH WARD, and during the whole evening expressed their dissatisfaction by continual cries for Mr. LATSON, who was not present. At about 9 o'clock, and after the cries had been increasing in number and vehemence, Mr. LATSON was actually carried from his house in West Twenty-seventh-street, to the hall, where he was received with tremendous cheers. His name was immediately substituted for that of Mr. WARD by the majority, and he was declared the Union candidate for the Seventh District, amid a perfect storm of applause, and the meeting adjourned. As soon as the adjournment had been declared, Mr. LATSON was carried from the room upon the shoulders of his friends. Mr. LATSON was placed in nomination by the "Minute Men" about six weeks ago.
