abstract: In the Richmond papers appears a notification that two large bodies of troops, constituting a portion of the force which Virginia contributes to the cause of the South, are to muster in serviceable order in the public parade-ground in that city, on the seventh day of November; and we are pointed to the presumption that they would not thus early be placed in marching order if they were not to be thus early wanted. On Wednesday, therefore, we may safely imagine the entire military arm of secession to be nerved and outstretched for action. Ex-Gov. WISE, with dashing uniform and the blue cockade, may be conceived of as mounting his charger to head those columns of Minute-men whom he has bidden to the conflict, and LUCIUS JUNIUS BRUTUS PEYOR may be depicted at a convenient grindstone in the act of bringing to a keener edge the dagger which is to pierce the breast of Mr. LINCOLN, and give peace to the country. What ragged regiments shall pour into Charleston, and what brilliant marches and counter-marches across the country shall be executed by the barbarian legions of the back country of North Carolina, are only to be preconceived by reference to those great popular uprisings in other times, when indignant races have risen in revolt against oppression, and called the very arriere-ban of the nation to arms. And all this we are to witness by the middle of the week.

abstract: Arnoux vs. Phelan. -- BOSWORTH, J. -- (Same Court.) -- Where the Court appoints a stenographie reporter, under Sec. 250 of the Code, as amended by Chap. 459 of the laws of 1860, and orders the expense thereof to be paid the parties equally, the prevailing party cannot tax the money thus paid as a disbursement. The Code by requiring this expense to be paid by the parties absolutely, without any provision that either may reclaim; in any event, the sum paid, disposes of the question by whom the expense is to be borne. The object of inclining it is not the relief of the Court alone. The parties are benefited, not only by a saving of time at the trial, but by a saving of labor and expense in the preparation of a case or exceptions, and amendments thereto, if either moves for a new trial. Arnoux vs. Callendor, the same decision is made.

abstract: We are likely to need larger jails. The vigi- lance of our Republican Wide-Awakes is dragging to light hundreds of cases in which votes have been falsely registered. Our police reports mention some arrests already on this ground; but in most cases those who have been "spotted" will be allowed to
lead_paragraph: We are likely to need larger jails. The vigi- lance of our Republican Wide-Awakes is dragging to light hundreds of cases in which votes have been falsely registered. Our police reports mention some arrests already on this ground; but in most cases those who have been "spotted" will be allowed to attempt the consummation of their crime and thus make the evidence of their guilt clear and unmistakable. It is not so generally known as it should be that the legal penalty for falsely registering a vote is a year's imprisonment in the Penitentiary. And with our present Police arrangements, and the active vigilance of the Wide-Awakes, who have taken in hand the special duty of watching the polls, there is scarcely one chance in ten of escaping detection and punishment.

abstract: A warrant was issued yesterday by Justice QUACKENBUSH for the arrest of GEORGE K. COOKE, the Democratic member of the Board of Registry for the Eighth District of the Fifteenth Ward, on a charge of having violated the Registry law. An affidavit has been made to the effect that COOKE, while acting as Registrar on the 17th ult., caused his name to be placed on the list of voters for that District, giving No. 308 Bowery as his place of residence. It was subsequently ascertained, however, that he resided at No 373 Fourth-street, which is not in the Eighth District, and that he had also been to the registering-place of the Ninth District, of the same Ward, and had his name registered there. NAPOLEON B. HOBBS, a clerk for LORD & TAYLOR, is also charged with an offence similar to the one of which COOK is accused. On the 30th inst. he caused his name to be registered as a legal voter in the Eighth District of the Fifteenth Ward, and went off boasting that he should vote for "The Union, the Constitution, and the enforcement of the laws." As, however, he had not lived in this State one year, having come here from Baltimore, Md., in March last, he was unqualified for voting at all, and his arrest was effected on the ground that he had willfully violated the law. Justice QUACKENBUSH required him to funish bail in $500 to answer. The penalty, upon conviction of the offences charged, is not less than one year's imprisonment in the State Prison.

abstract: The prolonged and unusually mild weather of the past week terminated what was regarded as the Indian Summer on Saturday. The soft south wind which had prevailed for several days, and given to the atmosphere uncomfortable warmth and moisture, then changed to the northeast, with signs of a storm, and towards noon the wind increased to a stiff gale, accompanied with rain.
lead_paragraph: The prolonged and unusually mild weather of the past week terminated what was regarded as the Indian Summer on Saturday. The soft south wind which had prevailed for several days, and given to the atmosphere uncomfortable warmth and moisture, then changed to the northeast, with signs of a storm, and towards noon the wind increased to a stiff gale, accompanied with rain. Throughout the afternoon the City and surrounding country was deluged with the heaviest rain-fall of the season, putting an end to all out-door business, and, generally, to travel. The cars and stages furnished comparatively little accommodation, when everybody wished to ride, and multitudes without umbrellas and overshoes went home drenched by the storm. The Eastern steamers prudently remained at their respective wharves, not deeming it safe to attempt the navigation of the Sound in the teeth of so violent a gale and so dark and murky a night. The two foreign steamers which left at noon, as well as all the Southern steamers, came to anchor below, and awaited the return of better weather. At 8 1/2 o'clock P.M. the wind canted to the southeast, and, for nearly two hours blew with the force of a hurricane. Vessels at anchor on the Jersey side of the bay dragged their anchor, most of them having both anchors down and all their "scope" out.

abstract: On Saturday evening John C. Adams and Valentine Eschenfelder visited several drinking saloons, and indulged in sundry liquid tokens of friendship. About midnight, as they were walking through Fifth-street, near Avenue C. Adams suddenly drew a dirk-knife and, threatening his companion's life, seized his watch and chain and ran off. The victimized German called upon the Police in a loud voice, and the Police responded in the person of Officer Reeves, of the Eleventh Precinct, who gave chase to the robber and eventually arrested him. The prisoner was taken before Justice STEERS yesterday, the property recovered, and Adams locked up as a warning to him.

abstract: MEETING OF THE VETERAN CORPS. -- Fourteen of the veterans of the war of 1812 were in session last evening at the Star Hotel in Lispenard-street. The eve of our election, like the eve of a battle, is generally an affair of solemn moment and all-absorbing interest, but the veterans who met last night worried their heads very little with politics. The only allusion to the pending canvass was an inquiry as to the sentiments of a certain candidate for reelection to Congress upon the Pension question, and how he had voted during his previous term. The apprehended dissolution of the Union ruffled not one hair on those gray heads. Possibly they felt assured that the Union would last as long as they did, and gave themselves no trouble beyond. "After us the deluge," may have been their thought. The veterans had a more important question to settle among themselves than the fate of the Union. Secession and disunion had crept into their own ranks. Their corps was divided upon some questions of little moment, and last evening a proposition came from the other wing for a coalition. It was proposed that they unite on the 25th of this month in a parade, burying all animosities, and elect new officers for the whole corps. After some little discussion the proposition, with some modifications, was adopted, and a Committee appointed to confer with a Committee from the other wing upon the coalition. A new member was admitted to the Society upon his producing proof of having shouldered a musket in the War of 1812; and it was announced that the corps now numbered 97; several of the veterans, during the past year, having marched, with knapsacks on their shoulders, in advance of their companies, to that land where all, sooner or later, are destined to bivouac. It was mournful to think that at each successive monthly meeting the number of veterans in session would become less and less, that one by one the ripe old heads would fall like blades of corn before the ruthless reaper, until, in the course of a few years, not one would be left to tell how he crossed muskets with the Britishers in the war of 1812.

abstract: -Hundreds of Democratic officials have declared that they will never hold office under a "Black Republican" President. It will be a great relief to Mr. LINCOLN to get rid of these gentry on the easy condition of their voluntary resignation; but we greatly fear that they will put him to the unpleasant task of making them keep their promises. It is related of an honest Quaker that when a rude fellow gruffly refused his kind invitation to dine, but afterwards reconsidered the matter and wished to come to the table, Broad-brim said, "No, friend, thee shall not tell a lie in my house." Mr. LINCOLN comes of this Quaker stock, and if he has not invited the Disunionists to remain with him, he will be sure to make them keep their voluntary pledge to resign.

abstract: -- One of the causes accounting for the largely increased registration of the present year is the security afforded to voters by the organization and drill of the new police. Under the displaced system it required much the same sort of courage which impels men to seek the bubble reputation at the cannon's mouth, to incite the elector to discharge the first obligation of citizenship. An election without its affrays and riots was, in fact, a social anomaly, of which instances were not remembered. The police, sympathetic with the disorderlies, refused all efficient interference. If arrests were made, it was the abused and disappointed voter, who was carried ignominiously to prison, while the ruffian, who did the wrong and inflicted the insult, was left on the ground, to do further partisan service of the same description.

abstract: At breakfast he offered to give my mother a few hints on buying fish, adducing his own superior experience of the sea as a reason for informing her ignorance as a young housekeeper. "Above all things, Jane," said he, "as they will endeavor to impose upon your inexperience, let nothing induce you to buy a plaice that has any appearance of red or orange spots, as they are the sure sign of an advanced stage of decomposition." My mother promised faithful compliance in the innocence of her heart, and accordingly, when the fish-woman came to the door, she descended to show off her newly-acquired information. As it happened, the woman had little but plaice, and these she turned over and over praising their size and freshness. But the obnoxious spots on every one of them still greeted my mother's dissatisfied gaze. On her hinting a doubt of their freshness, she was met by the assertion that they were not long out of the water, having been caught that morning. This shook my mother's doubts for a moment, but remembering my father's portrayal of the Brighton fishwoman's iniquitous falsehoods, she gravely shook her head, and mildly observed, in all the pride of conscious knowledge, "My good woman, it may be as you say, but I could not think of buying any plaice with those very unpleasant red spots." The woman's answer was a perfect shout: "Lord bless your eyes, mum! who ever seen any without 'em?" A suppressed giggle on the stairs revealed the perpetrator of the joke, and my father rushed off in a perfect ecstacy of laughter, leaving my poor discomfited mother to appease the angry sea-nymph as she could. -- Hood's Memorials.

abstract: half an hour before the time appointed for the meeting of merchants yesterday, presented a scene of unusual bustle and excitement. Here and there men were gathered in little knots talking earnestly; about the steps of the building crowds were beginning to congregate; now and then there was a cheer, and now and then a groan, accompanied with sibillant and uncouth-noises, was echoed with a hollow sound from the [???] granite front. Daily within the same mart of trade, the loud-mouthed auctioneers make the repeating walls hideous with their announcements of the terms of sale; so, yesterday, men whose apparent design it was to break up the meeting of the merchants, gave color to the scandal, which one in crowd gave tongue to, that with their hootings the hirelings were only publishing to the world the price of their opposition to the Republican candidate.

lead_paragraph: At an early hour on saturday morning last, the citizens of Poughkeepsie were startled from their slumbers by an alarm of fire. It was discovered, between 4 and 5 o'clock, issuing from the wholesale cooperage establishment of Messrs. SLEIGHT PAULDING, at the foot of Dutchess-avenue. The fire department were soon at the spot, but by this time the flames had gained fearful headway, rendering the attempts of the firemen to extinguish the fire futile. By their efforts, however, the flames were confined to the burning buildings, which raged fiercely for nearly two hours, illuminating the country for a considerable distance around. Shortly after 6 o'clock, the whole lay a mass of blackened ruins. Nothing was saved. The loss is estimated at $12,000. In the building were some fifty or sixty boxes of tools, belonging to those employed. Some of them were worth from one hundred to one hundred and fifty dollars. A large amount of stock piled on the outside of the building also caught fire, and was consumed. There was but an insurance of between $2,000 and $3,000 upon the building, the rest being a total loss, amongst which were the tools belonging to the workmen. These, numbering about fifty, are thrown out of employment by this unfortunate occurrence. Shortly before the fire was discovered, some boatmen who were on the dock state that they saw a light in the upper part of the principal building, but that they took no further notice of it, supposing it to be one of the workmen on business. In fifteen minutes after, the flames burst forth, when the alarm was given. This fire was also he work of an incendiary. Everything was quiet when the building was closed for the night, on Friday, the fires, as usual, being carefully extinguished, and the building examined.

abstract: We are requested to state in reply to sundry rumors that have been put in circulation by interested parties, that the Breckinridge and Lane State Ticket has not been withdrawn, but that it will be run in this City and throughout the State at all hazards. It is deemed important that that section of the Democratic Party should cast as large a vote as possible, for the purpose of controlling the Democratic organization of the State hereafter. It is obvious, moreover, that if LINCOLN is not the next President Gen. LANE will be; and the dispensation of the patronage of this State will, in that event, fall entirely into the control of the Breckinridge wing of the Party.

abstract: The interest in the election at hand is earnest and warm. It is expected that LINCOLN will certainly be elected by the people, and if he is not we shall all be greatly disappointed. Many honest, well-disposed people hope that LINCOLN will be elected, in the confident belief that it will end agitation, after a week or so of bluster. Everybody dreads such an event as sending the election to the House of Representatives.

abstract: -- A correspondent  writes to the Petersburgh Express, from Pellsylvania, C.H., under date of Oct. 30: "Our Circuit Court is now in session, his Honor Judge GILMER presiding, and has just fairly commenced upon a large docket, upon which there are, all told, over five hundred cases. The Grand Jury is now in session, and is doing a big business. To-day sn indictment was found against a man named DODSON, for advising and inciting negroes in this State to rebel and make insurrection. He was examined last night, and the proof was as follows, almost verbatim: DODSON was overheard to tell negroes in their cabin at a late hour of the night, 'that the children of Israel were in greater bondage than they, (i.e. the negroes) and that they threw of the yoke of Slavery by themselves; that the negroes of St. Domingo had overpowered their masters and set themselves free, and if they (the negroes of Virginia) would only be determined and show that they were in earnest, the North would send them help; that there were 500 men in this county who would help them, and that many of the remainder would do nothing against them, and that in a short time they could all be free." Straws show how the wind blows, so I think this language, when used in the heart of Virginia, tells the tale. I wish you would hurry up ANDERSON & CO., in their armory arrangements. We want some good shooting irons.

abstract: -- The inevitable exhortation to voters may, for once, be spared. Before this issue of the TIMES reaches its readers, multitudes of them will have accomplished their great civic duty, and be quietly enjoying the consciousness of a day well spent. But even to those whom we address earlier in the day, and before they have paid their yearly tribute to the Constitution and the country, it would be wholly superfluous to appeal with the usual commonplaces which are supposed to affect the conscience of the most obdurate elector. There is in the occasion itself every argument for action. The positions assumed by the two great parties who divide the people, are such as to compel each individual to the exercise of his decisive right. Thus the fusion combination bases its very existence upon the averment that the Union is in danger; and that so great is the hazard, and so close the contest, no citizen can decline to vote without incurring the responsibility of that calamity. The Republican Party, on the other hand, asserts this to be the critical and final struggle which is to decide whether Slavery shall be indefinitely increased and Slavery become a national institution, of whether the just balance and equilibrium of the Government shall be restored. It also, with great reason, predicts far graver danger to the Republic in case LINCOLN is not elected to-day, and the contest be transferred to Congress, than if by the universal energy of Republicans that alternative be avoided. Never before have the people been solicited by such urgent inducements to the fulfillment of a simple obligation. The stimulus acts equally upon partisans of all sorts, and may be trusted to act effectually.

abstract: -- Of the recent  failures in Baltimore, the Patriot of Saturday says: 'We learn that Messrs. JOSIAH LEE & CO., (GERARD and GEO. P. GOVER,) whose suspension was recently announced, have executed an assignment to STEVENSON ARCHER, Attorney, of Harford County, all of their property, which consists of debts due the firm, a considerable landed estate in Harford County, and all their personal property in said county. The terms of the assignment are that the partnership property shall first be devoted to the payment of partnership debts; their individual property to pay individual debts, and after the payment of individual debts, balance of the individual property to pay partnership debts. It is the impression, from our best sources of information, that the condition of the partnership will not realize more than 15 cents in the dollar. Deed of assignment will be recorded in Hartford county, and the estate settled in the Court of that county.

abstract: -- The panic manufacturers withdrew from business too soon. Yesterday, notwithstanding the imminence of election day, and consequently of that crisis which was to plunge the country in irremediable ruin, the Stock market insisted upon recovering its tone; the bank returns assumed a more cheerful and encouraging aspect; in short, the reaction from the abnormal and factitious action of the last four weeks fairly set in. It is to be lamented that so much damaging industry should have been spoiled for the want of a very little final perseverance. One day more would have sufficed to satisfy the world that while these panic rumors were quite baseless, they were not wholly without existence in the breasts of those who uttered them. As it is, we see that both the financial and the political world agree in thinking that ABRAHAM LINCOLN may be made President without dissolving the Union.

abstract: -- We are likely to have some very disgraceful results in our Judicial elections to-day. Candidates are in nomination for the Bench who would much more appropriately take the place of criminals; and as rigid party discipline seems to be the order of the day, there is great danger that some of them may be elected. We should very gladly have seen and aided some movement, irrespective of party, to preserve the honor and integrity of our Judiciary from the perils which threaten them. But no such movement was attempted in any form likely to make it effectual. Individual votes will be given for Judicial candidates without regard to party, but this will scarcely effect the result. The great mass of each party will vote for its own candidate; and it is fortunate, therefore, that the Republican candidates are without exception worthy, qualified and unexceptionable men.

abstract: A most horrible murder was committed, it is supposed on Tuesday night, by ROBERT STEWART, living in the Sand Hills, about four miles from Columbia. His house has been shut for a day or two. This excited curiosity, and finally suspicion, so strong that the door was forcibly entered. He was found lying on a bed by the side of the dead body of his wife. Upon examination it was found to be most horribly mutilated from head to feet. The head was severely cut in several places, and the body had been punched and disfigured with a piece of iron, which the flend must have heated for the purpose. He had been on a drunken frolic, and was still in that condition when he committed the horrible deed. A Coroner's inquest was held yesterday, and a verdict returned in accordance with the facts. STEWART was committed to jail to await his trial, Columbia South Carolinian, Thursday.

abstract: The November Term of this Court was opened yesterday, by Judge RUSSELL. The Grand and Petit Jury rolls were called, and excuses of jurors desiring to be discharged from service were heard. A large portion of
lead_paragraph: The steamship Adriatic, from Southampton on the 26th of October, arrived at this port yesterday morning, bringing five days' later mails, and three days' later advices than those received by the Prince Albert, at St. Johns; and the steamship Persia, from Liverpool on the 28th, was intercepted yesterday off Cape Race by the news yacht of the Associated Press. A large portion of this morning's TIMES is devoted to the news, which is of considerable interest. It is reported from Warsaw that the Imperial Conferences had been satisfactory to the illustrious personages concerned, and that the principle of a European Congress had been agreed upon. The promulgation of a new Constitution at this time by the Emperor FRANCIS JOSEPH is deemed significant, though, as far as Hungary is concerned, it is not believed that the restoration of a portion of her ancient privileges will quell the spirit of insurrection and revolution that is gaining ground there every day. We publish, among our extracts, the Prussian and Russian protests against the intervention of Piedmont in behalf of the revolution in Italy. Russia only has recalled her representative from Turin. There was a rumor that Great Britain was committed to the same policy, but the London Times indignantly denies its truth, and in an article, not very "complimentary to Prussia, declares that England would not follow in the lead of any despotism. An article in the Paris Constitutionnel, under the head of "French Policy in Italy," is supposed to have emanated from the Emperor himself. It shows that the proper course for France is non-intervention, and explains the impossibility of her interfering either in behalf of despotism against Italy on the one hand, or in behalf of revolution against constituted authority on the other. The London Times speaks of the article as "Napoleon's quiet reply to the divine-right demonstration at Warsaw." From Italy the news is not of an important character. According to a telegram from Naples, dated the 23d ult., hopes are entertained that Capua will soon be evacuated by the Royal troops. We are once more assured th[???] the Pope has no intention of leaving Rome. The Austrian war preparations in Venetia are being carried out upon a stupendous scale, and the impression strongly prevails that she will soon actively interfere against the Revolution. Our English. French, and German correspondence, received by the Adriatic, presents a full review of all the European news of the day.

abstract: The U.S. sloop-of-war Cumberland is expected to arrive here every day from Portsmouth, N.H. She is to be the new flag-ship of the Home Squadron. The Cumberland was formerly a frigate, but is now a "double-decked corvette." Her appointment as flag-ship is in direct opposition to the well-established custom, in obedience to which Commodores and Admirals have recently been placed on steamers by almost every power. She comes here to take on board an armament of twenty-four guns, which has been especially prepared for her. The razee Savannah, which left Yard in a few days, so that the old and new flag-ships of the Gulf Squadron are destined to be beside each other for a few weeks at Brooklyn.

abstract: The influence that American example is having on European politics is manifest in many recent events; but especially in the progress so rapidly made by the idea of universal suffrage. A few years ago the Emperor of France acknowledged the potency of this influence.
lead_paragraph: The influence that American example is having on European politics is manifest in many recent events; but especially in the progress so rapidly made by the idea of universal suffrage. A few years ago the Emperor of France acknowledged the potency of this influence. He submitted his claims to the greatest throne in Continental Europe to the decision of the ballot-boxes, and rules now by virtue of the indorsement he thus and then obtained. He liked the principle and its workings, and so did and do the French people who accepted the result that they themselves had accomplished.

lead_paragraph: No people cry out more piteously against violence and intolerance, widen they are themselves the victims, than the propagandists of Slavery. They will not suffer a Republican to make a speech, or to avow his sentiments in private conversation, where they have the power to punish him; but the faintest indication of intolerance manifested by their opponents is heralded forth as the most unheard-of crime. They seem to forget that in all the Slave States they utterly and totally suppress free discussion by violence, that they tar and feather men on mere suspicion of being Anti-Slavery in sentiment, and hang them when convicted before Judge Lynch, on negro testimony. Yet if a Democratic procession should be jostled in the streets in a Northern city, we should not hear the last of it for six months.

lead_paragraph: The fact that secretary COBB, the leading spirit in the Cabinet of Mr. BUCHANAN, is a disunionist, open and above board, is not denied by either himself or his friends. We have it on the authority of journals printed in his own State, that during a recent visit to his Southern home, he unhesitatingly counseled resistance to the Administration of a Republican President, and secession from the Union in the event of Mr. LINCOLN's election. During his visit to this City a few days ago he made no scruple to reiterate the same views in the presence of several gentlemen of his party; while from Washington, we have the full particulars of a disunion plot, in which one if not two or three of those who stand nearest him in official position, avowed their active sympathy.

abstract: It is universally conceded that the vote of New-York to-day decides the Presidential question. Every other Northern State is surrendered to LINCOLN. lead_paragraph: It is universally conceded that the vote of New-York to-day decides the Presidential question. Every other Northern State is surrendered to LINCOLN. The great West will pronounce for him by enormous majorities. No one has a moment's doubt about any NewEngland State, and the vote of last month rendered it absolutely certain that Pennsylvania will vote for him by at least 30,000 majority. The decision of the question, therefore, rests with New-York; -- and so certain is the vote of the whole interior, that nothing less than forty or fifty thousand against him in the City can cast a shadow of doubt on the result in the State at large.

abstract: The householders and inhabitants of New-York have cause to rejoice in the proof which was yesterday given them of the efficiency of our Police system. The most exciting general election which our times have seen, yesterday drew out the largest vote ever deposited in the ballot-boxes of the Metropolis. Nearly 100,000 citizens, representing a majority upon whose passions every possible inflammatory influence had been for weeks at work, and a minority, stung by attacks the most unsparing and unscrupulous, into an iron temper of determination, met on thisfield of conflict and exercised the highest prerogative of their civil state in such an absolute freedom, even from disturbance or annoyance of any kind, as could not have been guaranteed to a like population, in like circumstances, any where else in the world by regiments of armed men. Quietly, unostentatiously and impartially the gardians of the public peace did their duty supported at every point by the general good sense and good feeling of the people, with an unanimity beyond all praise, as it certainly was beyond all expectation. A happier augury could not be asked for the new era of our national politics, nor could a higher testimony have been offered to the actual organization of our Municipal Police. No honest man in his senses can think without a shudder of the scenes which must yesterday have been enacted in our streets had the protection of order been confided to the reckless Janissaries upon whom in former days the care of our homes and our highways reposed. The henchmen of Mayor WOOD, those heroes of his Honor's siege of the City Hall, would have made wild work with the great contest of 1860. Let not the very completeness with which the Police of yesterday did their duty blind us to the merits of the organization which alone has made that completeness possible.

abstract: A short time before 12 o'clock midnight, an impromptu gathering of the City Wide-Awakes took place, and preparations were made immediately for a demonstration. A banner bearing a full-length portrait of "Old ABE," with a broom in both hands, in the act of sweeping out the White House, and surmounted by the inscription, "Clear the track!" was carried in front of the procession.
lead_paragraph: A short time before 12 o'clock midnight, an impromptu gathering of the City Wide-Awakes took place, and preparations were made immediately for a demonstration. A banner bearing a full-length portrait of "Old ABE," with a broom in both hands, in the act of sweeping out the White House, and surmounted by the inscription, "Clear the track!" was carried in front of the procession. Forming in platoons of six abreast, they marched down Broadway, through the Park, and, halting in front of the TIMES office, gave rousing cheers for the success of the Republican ticket. The procession then marched down Park-row, headed by the banner, and marching to the tap of a drum. When they had reached a position opposite the Astor House, several rowdies broke into the procession and tore down the banner, while one of the party, at the same instant, struck one of the Wide-Awakes a heavy blow upon the mouth. This was the signal for a general fight; clubs and stones were freely used by all parties, and one of the rowdies, finding himself overpowered, drew a knife and made a rush at those nearest him, swearing that he would murder every Wide-Awake that he could get a hold of. Another drew a revolver and threatened to blow the first man's brains out who approached him. These actions and threats kept the Wide-Awakes at some distance, when one of the party shouted, "What, shall three or four loafers frighten us?" and instantly a rush was made, and before either party could use their weapons they were disarmed and badly beaten. Another of the assailants drew a heavy club, while the two parties were fighting at the corner of Broadway and Vesey-street, and struck one of the Wide-Awakes a severe blow upon the head, felling him to the ground. Hardly had he committed the assault, however, than he was seized by a number of the Wide-Awakes and most unmercifully pummeled. Finally he broke from them and entered an Eighth-avenue car, which had just started, and escaped. A number of the Wide-Awakes now went up Broadway, preceded by the banners, and the rest dispersed.

abstract: Our correspondent at the State Capital of South Carolina sends us the information, -- which may possibly startle the shattered nerves of our neighbor, the Herald, -- that the Legislature of that State has elected BRECKINRIDGE President, and LANE Vice-President. At first sight, this looks rebellion. It looks as if the Palmetto State had determined to try conclusions with the rest of the Union, and had stalked into the field under the banner of a new Pretender to the throne. We shall probably, therefore, have predictions of battle, murder and sudden death in all their forms,

abstract: THE LAURENS-STREET SHOOTING CASE. -- An inquest was held yesterday by Coroner SCHIRMER, at the New-York Hospital, upon the body of THOMAS COMANSKY, whose death has been already announced as having resulted from a gun-shot wound in the abdomen, received last Friday morning. Numerous witnesses were examined, but the testimony failed to develop any facts tending to establish the identity of the person who inflicted the wound. A verdict was therefore rendered of death from "Peritonitis," super-induced by the injury. Deceased resided in Laurens-street, near where the Police found him after he had been wounded.

abstract: The political campaign of eighteen hundred and sixty has reached its termination, and has unquestionably resulted in the election of ABRAHAM LINCOLN to the office, of President. In reaching this conclusion, we have very imperfect information from States which the consent of all parties and assigned to the Republican interest, but from, what have been regarded as doubtful States
lead_paragraph: The political campaign of eighteen hundred and sixty has reached its termination, and has unquestionably resulted in the election of ABRAHAM LINCOLN to the office, of President. In reaching this conclusion, we have very imperfect information from States which the consent of all parties and assigned to the Republican interest, but from, what have been regarded as doubtful States there are overwhelming majorities for the Republican ticket. The result in this City, where the Anti-Republican interest has obtained a plurality slightly exceeding twenty-seven thousand, has, in connection with such meagre returns as reach us from the counties, demonstrated the triumph of LINCOLN in this State; while in Pennsylvania, where a serious reduction of the thirty thousand majority of CURTIN in October had been looked to by all parties, that majority in favor of LINCOLN is swollen to an incredible figure, little less than a hundred thousand. From Connecticut we also have large Republican gains, evincing the astonishing growth of the Republican sentiment. It would be unsafe to estimate the actual majority upon the Presidential ticket, but it is safe to announce the election of Mr. LINCOLN, as entirely assured. As incidents of this general result, we may mention that Mr. BELL has probably carried both Maryland and Virginia.

abstract: At the second district poll of the Tenth Ward, located in Atlantic-street, near Smith-street, the election proceeded with the utmost spirit, mingled with good order, from sunrise to sunset. A very large vote was polled, and but for the inadequate facilities afforded for extending to the voters of the Ward the rights of franchise no cause for dissatisfaction would have marred the proceedings of the day. As it was, however, a large number of voters, probably one hundred and fifty, who were in every way eligible, were debarred the privilege owing to the expiration of the allotted time for voting, ere they could deposit their ballots. As early as 6 o'clock nearly one hundred voters were on the ground, and as soon as the poll was opened a line, which soon numbered upward of a hundred, was formed, and eventually doubling in force. During the day the line fell but little short of one hundred, and as the hour approached for closing it became apparent that many would be deprived of an opportunity to deposit their ballots. No little excitement ensued from this cause, and during the rest of the day, Inspector FOLK remained on the ground with a strong force of Police. The crowd toward evening became more and more excited, while it continued to gain in numbers. At four o'clock nearly five hundred persons were on the ground, though good order prevailed. Precisely at the hour of sundown the poll was declared closed, and at that moment over one hundred voters stood in line, awaiting their turn to deposit their ballots. The disappoitment expressed was of the most bitter nature, and not a few berated soundly the neglect of the proper parties in not providing more ample means for voting in the Tenth Ward.

abstract: The genius of order seemed to have taken and preserved the rule in this Ward throughout the entire day. Only three arrests were made -- two of a couple of half-drunken, half-grown boys, who got up a private quarrel at the Poll District, No. 33 Greenwich-street, and who were accommodated with a place on which to sleep off the effects of the bad rum which they had been pouring down, at the expense of the City. As there was no specific charge against them, they were merely detained until perfectly sobered, when they were discharged with a few further words of caution from the Sergeant in command. A man named JAMES STOHLES was arrested in the Fifth District of this Ward, for attempting to vote illegally, and was committed for examination.

abstract: If any one doubted last evening that the telegraph wires were big with the fate of this glorious Union, a walk in the vicinity of the different newspaper offices would have speedily convinced him to the contrary. Such crowds as were gathered around the doors of the TIMES, Tribune and Herald are only to be seen on these quadriennial occasions of the country's salvation or destruction. Even our mundane neighbor suffered from a temporary deluge of humanity, and crowds rushed to read the latest entries in the Day Book. The publication offices were soon filled; "happy thou," thought the crowd outside, who have gained admittance to the inner mysteries. It is very probable that the minnows in the North River envy those which are snugly boxed up and labeled sardines. Anxious to see as well as to hear the outside crowd flattened their noses painfully against the panes -- one would have imagined that they thought to smell out the returns. They climbed on each other's shoulders and stood on each other's heads in a vain attempt to peer in at the second story windows. Curiosity, apprehension, exultation -- these and all other emotions, were as plainly stamped on each individual countenance as the Eagle on a quarter or the Georgius Rex on an old-fashioned penny-piece. These emotions found expression whenever returns came in from a Ward or a County. There were cheers and groans and huzzas and hisses. And until the night had grown old and morning was born, the clamorous crowd demanded more news and later intelligence. They demanded to know the fate of the Union before daybreak, and many of them learnt it before they went home. But it is questionable whether the majority of them would find out during the coming Presidential term whether the country were saved or lost, if it were not for the information supplied by their party newspaper.

lead_paragraph: The principal head-quarters of the Bell and Everett men in Broadway was thronged as early as 7 o'clock P.M., by an eager multitude, whose impatience to learn the first tidings of the election manifested itself in shouts and other demonstrations. A steady stream poured in and out of the hall, which, from the confined state of the inside atmosphere made it almost impossible to breathe it. The meeting finally overran, and a large concourse blocked up the sidewalk in front of the building. It was not long before straggling returns from the Wards began to come in, and, as they were announced from the platform, a scene of the wildest excitement ensued. They shouted and cheered, waved hats, clapped hands, stamped, whistled, crowed and then cheered again. The crowd pressed up towards the platform, and mounted the benches, which gave way, one after another with a crash, precipitating the perchers to the floor amid derisive shouts and laughter. The announcement that APPLETON had beaten BURLINGAME in Boston created a furore of delight, and the whole company gave themselves up to yells, shouts and huzzas which were perfectly deafening. The announcement that New-Jersey had given eight thousand majority for fusion, and that "PENNINGTON was defeated," created another paroxysm which vented itself in a long, strong, and tumultuous pow-wow, which would have startled a tribe of Narragansett Indians. A motion was immediately made and carried, to receive New-Jersey into the Union. The news that the Ninth Ward had polled 1,000 majority for Fusion, brought out another prolonged and ear-splitting round of cheers, given after the most approved modern style, ringing the changes first on "U-n-i-o-n -- Bell-Everett -- tiger," and then with their "One-two-three-four-five-six-seven -- t-i-g-e-r!" In some cases the official returns were read as they were handed in, and at others the President would state that he had learned from an "authentic source" so and so. A transparency quoting the 1,000 majority in the Ninth Ward was finally brought into the hall, which appeared to set the whole meeting crazy with excitement, and for a time the din and confusion was perfectly appalling. The excitement had now reached a pitch which it was difficult to control, and it took the President, with the aid of several assistants, by signs, gestures, and grimace, to bring them to listen to what he wished to communicate. Seizing the transparency aforesaid, with one of the Union banners, they rushed out of the hall, and for several minutes flaunted it before the eyes of their astonished neighbors, the Republicans across the way. They then marched up and down Broadway, shouting with all their might and main. A statement that Niagara Falls had voted by a small majority, the Union ticket, brought out another torrent of the customary demonstrations.

abstract: One petition at least in the political litany of every honest and respectable citizen of New-York was yesterday heard and answered. The election of Mr. LINCOLN to the Presidency of the United States may or may not be that "direful spring of woes unnumbered" which the opponents of the Republican Party have for months
lead_paragraph: One petition at least in the political litany of every honest and respectable citizen of New-York was yesterday heard and answered. The election of Mr. LINCOLN to the Presidency of the United States may or may not be that "direful spring of woes unnumbered" which the opponents of the Republican Party have for months proclaimed that it would be. It may or may not result in the dissolution, immediate or proximate, of the Union; in the annihilation of Northern commerce and of Western agriculture; in the subjugation of New-England by frantic armies of ruined manufacturers from New-York under the command of GEORGE SANDERS, and in the erection of a Southern Empire to be protected by the Turcos and ruled over by Prince NAPOLEON. These are all eventualities on which it is not worth while just yet to speculate, which no one would thank us for treating gravely, and which it is hardly fair either to the course of events or to the temper of the still excited public mind to deal with in any other fashion.

abstract: A VESSEL HALF AS LONG AGAIN AS THE GREAT EASTERN. -- An official report has been published, in England, of a river steam vessel belonging to the Oriental Inland Steam Company, and intended to navigate the shallow rivers of the East, which possesses peculiar scientific interest from the fact of this composite vessel being the longest vessel ever yet constructed, being nearly half as long again as the Great Eastern. It appears that on trial this great vessel, or train, was found to be easily manageable, and attained a satisfactory rate of speed; and its success solves the important problem how to carry a very large cargo on a very small draught of water against a rapid stream. The train consists of a steamer and five barges, of the collective length of 900 feet. But these barges, instead of being, towed asunder like common barges, are joined to one another by circular joints, like a hinge, so that they constitute one long flexible vessel, with only one bow and one stern. The purpose of this arrangement is to obtain the necessary displacement with small resistance, and without the risk of damage, should the vessel get aground, and all these conditions are effectually fulfilled by the arrangements adopted. The train is 30 feet broad and 7 feet deep. At a draught of water of 3 feet it will carry about 3,000 tons of cargo. Such a vessel is greatly needed at the present moment to carry up railway materials in India, and to bring down cotton, flax, and other articles of agricultural produce.

abstract: The crowd which gathered about Tammany last evening, dispersed and reassembled several times before the old wigwam showed any signs of life. Not only was there no "Rynders pocket-piece," to scare the echoes in the Park, but there was no tarbarrel, there were no rockets or Roman candles. Not to speak of a full Band of music, there was not even a single drum or fife. Tammany was dismal.

abstract: The Republican rejoicings filled the City last night. They celebrated their triumph in the streets; they gathered in shouting crowds around the newspaper-offices; they inundated the Station-houses, and threw up their hats as the returns were announced; they assembled at the Head-quarters, No. 618 Broadway, in such numbers, that once wedged in one could...
lead_paragraph: The Republican rejoicings filled the City last night. They celebrated their triumph in the streets; they gathered in shouting crowds around the newspaper-offices; they inundated the Station-houses, and threw up their hats as the returns were announced; they assembled at the Head-quarters, No. 618 Broadway, in such numbers, that once wedged in one could not turn around to come out again. There Mr. DANIEL D. CONOVER took the Chair, and, with Gen. J.H. HOBART WARD and Mr. CHARLES SPENCER, received the returns, and from time to time computed the probable result. Mr. CONOVER read the figures, and every time he read the people cheered or jeered, according to the complexion of the news. The enthusiasm," which was wild, as soon as it was known how much below the estimate of the Fusionists was the result in the First Ward, increased steadily as the night wore on, and was incontinent at last. Never were there gathered together so many persons in so excellent a humor. While they were waiting for news from some Ward not yet heard from, all were talking and laughing at once; some were giving lusty cheers for LINCOLN and the whole Republican ticket; some were cracking jokes at the expense of the Opposition; those without were endeavoring to elbow their way in, and some within, half suffocated, were trying to force their way out. It was just such a hubbub of hilarity, in short, as you would expect to hear in the Republican Head-quarters on the night of the Republican victory. One, more enthusiastic, was incessantly proposing three cheers for somebody. He proposed three cheers for Gen. WARD; they were given with gusto. He proposed three more for Mr. CONOVER, and three more for Mr. SPENCER; they were given. Then he proposed "Three cheers for me." They were not given. Then, by way of variety, he proposed three cheers for Mr. CONOVER again. Here that gentleman interposed and requested that less noise should be made, and that men would stand still; he did not know how long the floor of the room would support such a mass of enthusiastic people. A man mounted a chair at the remote end of the room and shouted out the name of a friend, whom he said he wanted to go to a fire that was raging not far off. "There's a fire every where," said Mr. SPENCER, and that brought down the house -- almost the floor -- again. Loud as the din was during these interludes, as soon as the Chairman announced more returns, quiet was immediately restored -- to be lost again amid a storm of cheers as soon as they were read. Thus, till a late hour, they kept it up at No. 618 Broadway.

abstract: One of the finest races of the season took place at Poughkeepsie on Monday, between WILLIAM BERGER, of that city, and JOSHUA Ward, of Newburgh, the acknowledged champion of America, for $500. BERGER challenged any man in the country to row him a distance of five or ten miles for a sum of money and the championship, and the friends of WARD at once persuaded him to accept the challenge. The race was agreed between the parties to come off at Poughkeepsie, and the course to be rowed was twice around that recently rowed at the late regatta at that city. At 3 o'clock in the afternoon the signal was given, BERGER gaining the advantage of a boat's length in the start. This slight difference was soon, however, overcome by WARD, and the men rowed for miles nearly side by side. Nearly two thousand persons, from all parts along the river, were present to witness the race. A barge, filled with persons, steamed up and down the river. This was mostly filled with ladies. The Poughkeepsie crew, in their four-oared boat, rowed alongside of their champion, and cheered him on, while the Newburghers were provided with a small steamboat, which easily kept alongside of the rowers. The course was about ten miles. On the home stretch BERGER was slightly ahead, and would probably have won the race, if he had not made a mistake in crossing the river to the opposite side of the stake boat, to that which was agreed upon by the judges as the winning side, and before this difference could be regained, WARD had passed him and won the race by only 3 1/2 minutes. Time, 83 minutes and 86 1/2 minutes. It is expected that another match will be made up between them immediately.

lead_paragraph: We regard the result in Virginia, Kentucky and Tennessee, as having substantially dispelled all the danger of disunion which the election of LINCOLN was supposed to involve. But another peril of a still more fearful character may arise in its place. There is reason to apprehend negro insurrections, more or less extensive, in various portions of the South. How far they will spread, or with what circumstances of horror and atrocity they may be attended, it is impossible to predict. But we fear that they will take place in many sections of the South, and that very considerable inconvenience and suffering may result from them.

abstract: -- The brig Nathum Stetson, Capt. OLIPHANT, arrived at this port yesterday from Tampico, the 19th, having made the passage in seven days from the bar. She brings an important decree from Gov. GARZA, of the State of Tamaulipas, by which it is ordered that from this time forth, all Custom-house dues at Tampico, whether for exports or imports, must henceforth be paid in gold or silver. From the preamble to the decree, we, learn that the paper received for these dues has already amounted to $600,000; that this paper is daily increasing and depreciating in value; that, in fact, it can no longer be need as a just compensation to the employes, even in the Custom-house, and less to pay the employes of the civil and military government.

abstract: The clouds lowered gloomily over the City yesterday morning, when the polls were opened, and very shortly afterward rain began to drizzle, with every prospect of a wet day. Was it an omen, and if so, an ill omen to the Lincoln or Fusion ticket? It did not, at any rate, keep one or the other party from the polls, for never in the history of any political contest in this country, has more enthusiasm been exhibited, and the result has proved that though the "clouds" may have "lowered," the hopes of the Republican Party were not "in the deep bosom of the ocean buried." But of that anon and elsewhere.

abstract: October is generally one of the most agreeable months in our changeable climate, and in our cities it is usually one of the most healthy. The past month has proved to be somewhat an exception to the general rule, being colder and more stormy than the average of Octobers. The effect upon the public health has not, however, been very marked.
lead_paragraph: October is generally one of the most agreeable months in our changeable climate, and in our cities it is usually one of the most healthy. The past month has proved to be somewhat an exception to the general rule, being colder and more stormy than the average of Octobers. The effect upon the public health has not, however, been very marked. In the four weeks ending October 27, there were 1,611 deaths in the City, an increase of 107 over the corresponding period in 1859. This increase of mortality is no more than proportionate to the increase of population. Of the 1,611 deaths in the four weeks named, 852 were males and 759 were females. This is in accordance with the usual rule in all large cities. During the year 1859, the proportion of the sexes who died in New-York was 116 males to 100 females. But in the living population of this City there is constantly an excess of females, the proportion in 1855 being 92 males to 100 females. We find then, here, as in other northern cities, the curious fact that with a large excess of females among the living, there is constantly a large excess of males among those who die.

lead_paragraph: Yesterday forenoon the most painful excitement prevailed in the Naval circles of this City, owing to the fact that a letter from Brazil in the NEW-YORK TIMES, confirmed by two private communications; announced the intelligence that a burning propeller, supposed to be the United States steam gunboat Seminole, was seen off Pernambuco, Brazil. The Seminole left Norfolk to join our Brazil Squadron on the 14th of July last, or thereabouts, and was consequently over two months out on the 25th of September, at which date she had not reached Rio. The probability that the rumor of her loss is a cruel hoax has been altogether overruled. In view of the recent letters from the ship, which declared her to be a complete failure, we subjoin an extract from a communication received from her a few days ago. abstract: One of the most gratifying of the results of the canvass is the fact that Virginia has cast her vote for BELL and EVERETT. The Disunion movement could have received no heavier blow than this, at the hands of the Old Dominion. Mr. JEFFERSON always regarded Virginia and Pennsylvania as the great safeguards of the Union; -- so long as they stood by the Constitution, he did not believe that any portion of the Confederacy would withdraw. They occupy a central position and exercise a very strong influence upon both sections of the Union. The extremes of opinion prevail in the extremes of the Confederacy -- and the interposition of these two great States would always prevent any hostile collision between the remoter and more ultra members.

abstract: A WOMAN LYNCHED. -- On the 27th ult. Miss SUSAN JEMIMA BARNES, who resided about eight miles from Fulton, Mo., was brutally murdered by a negro woman in her employ. All of the white folks belonging to the family had gone to church, about two miles distant. Miss BARNES had prepared dinner and was sitting in the kitchen knitting when she was first attacked. A strand of yarn from the ball which she dropped showed that she had retreated through several rooms before she was finally overpowered. She was found with her head so beaten and broken that not a whole bone remained, except the right cheek bone. Her brains, were scattered over the floor, a large pool of blood was under her head, and there was every indication of a terrible struggle having taken place between her and the murderess. There were the marks of bloody hands on the wall, blood on everything about the house, and evidence that, in all probability, a knife had been used at some time during the difficulty, as Miss B.'s hand was very much cut.

lead_paragraph: It is too early to speak confidently of detailed results of yesterday's election. But there can be no reasonable doubt that the Republicans have elected their President. It has been universally conceded that the issue lay with New-York, and New-York casts her vote for LINCOLN. What the majority will be cannot yet be known. We believe, however, that it will fall very little, if any at all, below our estimate of 40,000. Pennsylvania, has very largely increased her majority of October, and there is no reason to doubt that the New-England State and the West are largely Republican.

abstract: -- Inness has recently completed a landscape entitled "A Thundergust" -- and while it is in many respects but a reproduction of some of his earlier works, it possesses many, points of superior excellence. The vast extent of absolute perspective cannot fail to impress one -- the heavy foregoing shadow of the dense and brooding cloud -- the majestic bending of the grand old oaks -- the graceful yielding of the lesser vegetation -- the scampering homeward of the life-like sheep, and the perturbed and troubled appearance of the human figures, are elements with which the artist has succeeded in painting a wonderfully fine picture, and one which will add to his deservedly high reputation.

abstract: The Republican pulse continues to beat high. Chanticleer is perched on the back of the American Eagle, and with flapping wings and a sonorous note proclaims his joy at the victory. The return of the the First NAPOLEON from Elba did not create a greater excitement than the returns of the present election. All day yesterday the inquiry was in everybody's mouth, "What's the latest news?" Newspapers were in demand. What, with the cries of the urchins who yended them, the demonstrations of the jubilant and the groans of the wounded, the Metropolis of yesterday was to the every-day New-York as Babel to a charnel-house. Every omnibus that carried its dozen of citizens businessward in the morning was a reading room, a political meeting-house and a pseudo stock board, all in one, -- e pluribus unum. Some read the papers, some fought the bloodless battle o'er again, bringing their batteries of profound argument to bear upon the proposition that they "knew LINCOLN would be elected;" and some in sarcastic mood bewailed with mock seriousness the heavy losses from depreciated stocks that were sure to follow the dire calamity of the inauguration of the chosen of a majority of the people. In the streets, in the restaurants, in offices and counting-houses -- counting certain counting-houses out -- such was the tenor of the talk, and the character of the occupations of all to whom a leisure moment came. There were few Fusionists to be found. There was a dearth of Democrats -- a searcity of those who professed and called themselves Bell-Everett men. Republicans everywhere seem wide awake, while

lead_paragraph: A number of residences have lately been broken into and robbed in Newburyport, Mass., and on Sunday night on suspicion that the dwellings of Mrs. ALBERT WOOD, Mr. JOHN OSSOOD, Hon. MICAJAH LUNT and Mrs. JOHN WILLIS, might be assailed, police officers were stationed there to guard against the burglars. About 1 o'clock the watchman stationed in the house of Mrs. WILLIS heard footsteps outside, and soon afterwards an attempt was made to cut out a square of glass with a diamond. This did not succeed, and the burglar next tried a "jimmy," which pried up the window. After the noise this operation occasioned, the burglar waited some time to see if his movements had caused an alarm. But all was quiet, and he removed his boots preparatory to entering. Just as he had climbed into the window, the policeman, according to his instructions, fired at him with a pistol, and the shot took effect in the burglar's breast.

abstract: Now that the election is over, we trust the Disunionists of the South will receive no more aid and comfort from the opponents of the Republican Party in the Northern States. It would probably be too much to expect that the organs of the Opposition should at once remedy the injustice they have done the Republicans, in representing them as aiming at the liberation of Southern slaves.
lead_paragraph: Now that the election is over, we trust the Disunionists of the South will receive no more aid and comfort from the opponents of the Republican Party in the Northern States. It would probably be too much to expect that the organs of the Opposition should at once remedy the injustice they have done the Republicans, in representing them as aiming at the liberation of Southern slaves. But they can have no further interest in concealing from their readers, the real sentiments of the President elect upon the subject of Slavery, and the issues which have been decided by this campaign. They have nothing to gain now, certainly, by misleading the public mind on these points. Like all other citizens, they are interested in the preservation of the public peace and the perpetuity of the Union: -- and they ought to take it for granted, except upon the most irresistible evidence to the contrary, that no man whom a constitutional majority of the American people may elect to the Presidency, will ever willingly disturb the one or endanger the other.

abstract: It used to be the peculiar boast of Western men that they could run faster, jump higher, dive deeper, and peel more bark in a day than any other individuals under the sun. Lately, however, material progress has become the special object of glorification.
lead_paragraph: It used to be the peculiar boast of Western men that they could run faster, jump higher, dive deeper, and peel more bark in a day than any other individuals under the sun. Lately, however, material progress has become the special object of glorification. AENEAS was not prouder of having founded a State, nor ALEXANDER of having built a city, than is the Western settler who "reckons" that his quarter section may be exactly in the centre of some great future Porkopolis, and that Porkopolis the capital of a sovereign State. If Manhattan Island was once sold for $25, and an American eagle judiciously invested, has often, under the enchantment of speculation, expanded into a fortune, why, indeed, despair of wealth in view of this romantic feature of the West,

abstract: The Fine Arts are taking their place, at last, among the serious elements of our national industry and commerce, and on purely material grounds have earned a right to the attention of political economists.
lead_paragraph: The Fine Arts are taking their place, at last, among the serious elements of our national industry and commerce, and on purely material grounds have earned a right to the attention of political economists. The moralist and the statesman are never likely to underrate the permanent importance to the national character of this development of human capacity, and it is unnecessary to insist upon considerations which have become commonplaces in the mouth of every lecturer whose "mission" it is to glorify the Beautiful, like Sir EDWARD BULWER, with a large B, and of every distinguished orator who undertakes the inauguration of a statue, a gallery, or a school of design. The more prosaic are not, for that reason, the least positive and significant aspects of the question of national aesthetics. It is a good thing in itself, and in its consequences for the State, that the creation of works of art at home and the importation of them from abroad, should have grown from insignificant incidents into prominent features of the national industry and commerce; and every influence which can aid in the healthy progress of artistic activity among us merits the attention and the assistance of the public mind, quite as much, to put the matter on its lowest grounds, as if it concerned the improvement of live stock, or the extension of the iron trade.

abstract: On the  night of the 12th of October, Mr. and Mrs. PETERSON were murdered near Picton, C.W. Suspicion was directed against SETH SMART, an Indian, and his sister, MARY SMART. After a tedious pursuit, for they left the vicinity soon after committing the deed, the two were...
lead_paragraph: -- On the night of the 12th of October, Mr. and Mrs. PETERSON were murdered near Picton, C.W. Suspicion was directed against SETH SMART, an Indian, and his sister, MARY SMART. After a tedious pursuit, for they left the vicinity soon after committing the deed, the two were [???] at Branford, C.W., a few days since. On Friday, the prisoners were brought before Mayor JONES and a bench of County Magistrates. Sergeant-Major CUMMINS, after relating the particulars of the capture of the prisoners, stated that while on their way down from Toronto to Picton, the male prisoner after being duly cautioned that anything which he said would be used against him at his trial, acknowledged to him that he was present when the murder was committed. He had, he said, only come out of the Penitentiary about a month, previously, having served a period of tour years for cattle stealing. During his incarceration, his wife had decamped with another Indian, and he left his mother's house on the night of the murder for the purpose of stealing a cow in order to procure money to go in search of the missing wife. He had no intention to commit murder when he started, but while in the vicinity of Mr. PETERSON's residence, he met two men and a boy whom he had never seen before. They entered into conversation, and it was then decided to murder Mr. and Mrs. PETERSON and rob, and afterwards set fire to the house in order that evidence of the crime might be obliterated. The boy entered the house and killed both, and then took possession of several articles and set fire to the house. The fire burned through the floor and then fell into the cellar and was extinguished.) He (Sergeant-Major CUMMINGS) asked SMART who these parties were, and he replied that he had seen them in Toronto jail while he was confined there on his way down, but immediately added. "Oh, never bother about them, I will be hanged and that is enough" Various articles which belonged to Mr. and Mrs. PETERSON and which were found were SMART was known to have hidden them, where produced, and the evidence being conceded sufficient against him, he was committed for trial. His sister was discharged for want of evidence.

lead_paragraph: The further returns which we are enabled to present this morning, are extremely meagre, but not unsatisfactory. They sustain the first tidings of the undoubted election of Messrs. LINCOLN and HAMLIN; and while the first wild estimates of majorities are, as was to be expected, seriously modified, there is no question about the overwhelming majority secured by the Republican ticket. Some interest is still felt in the contest at the South, as measuring the relative strength of the ultra and conservative sentiments in that section. Mr. BELL appears likely to have gained Maryland, Kentucky and Virginia, while returns received from. Georgia and Arkansas are unexpectedly favorable to him. Mr. BRECKINRIDGE is successful in Delaware, North Carolina and Louisiana; while Mr. DOUGLAS prevails, in Missouri. We are without reports from the other States.

abstract: RECEPTION OF THE PRINCE OF WALES IN NEW-YORK. -- We copy from the London Times the report given by its special correspondent of the Reception of the Prince of Wales in this City. Besides its interest as a picturesque and striking description of an important event, it will be read with special pleasure, on account of its cordial and thorough appreciation of the welcome extended to the Prince by the people of this country. There are passages in it which indicate a lack of accurate information concerning us, but this could scarcely be otherwise under the circumstances. Although the letter refers to a past event in our history, it will still be read with interest.

lead_paragraph: On Friday, the 2d inst., a boiler of the Mississippi steamer H.R.W. Hill exploded, instantly killing thirty-nine persons. The same day a boiler blew up at New-Haven, fatally injuring three or four persons. The next day the boiler of the tow-boat Baltic exploded in Mobile Bay, killing and fatally injuring several people. On the 24th ult. -- a little over a week ago, a boiler explosion occurred at Lee, and another at Lowell; and the day before there was another at New-Orleans, each one killing its man and injuring others.

abstract: A SMALL EXCITEMENT IN THE CITY HALL. -- In the absence of any news from the various City Departments, the components of which were engaged, yesterday, in cyphering up the grand result, a small excitement was created in the City Hall by way of affording an item for the reporters. It appears that Mr. JOHN CALLAHAN, who ran for and claims to be elected as member of Assembly from the lower district, was violently opposed by THOMAS BYRNES, Superintendent of Lands and Places, long a resident of the Fifth Ward, and who, claiming the right of free speech, had expressed very openly his opinions as to Mr. CALLAHAN's qualifications for the office to which he aspired. These not being remarkably favorable, aroused the ire of the member elect, and yesterday afternoon, while CALLAHAN was surrounded by friends, Mr. BYRNES was discovered approaching the City Hall, in the vestibule of which the party were standing. Mr. BYRNES, unconscious of any premeditated attack, entered the Hall on business, when he was accosted by Mr. CALLAHAN, and angry words ensued, the result being that Mr. CALLAHAN was caught by the throat and so tightly squeezed, that he called for some friend to cut his cravat. Mr. BYRNES got off with a torn coat. The fracas caused, for a time, much excitement in and about the City Hall, but it gradually subsided after the belligerents had separated. The greatest damage done during the affray, was the blacking of the eye of an innocent porter who chanced to witness the affray, and who was unguarded enough to express his disapprobation of the proceedings.

During the canvass it suited the purposes...
lead_paragraph: Now that ABRAHAM LINCOLN is to be President of the United States during the next term, all parties are equally interested in understanding his precise position on the great question by which the country has been, and still is, so profoundly agitated. During the canvass it suited the purposes of his opponents to represent him as an Abolitionist -- as a man utterly reckless of the rights and interests of the Southern States, and disposed to make war upon Slavery, wherever it exists, regardless less of its effect upon the prosperity of the country and the stability of the Union. It was to little purpose that his friends denied the truth of these representations; what they said was charged to the natural zeal of political partisans. But now that the election is over, and the result fixed, we have all one common interest in ascertaining upon what principles his Administration will probably be conducted.

abstract: -- So far as our City is concerned the Republicans have gained two. WALL is elected in the Fifth District, represented in the present Congress by Mr. MACLAY, a Democrat. WARD succeeds BRIGGS, -- and this is not a loss to the Republicans though it is gain to the Democrats. CONKLING is elected in Mr. COCHRANE's district, and DELAPLAINE, Democrat, carries the district now represented by CLARK. Mr. WAKEMAN, the Republican candidate in this district, deserved success, for his ability, industry and acquaintance with public affairs. WILLIAMSON, in the lower district, made a very strong and creditable contest against WOOD, but the financial popularity of the latter proved too strong for him. His vote proves that he had a strong hold upon, the esteem and confidence of the laboring men of the district.

lead_paragraph: From the few additional returns of the election received, we gather nothing which changes the result as already announced. We publish, however, this morning, a great variety of interesting matter indicating the manner in which that result has been received, especially in the South. Sentiment is varied, but the preponderance seems to be against any immediate movement looking to disunion, and in favor of awaiting some "overt act" on the part of the incoming Republican Administration which may justify such action. South Carolina, of course, -- if we are to place reliance upon the dispatches received, -- is in favor of an immediate movement towards secession, and her prominent public men, well known for their advocacy of a Southern Confederacy, are urging it with all their eloquence. It is announced that a State Convention is to be called at once. Gov. BROWN, of Georgia, sent a special message to the Legislature of that State, yesterday, in which he disapproves of the idea of calling a Convention of the Southern States, and declines to recommend the appointment of delegates. He thinks, however, that the constitutional rights of the South have been violated, and suggests a measure of retaliation in the shape of reprisals. In this connection he points particularly to the State of Massachusetts. The Governor contends for the right of secession -- not, however, while each State of the Confederacy fulfills, in good faith, its constitutional obligations -- and that the withdrawal of one State virtually dissolves the whole compact of Union. In Virginia and Maryland, there is comparatively very little excitement. It is not probable, judging "from the telegrams of our special correspondents, that a movement towards disunion will be countenanced by the majority. At the National Capital there appears to be considerable alarm at the position of affairs, and serious difficulty is apprehended from the resignation of Federal office-holders, especially those engaged in the collection of the revenue. The Collector of the port of Charleston, as we yesterday announced, has already resigned, and it is feared his subordinates may follow his example. If they have not done so already, however, there is not much probability that they will. Meantime President BUCHANAN maintains an unbroken silence in reference to the matter, even to the members of his Cabinet. It is expected that he will indicate his views to-day, in Cabinet meeting. It is not considered probable that any of the Government officers at Washington will resign, notwithstanding the threats previous to the election.

abstract: HORRIBLE BRUTALITY. We find in the English papers an account of admissions made by the students at the great French Veterinary School at Alfort, to Dr. FRASER, concerning the continued practice of horse torture at that school. The Doctor states that the students "unhesitatingly admitted that, in addition to practicing vivisection for the sake of physiological research or experiment, every operation which could by possibility be required to be performed in the course Of veterinary.
lead_paragraph: HORRIBLE BRUTALITY. -- We find in the English papers an account of admissions made by the students at the great French Veterinary School at Alfort, to Dr. FRASER, concerning the continued practice of horse torture at that school. The Doctor states that the students "unhesitatingly admitted that, in addition to practicing vivisection for the sake of physiological research or experiment, every operation which could by possibility be required to be performed in the course of veterinary practice was, on two days of the week during the session, performed over and over again by the teachers and students, on living (diseased or worn-out) horses, operations of the most exquisitely painful nature being successively performed on different parts of the same horse, until nature gave way, the wretched animal having been tortured to death by knife and fire, in as barbarous a manner as man or devil could devise. To add to the brutality, horses which have only been partially experimented on are often left till the next operating or experimenting day, (not the following day,) when a renewal of their torture takes place. His question as to whether they ever gave chloroform or other to the animal before vivisection, was answered in the negative, and with a derisive smile."
