abstract: Not the least important feature in the present array of forces which are to acquire for Italy her place among the nations, and to maintain that place when won, is the naval armament of the States now so nearly reunited under the sceptre of King VICTOR. Italy is destined, not less by the hereditary genius of her people than by her geographical position and the character of her enormous coast-line, to become a great maritime Power whenever she becomes a Power at all. If Holland and America may lawfully dispute the right of modern England to sing the proud song which claims for Britannia the empire of the waves, Italy, from the height of her magnificent mediaeval history, may smile at the pretensions of all. She it was who first made navigation mistress by the compass, over all the accidents of cloud and wind and tide; she it was who gave to mankind the mighty oceans, now become the highway of commerce between old Europe and the new continents, revealed by the genius, and reached by the daring of an Italian sailor. Three centuries have dimmed the glory of Venice, of Pisa, of Florence, and of Genoa; but they have neither changed the outlines of the Italian peninsula, nor destroyed the qualities of the Italian race. A single glance at the map will show how marvelous are the natural maritime advantages of the wonderful country which is now hailing with a thousand voices the dawn of her new era, and the greatness of her heaven-sent deliverers. VICTOR EMANUEL, welcomed in the South as King of Italy by the overwhelming acclamation of eleven millions of Italians, upon whom rested six short months ago the pall of the basest of Bourbon despotisms, has now added to Genoa and Leghorn and Spezzia, each the possible centre of a commerce equaling that of Trieste or Marseilles, the whole sea-coast of Sicily and of Naples. Palermo, Messina, Naples, the numerous ports of Calabria and the Tarentine Gulf, Ancona and her Adriatic sisters offer to the new Kingdom, even while Venice still awaits her hour, inlets and outlets of traffic which place it at once upon a level with the busiest, nations of the Continent. The enterprise which has fought its way so gallantly up, in the face of all the trials and troubles of a divided Italy, till Genoa and Leghorn have carried the flags of Sardinia and of Tuscany into every sea, will take a fresh and startling impulse from the new prosperity of an Italy independent and united.

abstract: The Stuyvesant Institute was well filled by Republicans last evening, in response to a call from the Young Men's Republican Union for a gathering of the victors in the lately decided contest, for conference and congratulation. The meeting was called to order by Mr. CHAS. T. RODGERS, the President of the Young Men's Republican Union, who said that in the language of the immortal PERRY, "We have met the enemy and they are ours," and they had met there tonight to rejoice over the victory. After a few introductory remarks relating to the part taken in the contest by the Young Men's Republican Union, he introduced as Chairman of the evening Mr. WM. CULLEN BRYANT, who was received with loud and long-continued cheers.

abstract: During the canvass our neighbor the Tribune warned the public against a plot which the TIMES was supposed to favor, to fuse with a portion of the Democrats on a Judiciary ticket. It was well known that a very influential portion of the Democratic Party was utterly disgusted with the character of some of their judicial nominations, and stood ready to unite with the Republicans in supporting Judge BONNEY and JOHN SEDGWICK, Republicans, against Recorder BARNARD and JOHN MCCUNN, provided the Republicans would support Judge ULSHOEFFER for the Superior Court and E.C. WEST for, Surrogate. They were prompted to this proposal, doubtless, partly by political motives; -- but it was nevertheless calculated to maintain the character and dignity of the Judiciary, and to meet the wishes of the great mass of the better portion of our citizens.

abstract: We are not surprised, -- nor in the least alarmed,-- at the symptoms of resentment and the movements towards secession which greet the news of LINCOLN'S election in the Southern States. We have never supposed the South would sit down quietly and submit at once to Republican ascendency in the Federal Government. The stake for which they have been playing is too high. They are too deeply committed to permit any such retreat. They would incur the scorn and contempt of their own people if they were thus to quail before the spectre they have invoked. They are compelled to go ahead, -- if only to prove that they were not hypocrites and knaves in their threats.

abstract: SHOCKING CASUALTY. -- Early yesterday morning, a Mrs. ELWIG, residing at No. 112 Barrow-street, had occasion to leave home for a few minutes, and she locked up her two children -- a boy of four years and an infant five months old -- in a room together. When she returned she found the bed-clothes in flames, and the babe almost dead in consequence of the lad having found a box of matches which he had ignited and fired during her absence. The little sufferer was conveyed to the New-York Hospital, where its death soon occurred.

abstract: THE OFFICE OF CORONER. -- The Secretary of State directed no call to be made for the election of Coroner in the First District of the city. But Ex-Coroner REDDING, it seems, had his eyes open, and got up a ticket with his name upon it, which received about 100 votes in the Ninth Ward. He now claims that he is entitled to the office, now held by Coroner HERTON, on the 1st of January next. But there is also another claimant. Mr. WM. MURPHY was one of the Democratic candidates at the recent election for Coroner in the Second District. By some mistake. a portion of his tickets were printed for the "First District." and about 400 of these tickets were polled before the error was corrected, so that if any one gets the office by this series of mistakes, it will doubtless be Mr. MURPHY.

abstract: The public were invited to attend the anniversary meeting of the Academy of Medicine, held on Wednesday evening, at the Hall of the Historical Society. The attendance was far less than the occasion and the very interesting nature of the exercises deserved. After an appropriate prayer, Dr. JOHN WATSON, the President of the Academy and orator of the evening, was introduced at precisely 8 o'clock. He spoke for nearly an hour and a half, but the attention of the audience never flagged for a moment during the whole of this time. His main theme was "the character of the true physician," and he discussed the requisites, both natural and required; the duties and the mission of the medical practitioner in all the varied relations and circumstances arising from his position. Dr. WATSON vindicated the character of the profession in this country, insisting that although there were, perhaps, fewer examples of (as it were) concentrated or monopolized learning in America; compared with Europe, yet the mass of our physicians were more than equal in knowledge and practical tact to the mass of the physicians in other countries. He also dwelt at length upon the manners and general conduct of a physician to his patients; and spoke of the mental and moral influences that he should be ever ready to exert in his practice; to gain and preserve the confidence and respect of his patients, to aid in the discovery of disease, to enter largely into the treatment, to advance the cause of honor, science and human justice and to soothe and comfort the sufferers from irremediable ills. He illustrated the facts, principles and suggestions in his address with innumerable anecdotes and sketches which, however familiar they may have been to the well-read of the professional gentlemen present, were exceedingly apropos to the subject, occasion and general audience, and displayed an inexhaustible fund of medical lore of all times and all nations. After he had concluded, Dr. JOS. M. SMITH moved that the thanks of the Academy be tendered to Dr. WATSON for his elaborate and valuable address, and that the latter be requested for publication, and diffused widely among the students and profession generally, as well as the public. Dr. ALEXANDER STEVENS seconded Dr. SMITH's motion, and it was, of course, unanimously carried, and after an invitation to all present had been tendered by the President of the Historical Society to visit the Society's valuable library and picture-gallery, the meeting adjourned.

He spoke for nearly an hour and a half, but the attention of the audience never flagged for a moment during the whole of this time. His main theme was "the character of the true physician," and he discussed the requisites, both natural and required; the duties and the mission of the medical practitioner in all the varied relations and circumstances arising from his position. Dr. WATSON vindicated the character of the profession in this country, insisting that although there were, perhaps, fewer examples of (as it were) concentrated or monopolized learning in America; compared with Europe, yet the mass of our physicians were more than equal in knowledge and practical tact to the mass of the physicians in other countries. He also dwelt at length upon the manners and general conduct of a physician to his patients; and spoke of the mental and moral influences that he should be ever ready to exert in his practice; to gain and preserve the confidence and respect of his patients, to aid in the discovery of disease, to enter largely into the treatment, to advance the cause of honor, science and human justice and to soothe and comfort the sufferers from irremediable ills. He illustrated the facts, principles and suggestions in his address with innumerable anecdotes and sketches which, however familiar they may have been to the well-read of the professional gentlemen present, were exceedingly apropos to the subject, occasion and general audience, and displayed an inexhaustible fund of medical lore of all times and all nations. After he had concluded, Dr. JOS. M. SMITH moved that the thanks of the Academy be tendered to Dr. WATSON for his elaborate and valuable address, and that the latter be requested for publication, and diffused widely among the students and profession generally, as well as the public. Dr. ALEXANDER STEVENS seconded Dr. SMITH's motion, and it was, of course, unanimously carried, and after an invitation to all present had been tendered by the President of the Historical Society to visit the Society's valuable library and picture-gallery, the meeting adjourned.

abstract: A few days ago two young men called at the house of Mrs. Marcella Hunter, No. 410 Sixth-avenue, and offered to sell her a new Grover  Baker sewing machine for $20, representing that they had taken it
lead_paragraph: A few days ago two young men called at the house of Mrs. Marcella Hunter, No. 410 Sixth-avenue, and offered to sell her a new Grover & Baker sewing machine for $20, representing that they had taken it for debt, and were thus enabled to sell it at so low a price. Mrs. Hunter determined to purchase it, and to accommodate her the young men offered to let her have it for $5 cash, and the balance in two days. The bargain closed, Mrs. Hunter showed her acquisition to her friends, one of whom, having heard of the circumstances under which she had procured it, told her it must have been stolen. She therefore called at Grover & Baker's store and inquired about the matter, and an investigation showed that she had bought a machine which had been stolen from the store a few days before. Measures were therefore adopted for the arrest of the young men should they apply to Mrs. Hunter for the balance of the money, and on Thursday John Sharkey, one of the individuals in question, having presented himself with that object, he was arrested. Subsequently Officer Colfax arrested his confederate, a man named James Fitzsimmons, and both prisoners were committed by Justice CONNOLLY for trial. It is believed that the accused are in league with one of the employes in the store, and that a clue has now been obtained to the recent theft of several machines. The prisoner Fitzsimmons, yesterday afternoon, escaped from the cell in Which he had been confined at the Jefferson Market Prison, and as his escape is attributed to negligence on the part of one of the keepers, Justice CONNOLLY will probably investigate the matter.

lead_paragraph: Somebody has telegraphed to the Charleston Courier, from Washington, that President BUCHANAN "recognizes the right of secession, but not of nullification." This is a distinction without a difference. If Mr. BUCHANAN has authorized any such announcement his case is more hopeless than we had supposed it to be. He must be dreadfully frightened, by the menaces of the South, to dream of making any such distinction as the basis of official action.

abstract: REPUBLICAN REJOICINGS. -- The Republicans of the Seventeenth Ward held a public meeting in their Wigwam on Thursday evening to manifest their satisfaction at the result of the election. Speeches were made by J.N. STEARNS, C. POORY, J. MCDIARMID, J.P. HALLETT, S.W. BAILEY and others. A salute of 33 guns was fired by Capt. TAFT. The Republicans of this Ward claim for it the title of the Banner Ward of the County. In 1856, out of a vote of 600, FREMONT had 215; while in 1860, with a vote of 1,254, LINCOLN has 683 votes to 571 for Fusion. The local Republican candidates received a much larger majority. One hundred guns were fired in this city on Thursday evening in honor of the recent victory.

abstract: The case of New-Jersey, as the only State east of the Rocky Mountains, which gave a majority adverse to freedom, and submission to the absolute will of the Slaveholding oligarchy, is so much of an anomaly as to war
lead_paragraph: The case of New-Jersey, as the only State east of the Rocky Mountains, which gave a majority adverse to freedom, and submission to the absolute will of the Slaveholding oligarchy, is so much of an anomaly as to warrant peculiar attention and study. It is hardly worth while to say that devotion to the Union had no more to do with the result than in any adjoining State; for the willingness to transfer the election to the more hazardous chances of the House is the worst possible evidence of such loyalty. By what secret then, the influences favorable to LINCOLN, which pervaded so thoroughly every neighboring State, which actually flowed up in vast surges to the very frontier, giving Pro-Slavery Philadelphia to the Republicans, and disappointing all the calculations of fusion in New-York -- why these waves stopped on the boundaries of this little Commonwealth, and left it unbaptized, may reasonably puzzle those who are unacquainted with the politics of this singular people.

abstract: THE ADVENTURES OF A LOOKING-GLASS. On yesterday a lady engaged one of the City Express wagons to convey a large and valuable looking-glass to the upper part of the City, but through some carelessness on the part of the driver it was broken.
lead_paragraph: THE ADVENTURES OF A LOOKING-GLASS. -- On yesterday a lady engaged one of the City Express wagons to convey a large and valuable looking-glass to the upper part of the City, but through some carelessness on the part of the driver it was broken. Complaint was made at the Mayor's Office, and the driver brought before the First Marshal, who directed that the glass should be restored. This was promptly complied with by the owner of the express line, but the driver, instead of delivering it at the house of the owner, or even notifying her of the replacement of the glass, took it to the Mayor's office, where it was placed in an embrasure of a window outside the railings, and a notice was sent to the owner to call and receive it. Meantime, and before the lady reached the office, a poor Irishman, who was looking for employment, started into the Mayor's Office, and gladly availing himself of the bench which stands there to rest his heavy limbs, he sat down, and leaning his head against the corner of the embrasure, was soon enjoying the pleasures conferred by "tired nature's sweet restorer," and went off to the land of dreams. The corner against which his head reclined was sharp, his head was round, and as a consequence, it slipped, his body followed, and the consequence was the entire demolition of the glass a second time, as he fell directly upon it. Of course, any claim for damages as against him would have been preposterous, and the unfortunate owner of the glass has only its memory and its associations for her consolation.

abstract: -- Thomas H. Benton Bruner, a barber in St. Joseph, Mo., recently succeeded in winning the heart and hand of one of the fair damsels in that city. While he was enjoying his honeymoon he received information that a wife who had prior claims upon him, was about coming to see him; and to avoid an unpleasant scene, he left there suddenty, writing a note to his second wife, to inform her that he would return in a few days. Soon she received a letter, stating that he had been killed on the railroad and that if she desired to have the body of her deceased spouse she must come for it. Her brother-in-law at once procured a coffin and started, but when he reached the town at which the letter was dated, he learned that the whole story was a hoax. At last accounts he was in pursuit of the gay deceiver, asserting most solomnly that the coffin should not go back empty.

abstract: About 1 o'clock yesterday morning, a fire broke out in the sub-cellar of the wholesale drug-house of PENFOLD, PARKER  MOWER, No. 15 Beekman-street, and notwithstanding the fact that the fire companies
lead_paragraph: About 1 1/2 o'clock yesterday morning, a fire broke out in the sub-cellar of the wholesale drug-house of PENFOLD, PARKER & MOWER, No. 15 Beekman-street, and notwithstanding the fact that the fire companies promply repaired to the place, where they worked faithfully, the fire continued to smoulder until near noon, and not until that time was it completely extinguished. The fire was confined to that portion of the building in which it broke out, and the flooring of the story above was not even burned through. The stock of drugs stored in the cellar was so valuable, however, that the quantity destroyed is estimated to have been worth at least $70,000. The entire building is occupied by Messrs. PENFOLD, PARKER & MOWER. It forms one of the handsome row of six-story brownstone buildings at the corner of Beekman and Nassau streets, owned by WHITLOCK BROTHERS, after whom they were named. Persons passing by the premises would not even suspect that a fire had occurred inside; the exterior of the buildings have not been injured at all, and, in fact, it is thought that the damage to the interior may be repaired for $1,000.

abstract: THE HOMICIDE IN NEW-HAVEN. -- One of the Police Courts in New-Haven, Conn., is now investigating the homicide of young STAFFORD. On Wednesday morning a most affecting scene occurred. The mother of young BELDEN, who had just arrived in town, came into the court-room, and threw herself upon her son's neck, sobbing, "My son, my son, how came you here?" She finally sank into her son's arms, where she remained in an almost unconscious state throughout the day.

abstract: From the highly interesting special dispatches from various points, which we publish this morning, it will be seen that the disunion feeling in the South has already reached its culminating point, and that a calmer condition of the Southern mind
lead_paragraph: From the highly interesting special dispatches from various points, which we publish this morning, it will be seen that the disunion feeling in the South has already reached its culminating point, and that a calmer condition of the Southern mind is gradually being attained. Even in South Carolina, according to our latest accounts, the people are not so ready for extreme measures as we were led to infer from the first intelligence following the knowledge of the success of Mr. LINCOLN, and, of course, unless South Carolina takes the lead, it is not probable that any movement towards a disruption of the Union will be made in any other quarter. A dispatch from Columbia, received yesterday, announces that a bill had passed the Senate providing for the calling of a State Convention to consider the subject of secession, but fixing the 8th of January as the day for electing delegates thereto, and the 16th of January for the assembling of the Convention. The House may insist upon an earlier day, but there is evidently a disposition not to be too precipitate. From Washington we learn that the President and Cabinet held a meeting yesterday, at which the condition of affairs in the South was discussed. President BUCHANAN, according to the dispatch of our correspondent, is confident that South Carolina with leave the Confederacy, but not during his term of office. Should the issue, however, be precipitated before that time, he believes it to be madness, to attempt coercion, as that would have the effect to disrupt the whole Union. It is understood that Secretary COBB alone excused the extreme position of the Palmetto State. The hope was generally entertained that, even in case she saw fit to secede, the cool judgment of the best men of the South would prevent any such action on the part of other States. At any rate, should South Carolina annul the resolutions by which she adhered to the Federal Constitution, she will be let alone by the present Administration. It seems that the rumor of the resignation of the Collector of the Port of Charleston was untrue, but that the Federal Judge has resigned, as stated. No effort will be made at present to fill the vacancy, as the only embarrassment occasioned will be felt by the South Carolinians themselves.

abstract: The distrust which attends all the beneficial propositions of Mr. BUCHANAN'S Cabinet, has relaxed in the single instance of the Slavetrade. The public is half convinced that so
lead_paragraph: The distrust which attends all the beneficial propositions of Mr. BUCHANAN's Cabinet, has relaxed in the single instance of the Slavetrade. The public is half convinced that so far as this Government possesses power, the Administration is disposed to use it vigorously and earnestly for the suppression of the traffic; and it is quite certain that the Administration of Mr. LINCOLN will prosecute the duty with at least equal energy. The fact, therefore, that a well-defined policy is found to exist, naturally excites attention to the mode of putting it in action; and elicits from those best acquainted with the subject a variety of useful and practical suggestions, some of which may be found in the letter of a correspondent in another column. Of these it may he profitable to state the purport.

abstract: Now that the people have finished Presidentmaking, it is probably that our publishers will devote themselves assiduously to the making of books. Little people seem to enjoy the favor of these latter gentlemen amazingly, and books are showered for their benefit as plentifully as kind nurses are wont to scatter bons-bons.
lead_paragraph: Now that the people have finished President-making, it is probably that our publishers will devote themselves assiduously to the making of books. Little people seem to enjoy the favor of these latter gentlemen amazingly, and books are showered for their benefit as plentifully as kind nurses are wont to scatter bons-bons. These little clear-paged volumes are as indicative of the coming of Christmas as are the first flakes of snow which begin to drift downward through the air. The APPLETONS have prepared for their delectation New Fairy Stories, for My Grandchildren, translated from the German of GEORGE KEIL by S.W. LANDER. Germans are always at home in Fairy Land. They can move their goods and chattels, pipes and philosophy, into the clouds at a moment's notice, and discourse with shadows and sunbeams as familiarly as with old acquaintances. It is safe to commend any fairy tale of German origin. Even though a thin haze of transcendentalism and misty irreligion may be discernible, it is powerless to fog a child's mind. Children generally get at the kernel of a nut, and reject the bitter husk, more readily than grown people. If you give them a sugar-coated pill they are sure to nibble off the sugar and discard the bitter balance of the globule. KEIL, however, deals only in moral fairies, and is perfectly unobjectionable. The same publishers give their young friends an opportunity of spending A Year with Maggie and Emma, which book is edited by Miss MCINTOSH. The young ladies whom Miss MCINTOSH introduces to the world of jackets and short frocks are very pleasant indeed, and will probably become favorites. But the crowning blessing which the munificent APPLETONS vouchsafe to family circles is The Young American's Picture Gallery, containing five hundred wood-cuts of everything in and out of nature, including Gen. WASHINGTON on his celebrated white horse, the Great Eastern, Gen. PUTNAM and JULIUS CESAR. The illuminated picture on the cover, of a Cupid performing an aerial journey on a frog's back, would alone suffice to keep a baby's eyes open, and mouth correspondingly closed, for an entire week.

abstract: FIRE -- TWO HORSES BURNED. -- Yesterday afternoon about 4 o'clock, a fire broke out in a temporary stable in Gregory-street, near Washington-alley, Jersey City, owned by CHARLES NEWAY. The Fire Department were soon at work, but owing to the inflammable material, the stable, together with two horses, harness, &c., were destroyed. One of the horses was owned by LEWIS REIN, whose loss is $200; the other belonged to Mr. NEWAY, whose loss, including the horse and stable was about $175. The fire was undoubtedly the work of an incendiary.

abstract: -- The case of young William Blue, now paying the penalty for passing counterfeit coin in a Western State, is a hard one. He is the son of a wealthy New-England farmer -- graduated at an Eastern college, married a young lady of this City, went West, lost all his money by speculating in land, became reduced to want, was tempted and led into the commission of his first crime, for the doing of which he was arrested within twenty-four hours, tried within a month, and leaving his wife and three little ones with no money and few friends, has entered the State Prison, where for years he will mourn his folly and his fault.

abstract: Anstria has taken the first step towards the liberation of Venetia. Not, indeed, with the good will or the conscious participation of the Imperial Government, for the same hand which signed the new charters of the prov
lead_paragraph: Anstria has taken the first step towards the liberation of Venetia. Not, indeed, with the good will or the conscious participation of the Imperial Government, for the same hand which signed the new charters of the provinces confirmed the appointment of a strictly military martinet to the highest civil authority in Venice, and the gorges of the Tyrolean Alps are resounding with the rattle and roar of trains crowded with troops hurrying to Verona and Mantua, while the bells of Pesth and Comorn are ringing in the restoration of Hungarian institutions to the Hungarian race. The defiance flung down to FRANCIS JOSEPH so haughtily at Naples by the King of Italy has been taken up as haughtily at Vienna, and all Europe awaits in apparent anxiety the collision now deemed by half her wisest diplomats inevitable, between the liberator of the Peninsula and the despot of the Northern Adriatic. In the tone, the temper, the language and the official acts of the Viennese Government, Venetia is still more sternly than ever claimed as an inalienable appanage of the Crown of the Hapsburgs. All official Europe beside, from ALEXANDER II. and Prince GORTSCHAKOFF at Warsaw, to VICTORIA and Lord JOHN RUSSELL at London, agrees at last with the far-seeing Emperor of the French in regarding the Austrian dominion at Venice as an impossibility, to be tolerated, perhaps, provisionally, in the hope that toleration may lead to a settlement of the question otherwise than by war, but not at all to be entertained as a permanent element in the European system. So much has been won for common sense and common justice in the diplomatic world by the courage, the genius, and the good faith of the great Sovereign who spoke at the Tuileries in the hearing of all mankind, on the first of January, 1859, those memorable words, which have proved to Italy the "Open Sesame" to a once seemingly hopeless future. It is now an easy common-place of European opinion that Venice belongs naturally to the Venetians. Eighteen months ago it was revolution to hint the thought, and NAPOLEON was denounced as the enemy of mankind for putting the thought into deeds.

abstract: During next week the benevolent will have an admirable opportunity of indulging their inclinations to do good; for, from Monday until Saturday a Fair for the benefit of the Protestant House of Mercy will be open at No. 783 Broadway, between Ninth and Tenth streets. The directors of this institution have aimed to make it a home for both friendless and fallen girls, rather than an asylum for the reclamation of vicious adults, and since its incorporation in 1855 it has accomplished a noble work. Within its walls 187 girls and women have found refuge, and of this number 63 are believed to be doing well. Twenty were confirmed drunkards when they were received; six have died, and nine are married. The Provisional Bishop of the diocese has visited the House officially three times, and has confirmed in all 25, who have taken upon themselves the vows of the Church. These results have not been achieved without great sacrifice, and much credit is due Mrs. RICHMOND for the untiring energy which she has displayed in advancing this enterprise, the interests of which she has had so much at heart. Besides the $6,000 balance due on the mortgage, the institution is in debt to Mrs. RICHARDSON to the amount of $4,370. Next week much may be done to reduce these incumbrances. Shall the institution be allowed to labor under them longer?

abstract: In the papers of Friday morning, Nov. 9, a call appeared for the Southern Medical Sutdents attending lectures in this City to meet at the hall of the Medical College, on Fourteenth-street, to take action as to their course in remaining here or going home, since the result of the election of Tuesday.
lead_paragraph: In the papers of Friday morning, Nov. 9, a call appeared for the Southern Medical Students attending lectures in this City to meet at the hall of the Medical College, on Fourteenth-street, to take action as to their course in remaining here or going home, since the result of the election of Tuesday. The Faculty, however, being unwilling that the hall should be used for political purposes, refused to open it for the meeting, and consequently the place of meeting was changed to the Democratic Head-quarters on Broadway, opposite Astor-Place.

abstract: The People ex rel. the Bank of the Commonwealth in New-York vs. The Commissioners of Assessments and Taxes of the City and County of New-York. -This case has been once or twice stated in the TIMES, and will be readily remembered. The Bank of the Commonwealth had invested in United States stocks of the loan of 1858 the sum of $103,000, and claimed that the investment was exempt from taxation under the United States Constitution. The Commissioners of Taxes denied that the investment was so exempt from taxation, and assessed the personal property of the Bank for the year 1859 at $561,165 16 -- being for the amount of capital stock actually paid in, less the sum of $188,834 84, which was invested in real estate, upon which the banking institution was located.

abstract: On Saturday evening the discovery was made at the New-York Hospital, of a plot on the part of some one to poison Capt. ISAAC GILLY, master of the coasting schooner Sea Bird, who, for some time past, has been a patient in the institution, under treatment for intermittent fever.
lead_paragraph: On Saturday evening the discovery was made at the New-York Hospital, of a plot on the part of some one to poison Capt. ISAAC GILLY, master of the coasting schooner Sea Bird, who, for some time past, has been a patient in the institution, under treatment for intermittent fever. The circumstances of the occurrence, as narrated by the officers at the Hospital, are as follows: Capt. GILLY occupied a bed in the same ward with three men named H.W. JENKINS, CHAS. BROWN and JOHN KEIGER, and a few days since in their presence he took from his person a leather belt, containing $200 in gold, and having counted the money, he replaced it about his waist. The exhibition of this little hoard seemed to have excited the cupidity of the three patients whose names have been mentioned, and a plot was concocted by them, as subsequent developments appear to indicate, by which they were to obtain possession of the money. Accordingly on Saturday last, at dinner time, some Croton oil was poured into the soup which had been served to Capt. GILLY, but the unpleasant taste which was thus imparted to the mixture, induced him to leave it almost untouched. During this time it is said that the man JENKINS had narrowly watched the action of the Captain, and, having observed what disposition had been made of the broth, he took occasion to overturn the bowl which contained it upon the floor, as if by accident, hoping in this way to destroy the evidences of the plot. Capt. GILLY had not entertained any suspicion that the nauseous compound contained poison, therefore he made no statement of the case to the nurse in charge of the ward. Later in the day he obtained permission to take a walk, and while down-town he placed his money in one of the savings' banks, returning to the Hospital in time for tea. At tea-time he and another patient, named MAHONEY, were each supplied with a bowl of milk. Its appearance, however, was very dark, and, although the matter was made the subject of remark between them, it did not deter either from swallowing a large draught. Soon afterwards both were taken ill, with symptoms of having been poisoned, and the peculiarly unpleasant taste of the milk led them to believe that the dose had been administered in that. Mrs. REYNOLDS, the nurse, was informed of their suspicions, and to satisfy herself, she tasted some of the mixture which GILLY had left in the bowl. The result was that her lips became blistered, and Dr. HARRIS, the house surgeon, was made aware of the matter. After tasting the milk, the doctor unhesitatingly stated that it had been tinctured with Croton oil, and immediately Superintendent DARRAGH was sent for. Meantime GILLY and MAHONEY had become so sick that fears were entertained that they would not survive the night, and a messenger was dispatched to the office of the Detective Police, asking assistance to investigate the circumstances. Detectives BENNETT and MCDOUGAL were detailed to inquire into the case, and having done so, they took JENKINS, BROWN and KEIGER into custody, a linen coat which had been worn by the former having been found partly saturated with Croton oil. The prisoners were taken to headquarters, where all of them are now detained pending an investigation by a magistrate of any charge which shall be brought against them. JENKINS admits that the poison was placed in the soup and milk by himself and the other accused parties, but states that it was done for a "lark," and with a desire to "physic" Capt. GILLY. This story, however, is not fully credited. It has not yet transpired whether the prisoners obtained the oil from the Hospital dispensary or from a drug-store, but in either case it is not probable that they could have been ignorant of its poisonous properties. At a late hour last night the patient MAHONEY had recovered sufficiently to be considered out of immediate danger, but Capt. GILLY's symptoms were still unfavorable.

abstract: The secession excitement in the South continues gradually to subside, and everywhere outside of South Carolina and Georgia the probability of a disunion movement grows "small by degrees and beautifully less." It is true, Senator CHESNUT,
lead_paragraph: The secession excitement in the South continues gradually to subside, and everywhere outside of South Carolina and Georgia the probability of a disunion movement grows "small by degrees and beautifully less." It is true, Senator CHESNUT, of South Carolina, and Senator TOOMBS, of Georgia, have resigned their seats in the United States Senate -- so the telegraph informs us -- but no particular significance is to be attached to the action of these gentlemen, inasmuch as it was the declared intention of the latter to resign whether the Republicans succeeded in electing Mr. LINCOLN or not; and as the former could hardly do otherwise in the face of his repeated declarations. On the other hand, indications of movements on the part of the conservative people in the Slave States now begin to reach us. A meeting has been held in Augusta, Georgia, at which resolutions were passed, deprecating hasty action; and our dispatches generally show that a better feeling is everywhere beginning to prevail.

abstract: It would be singular if all those in the extreme South who threatened a dissolution of the Union before the election, should immediately subside into peaceful submissionists the day following that event. There is no reason why they should.
lead_paragraph: It would be singular if all those in the extreme South who threatened a dissolution of the Union before the election, should immediately subside into peaceful submissionists the day following that event. There is no reason why they should. There is no more danger or inconvenience in persisting in the policy which has been pursued for years, now that it is ascertained that we are to have a Republican President, than there was in the days of JACKSON or TAYLOR or FILLMORE. The Disunionists of South Carolina and the Gulf States have dictated the policy of this Government, with the exception of four or five years, during the last quarter of a century. They have given their support to the Democratic Party on the single condition that its administrative policy should favor the extension of Slavery, and rigidly withhold patronage from all who oppose or refuse actively to cooperate in the support of pro-Slavery measures. Whenever there has been any shrinking on the part of the Northern Democracy from this policy, the Southern ultraists have, until recently, had little difficulty in reining them into line by threatening to break up the party and the Union itself. The tactics of the ultraists have never disappointed them but once, and it is not surprising that those who have so long relied upon them should still have faith in their virtue.

abstract: On Friday last, while the drawbridge over the Flushing Creek was turned to permit a vessel to pass through, by some mismanagement or bad steering, the vessel struck the abutment, which sustains the revolving portion of the bridge, with such force as to throw the whole structure from its position. The draw was so much damaged as to require a suspension of the through trains, but the care, which were fortunately on the Hunter's Point side of the creek at the time, continue to make their regular trips, with the exception of that to Flushing. By the efficient exertions of Mr. BOTTORFF, the Superintendent of the Road, the bridge was put in thorough order on Saturday, when the through trains resumed their regular trips.

abstract: Yesterday was a great day at Plymouth Church. Thousands of people gathered there early in the morning -- it having been announced that Mr. BEECHER would preach a sermon relating to the present state of affairs in the Republic. Not room enough was left unoccupied for the thinnest man in the two cities, and a solemnity not unmingled with curiosity pervaded the vast assemblage. As will be seen by the reports below, Mr. BEECHER preached both morning and evening on the topics of the day, and rarely has he been surpassed in manner or matter even by himself. The text on which the morning's sermon was based, is found in Isaiah li. 7, 16. "Hearken unto me, ye that know righteousness, the people in whose heart is my law; fear ye not the reproach of men, neither be ye afraid of their revilings," &c.

As will be seen by the reports below, Mr. BEECHER preached both morning and evening on the topics of the day, and rarely has he been surpassed in manner or matter even by himself. The text on which the morning's sermon was based, is found in Isaiah li. 7, 16. "Hearken unto me, ye that know righteousness, the people in whose heart is my law; fear ye not the reproach of men, neither be ye afraid of their revilings," &c.

abstract: We have on record  a speech delivered not many weeks ago by Gov. HENRY A. WISE, of Virginia, in which that always moderate and pious gentleman made the following declaration : "I will never remain in the Union twenty-four hours after LINCOLN'S election, so help me God!"
lead_paragraph: -- We have on record a speech delivered not many weeks ago by Gov. HENRY A. WISE, of Virginia, in which that always moderate and pious gentleman made the following declaration: "I will never remain in the Union twenty-four hours after LINCOLN's election, so help me God!" This solemn and fervent vow was received with cheers by the intelligent citizens of Princess Anne County, who well knew the Governor and his fidelity in keeping every promise. But now, the melancholy contingency which was to cause the departure of Mr. WISE out of the United States having arisen, his many friends at the North are anxiously inquiring, to what part of the earth has he betaken himself? His devotion to the South forbids us to believe that he can have crossed the briny deep to Europe, at a time when the sunny section of his nativity may at any moment need his trenchant arm to point with his sword the road of her conquering legions as they march Northward to camp in New-York. This destination, then, being placed out of the question, many believe that he has retired to Coney Island, which clam-producing region has been formally dissevered from the United States by the decree of Gov. GIL. DAVIS, bearing date last Wednesday morning.

abstract: -- The present Governor (DOWNEY) of California is a little, pleasant-faced, smooth-tongued Irishman. For years he was a prominent politician in the region of Los Angeles, devoting himself to the political fortunes of Senator LATHAM, then a promising young lawyer of Sacramento. Subsequently, through LATHAM's influence he was elected as Lieut.-Governor on the ticket with himself; and when LATHAM, the Acting Governor, was declared Senator, DOWNEY, by virtue of his position, became the head of the State Government, in which capacity he has developed and exhibited the most remarkable executive ability, and is in favor with all parties, cliques and clans.

abstract: Men, after all, are very much like sheep. They go in droves, and not only follow anybody who will take the trouble to lead them, but they run, when anybody will take the trouble to scare them.
lead_paragraph: Men, after all, are very much like sheep. They go in droves, and not only follow anybody who will take the trouble to lead them, but they run, when anybody will take the trouble to scare them. A flock of sheep will leap fences, cross ditches, flounder through swamps and lose half their aggregate fleece, at the chance bark of a wretched Scotch terrier, -- when they happen to be in the mood. That a crowd of brokers in Wall-street have the same habit, and obey the same impulse, our readers may satisfy themselves by taking a look at the stock sales of yesterday. That body of wise men, held by some people to be thermometers of public opinion, acted as if the world was to come to an end next week. Perhaps it will, -- but we don't believe they would be the persons to find it out in advance.

abstract: A delegation  from Philadelphia, consisting of a Seleet Committee of nine members of the Common Council, the Chief Commissioner of Highways and his two Assistant Commissioners, the Chairman and Committee of Highways, together with several members of both Boards of the Common Council, visited New-York on last Friday, for the purpose of investigating the subject of cleaning streets by street-cleaning machines.
lead_paragraph: -- A delegation from Philadelphia, consisting of a Seleet Committee of nine members of the Common Council, the Chief Commissioner of Highways and his two Assistant Commissioners, the Chairman and Committee of Highways, together with several members of both Boards of the Common Council, visited New-York on last Friday, for the purpose of investigating the subject of cleaning streets by street-cleaning machines. Notwithstanding the storm on Friday night, the entire delegation were out at a late hour, witnessing the practical working of the machines on Broadway. At their request the machines were operated upon a few blocks of cobble-stone pavement, being the pavement in use in Philadelphia. The merits of the machines were freely discussed, several of the party expressed their agreeable surprise, having had no idea that the machines had power or capacity to sweep such mud and slush as they were then doing. The inclemency of the weather prevented their stay to witness an extended trial. As it was, they got a thorough soaking from the rain, which fell in torrents during the whole time. On Saturday morning they called upon the Mayor, who gave them some information in regard to our municipal affairs and the subject under consideration. At the Mayor's suggestion they called upon City Inspector Col. DELAVAN. During the conference with that gentleman, the present or old plan of cleaning streets, &c., was regarded as a costly farce, unworthy of such cities as New-York and Philadelphia. Col. DELAVAN furnished the Committee with a variety of useful information in respect to the sanitary regulations of New-York. In reference to the sweeping machines, the City Inspector freely declared his opinion of their usefulness and economy. In the afternoon the Committee visited the stables in Twenty-eighth-street, and thoroughly inspected the machines, two of which were operated before them at their desire on Twenty-eighth-street, between Seventh and Eighth avenues. The work was done quickly and thoroughly. The gentlemen returned home by the 6 P.M. train on Saturday.

abstract: Washington  correspondents agree in representing Mr. BUCHANAN as indifferent to the fact that Federal law has ceased to be administered in South Carolina.
lead_paragraph: Washington correspondents agree in representing Mr. BUCHANAN as indifferent to the fact that Federal law has ceased to be administered in South Carolina. "If," we are told, "South Carolina does not desire the Federal Courts, the President thinks no one should complain." On this point, as on some others, people will be met with who dissent from the Administration view. Those, for instance, whose bills upon South Carolina Banks and merchants have returned protested, may fairly complain if they are precluded from the only medium of collection which, in the actual condition of things, can be made available. It is needless to say that to sue upon such claims in the local courts, would subject the litigant to personal hazard, uncompensated by any possibility of success. The United States District Court is the only tribunal accessible; and if, Judge MCGRATH having declared that court finally closed, the President does not reopen it, he will exhibit an indifference to two or three provisions of the Constitution, remarkable even in that Old Public Functionary. One collector, we are informed, returned yesterday to this City with $700,000 of bills due from South Carolinians, not a dollar of which could be had. If the holders of these obligations he appealed to, we suspect the President will find a strong disposition to complain, if there be no judicial authority maintained to aid in their enforcement. Or has Mr. BUCHANAN, from long habit, come to think that any state of things satisfactory to the South, should be acquiesced in everywhere?

abstract: A PAIR OF LAW  LESS SQUATTERS. For many years the citizens of New-York have lived under the delusion that the Battery was public property, and that the cession of that once beautiful spot to the City by the Legislature was a valid grant Recent events, however, which have trans-...
lead_paragraph: -- A PAIR OF LAW LESS SQUATTERS. -- For many years the citizens of New-York have lived under the delusion that the Battery was public property, and that the cession of that once beautiful spot to the City by the Legislature was a valid grant Recent events, however, which have transpired, would fairly lead to the inference that there must be some flaw in the title under which the City claims ownership. Not many weeks since we recorded the action of the the Common Council granting to GEORGE LAW the privilege of constructing a bulkhead north of pier No. 1 East River, to correspond with the enlargement of the Battery, and as a consideration for the enormous expense which such a work would entail upon that public-spirited citizen, they kindly added the grant of a perpetual ferry franchise to and from Staten Island, which franchise, by the way, Mr. LAW had enjoyed gratuitously for many years. Mr. HAWS, the Comptroller, notwithstanding his ardent admiration of Mr. LAW's desire to advance the interests of the City, could not find any Law which warranted the donation of such a privilege, slight as it was, and he took the only means at his command to remedy the error into which our municipal Solons had fallen; he closed up the "right of way" to the ferry by means of heavy stone posts and iron chains. Nothing daunted Mr. LAW procured from Mr. VANDERBILT the right of way to his own ferry-boats across the property owned by Mr. V., and the Jerry continues to run.

abstract: The New-York City Guard, commanded by Capt. M. LOVELL, went to Fort Hamilton yesterday for the purpose of target firing with sea coast artiliery.
lead_paragraph: The New-York City Guard, commanded by Capt. M. LOVELL, went to Fort Hamilton yesterday for the purpose of target firing with sea coast artiliery. The excursion was made on the ferry boat Peconic, which had been generously furnished for the occasion, free of charge, by the Union Ferry Company. Among the invited guests were Brig. Gen. HALL, Maj. J.C. BURNHAM, C.P. SMITH, Esq., President Union Ferry Co., Col. BOSTWICK, of the Eleventh Regiment, Col. LANSING, N.Y.S.M., Col. SWEENY and Seargt. JOHNS, U.S.A., J.M.B. LOVELL of Savannah, Ga., Hon. Mr. TOWNSEND and many other distinguished military gentlemen. The Guard numbered about fifty-six muskets, and were accompanied by Dodworth's full military band. On arriving at Fort Hamilton it was found that the greater portion of the target, which lay at a distance of over a mile from the shore, had been cut away during the morning by a schooner, leaving merely a low black line on the water which was illy adapted for the purposes intended. It was resolved, however, to use this, and seven of the heavy barbette guns of the fort, thirty-two pounders, were at once manned and prepared for action. Four rounds of seven guns each were fired. In the first round, the best shots fired were the first and fourth, each of which, it was judged, struck within fifty or sixty feet of the mark. The second shot was also a fair one, and all were excellent line shots. In the second round, the first two shots fired each struck the target, cutting it loose from its moorings and starting it floating down the Bay. The sixth was a fair shot, but all the others in this round were very wild. In the third round, the sixth gun again fired a good shot, but the target was moving so rapidly now that great difficulty was experienced in getting it in range, and all the others in this round were wild. In the fourth and last round the best shots were the third, fourth, and seventh, which struck, as near as could be judged, at a distance of from 50 to 100 feet from the mark. The target had now floated so far down as to be out of the range of the guns, and the firing was stopped. The gunners of the two guns which struck the target were Messrs. C. HUBBARD and L. BURKE. The gunner of No. 6, which also did some very fair shooting, was Dr. MCNEIL. The officers of the Fort who were present admitted that the firing was generally much better than that of the regular soldiers. On the return to the City a bountiful collation was set out, and after it had been disposed of speeches were made, songs sung, etc., until the boat landed at the foot of Wall-street, whence the Guard proceeded to their Armory.

abstract: The American edition of Carlyle's Essays, published by BROWN & TAGGARD, of this city, has pleased even the crusty author. In a private letter to the editor of the edition, CARLYLE writes: "It is one of the prettiest books imaginable: printed with beautiful accuracy and taste; beautiful paper, careful index, nothing deficient, nothing superfluous -- perfectly got up in all respects." We understand that an edition of Macoulay's Essays, printed at the Riverside Press in a style of equal beauty and elegance, is soon to be published. -- Boston Transcript.

abstract: The death of Lord DUNDONALD is announced this morning in our European news. Few men have had so eventful a career, and have been permitted to reach the advanced age of 85 years. The deceased, THOMAS COCHRANCE, tenth Earl of Dundonald, and bet-...
lead_paragraph: The death of Lord DUNDONALD is announced this morning in our European news. Few men have had so eventful a career, and have been permitted to reach the advanced age of 85 years. The deceased, THOMAS COCHRANCE, tenth Earl of Dundonald, and better known to tame as Lord COCHRANE, went to sea in 1793, and in 1795 fought his first action with the French, whom be defeated off the North American coast. In 1799, as commander of a party sent to relieve the Lady Nelson cutter, then surrounded and attacked off Cabritta Point by several French privateers and Spanish gun-boats, he displayed that desperate gallantry for which he became remarkable in after life. In 1800 he captured the French 74-gun frigate Le Genereux, and was appointed her acting captain Thence he was promoted Commander of the sloop-of-war Speedy, and during the ten months that he held this appointment he took 14 of the enemy's vessels. On the 8th of August, 1801, Lord COCHRANE received his commission as Post-Captain. The Speedy herself ultimately fell into the hands of a French 74-gun frigate, but during the action Lord COCHRANE displayed such conspicuous courage that the conqueror refused to accept his sword, requesting him to wear what he had so nobly used. During the next five years Lord COCHRANE distinguished himself in a variety of ways. Among the Spanish prizes that he captured was one from the La Plata, with nearly a million in specie. He destroyed the semaphores along the Trench coast carried by storm the battery at Pointe l'Equilon, and during January, 1807 -- some days, short of a month -- he took and destroyed fifteen of the enemy's ships. In 1868 Lord COCHRANE cooperated with the Spanish patriots of Catalonia, against NAPOLEON, and was engaged in many brilliant enterprises on shore and at sea. In April, 1809, he was selected, from his daring intrepidity, to command a fleet of fire ships intended for the destruction of the French fleet, then lying at anchor and blockaded by Lord GAMBLER, in the Basque Roads. On the night of the 11th of that month he went on board one of the explosion ships containing 1,500 barrels of gunpowder, and performed the hazardous service confided to him most effectually. For this act he received the Knighthood of the Bath. At this time the illustrious sailor was member of Parliament for Honiton. It is to his political course and his continued opposition of the Ministry, that the ruin of his own prospects of promotion is, in the first instance, attributed. His stock-jobbing operations, in 1814, did him more serious injury. Early in that year a false report was circulated that NAPOLEON had fallen, on which the funds suddenly rose, and Lord COCHRANE and several of his friends sold out to a large amount. He was tried and found guilty of being implicated in the fraud, and was sentenced to a heavy fine, a year's imprisonmment, and to stand in the pillory. He was also deprived of the Order of the Bath, of his rank in the navy, and expelled from the House of Commons. The sentence to the pillory was remitted. The electors of Westminster again chose him for their representative, and, under circumstances of extraordinary daring, he broke out of prison and reappeared in his place in Parliament. In 1818 Lord COCHRANE accepted the command of the Chilian fleet, and mainly contributed to the success of the Chilian war of independence. The cutting out of the Esmeralda from the guns of the Castle of Callao, has always been regarded as one of his most celebrated exploits. In 1823, Lord COCHRANE gave his services, to Brazil, and was appointed by the Emperor to the command of the Brazilian fleet, and created Marquis of Marenham. In 1827 and 1828 he served in Greece. In 1830 he was reinstated in his rank in the British Navy, and in 1847 the Order of the Bath was restored to him. He became Vice-Admiral of the Blue in 1841, of the While in 1851, and Rear-Admiral of the United Kingdom in 1854. Lord COCHRANE was the possessor of various foreign orders of merit and distinction. As a scientific man his reputation stood high, and the projectile which he invented for blowing up fleets, is said to be overwhelmingly destructive. A pamphlet written by the Earl, entitled "Observations on Naval Affairs," attracted considerable attention at the time of its publication. Lord DUNDONALD was engaged, at the time of his death, in writing his personal memoirs. Two volumes have already appeared, and it is to be hoped that the others are sufficiently advanced for publication.

lead_paragraph: Coroner GAFFNEY, of Jersey City, commenced an investigation upon the body of Mrs. JANE ABSOM, wife of WM. ABSOM, market gardener, residing at Communipaw, who died very unexpectedly on Friday morning last. Owing to some family difficulty and alleged threats against the life of deceased, her brother, JOHN BENNETT, applied to the Coroner for an investigation. The Coroner accordingly took charge of the body, and on Saturday a post-mortem examination was made by Dr. QUIDOR, of Jersey City, and Dr. Z.S. BOOTH, the attending physician. Mrs. ABSOM had been in poor health for many months, of a complaint to which females are only subject, but which, in his opinion, would not have caused death in a long time, if ever.

abstract: Ground was  broken, yesterday afternoon, at the corner of Lafayette-avenue and Oxford-street, for a new church edifice for the Park Presbyterian Society, which now worships in a small building on the corner of DeKalb and Carlton avenues.
lead_paragraph: -- Ground was broken, yesterday afternoon, at the corner of Lafayette-avenue and Oxford-street, for a new church edifice for the Park Presbyterian Society, which now worships in a small building on the corner of DeKalb and Carlton avenues. The new church will be of the Romanesque style of architecture, of plain brown stone, with a front of 84 feet on Lafayette-avenue, and extending back 144 feet on Oxford-street. The front tower will be 75 feet high, and the one at the rear 111 feet with a spire reaching 190 feet. The auditorium will be 90 feet by 76, and will be finished in a similar style to Plymouth Church, and will contain 285 pews, with seats for 1,650 grown persons. If necessary, seats for 350 more persons can be added. The lecture-room, which is to be located at the rear of the church, will be 90 by 29 feet. The building complete, it is estimated, will cost $50,000. At the breaking of ground, yesterday, there was a large attendance of people. Rev. Mr. ELMENDORF read a portion of Scripture; Rev. Dr. BUDDINGTON made a prayer; after which, Rev. Mr. CUYLER, the pastor, made an address, and formally commenced the excavation by throwing up a shovel-full of earth.

lead_paragraph: Last evening Street Commissioner SMITH announced to the Board of Aldermen the expiration of his official term, and that he now only awaits the appointment of his successor to hand over the Street Department, with all its books, papers and accounts in good order, to whomsoever shall be appointed by the Mayor and confirmed by the Board of Aldermen in his stead. This is far more of a loss to the City than to the officer who ceases to be her servant; but we have faith that for some weeks to come -- possibly for some months -- the Mayor and Board of Aldermen may fail to come to any mutual understanding as to the person who shall succeed Capt. abstract: Our readers will not fail to be more and more convinced, from the perusal of our dispatches this morning, that the disunion sentiment is rapidly losing ground in the South.
lead_paragraph: Our readers will not fail to be more and more convinced, from the perusal of our dispatches this morning, that the disunion sentiment is rapidly losing ground in the South. The more conservative portion of the population of the Slave States are at last waking up to the necessity of making some movement to stay the tide which might otherwise overwhelm them, and the result is seen in the altered tone of the advices from all quarters. At Henderson, Ky., a mass meeting was held yesterday of men of all parties, at which strong Union speeches were made by Douglas, Breckinridge and Bell men, and resolutions were adopted expressive of the abhorrence felt by all sensible people at the idea of a separation of the States. Arrangements were also made for holding a great mass meeting of the whole country at Louisville at an early day, having the same purposes in view. From Washington, we learn that it is the intention of the Administration to make no move towards coercing South Carolina, excepting in a certain contingency. She will be allowed to take any position she pleases -- to suspend the Courts and to stop all the mails if she will -- but not to interfere with the public revenue or to open a port. The moment this is done a man-of-war will convey a revenue officer to Charleston, to see the laws enforced. It is stated to be the purpose of Virginia to attempt the office of mediator between South Carolina and the Federal Government in case secession actually takes place, and that an effort will be made to effect a rearrangement on a basis which will prove satisfactory to all sections of the country. What the proposed basis is to be maybe gathered from the dispatch of our correspondent.

abstract: -- Prof. CHARLIER had a very large and pleasant gathering of his pupils and their parents at his house in East Twenty-fourth-street on Friday evening. It was in celebration of his wife's birthday, and in accordance with his annual custom. Over a hundred boys were present, and everything went off with great eclat. A distribution of gifts, over four hundred in number, and many of then, very handsome and valuable, by a lottery in which there were no blanks, formed a somewhat noisy but very, agreeable feature of the evening. This was followed by an elegant and bountiful supper. The lads of the school showed their appreciation of their teacher's attentions by the present of a very elegant opera cloak to Mrs. CHARLIER. Prof. CHARLIER is a very successful and popular teacher, and has one of the most flourishing schools in the City.

abstract: From the 4th of March next, the country is to be for four years headed by a Black Republican; and the question now presented to us and to each man in the land, is: What is my duty in this crisis in our national affairs? What does patriotism require of me? How, as a true man, recognizing all my responsibilities as a citizen of the United States, as a citizen of the State of Mississippi, and as a member of society, am I to comport myself? Shall I follow the rash and mad advice which the Governor of this State, forgetting the dignities and solemn trusts of his post as guardian of the safety and rights of the whole State, has, in advance of the actual fact, urged upon the people? Shall I yield to the passionate and inconsiderate teachings of our United States Senators, who, sworn to support the Constitution, have recommended, to the people of Mississippi, in the contingency that is now upon us, to break the bonds imposed by that sacred instrument and put ourselves into a hostile attitude to the Government under which we live, and over which they themselves but yesterday sought earnestly, by the peaceful and lawful method of the ballot-box to place a ruler of their own choice? Shall I, in consequence of the election of Mr. LINCOLN, odious as it is, obnoxious as he is, dangerous as he may be to our rights and mortifying to our pride as the success of his party is, and ultimately disastrous to us as will be their policy if it finally prevail, shall I refuse to submit to his Government, throw off my allegiance to it and raise the standard of rebellion against the constituted authorities?

abstract: We see no reason to change our opinion, expressed yesterday, that the disunion movement in the South is unpopular with the great mass of the people in those States in which it Has been inaugurated, excepting perhaps in South Carolina. Our dispatches, and the numerous newspaper extracts which we give elsewhere, almost all tend to this conclusion. The South Carolina Legislature adjourned yesterday, and the members have retired to their homes. Gov. PETTUS, of Mississippi, has issued a proclamation convening the State Legislature, to consider the propriety and necessity of providing surer and better safeguards for the lives, li berties and property of Mississippians, but he does not, so far as we can gather from the dispatch announcing the fact, say one word about secession. Indeed, it is a significant fact that the first newspaper which reaches us from the State containing the intelligence of LINCOLN'S election has a long article denouncing disunion in the severest terms. We find in the Washington Constitution one of the forms of Declaration of Independence that is to be submitted to the South Carolina Convention. It embodies a portion of the American Declaration of independence, with the list of grievances altered to suit the present condition of 'affairs hi that State. A copy of this, it is understood, has been laid before the President -- of course in a spirit of bravado.

abstract: Amos Robbins and Eli Robbins vs. Henry A. and Stephen D. Dillaye. -- This case has been several times published. The action was brought by the plaintiffs as indorsers and holders of two promissory notes made by the defendant, Stephen D. Dillaye, and indorsed by Henry A. Dillaye. The defence on the trial at the Circuit of the Supreme Court was, first, that the notes were discounted by the Messrs. Lelands, at their Valley Bank, at usurious rates. The defendants testified that they obtained the bills of that bank for the notes, supposing that they were good; but that they were far below par value, and were subsequently offered back to the Lelands, and were refused. The second defence was that the Valley Bank was insolvent at the time the notes were there discounted, and that the Lelands knew such to be the case when paying out their bills for the notes in suit, and that they fraudulently kept the fact from the defendants.

abstract: South Carolina must move by herself, if at all. Such indeed seems to be the prevailing resolve. If the State proceeds to extremes, takes possession of the public buildings and offices, and erects her own independent government, it will certainly create a profound sensation. Not, however, so much on account of the act itself; for that is trivial, and would be heard of with decided gratification by many a National man who has been bored nearly to death with the disunion rockets from that quarter, were it not to be apprehended that more important and conservative States would also be drawn into the measure. Let the country be convinced, the secession movement is not to carry off any State but South Carolina, and the subject would scarcely excite more than curiosity. That State would most likely be permitted to try the experiment without interruption from the General Government, or from any other quarter, and it would no doubt be rather a laughable spectacle. They would be too proud ever to ask to be taken back, but in ten years, a man worth a thousand dollars would be considered rich, if they carried on their government in a style commensurate with their haughty pretensions. The next generation might undo the action of the present, and probably would, as it could be done without inconsistency. But will Georgia go with South Carolina in this thing? If not, there is an end of the danger, be it more or less. Alabama and Mississippi would not join South Carolina, separated by an intervening State of the old Republic, in Georgia there is a strong Union party; so also in Alabama, and we may suppose that a measure so important as secession will not be insisted on by a bare majority in any State. Anything short of an overwhelming majority would not like to take the responsibility of so uncertain an experiment.

abstract: This Board met yesterday, first in the office of the County Clerk, where they were sworn in by Mr. CLANCY, and, having elected Mr. TWEED Chairman, proceeded to their own chamber, where they were resworn by the Chairman. Some confusion was visible at first, but it was quieted by the adoption of a motion to commence with the canvass of the First District of the First Ward, and proceeded regularly through each District of the various Wards, commencing with the Electoral ticket, and going through the entire ticket in regular order.

abstract: Coroner HORTON held an inquest, yesterday, on the body of a child two years old, named WILLIAM HARTUNG, who died on Sunday under suspicious circumstances. The child was taken sick on Thursday, and on Saturday the father applied to a Dr. BERGHAUS, in New York, for medicine, when powders were given, and the child died the following morning. The Doctor, who had never seen the child, gave a certificate that it died from laryngitis, when, in fact, as was ascertained by Drs. BONEY and WILLETTS, death was caused by inflammation of the kidneys. The jury rendered, a verdict in accordance with the above, and censure Dr. BERGHAUS for giving the certificate.

abstract: -- The Portland Argus sums up a case recently argued in that city in the following curt style: "Freeman Waterhouse, libelant, vs. Eliza A. Waterhouse -- Petition for divorce -- cause, desertion. From the evidence in the case, it appeared that the wife was an 'exceedingly pious' woman, and that she left her husband on account of his profanity. Judge Appleton said she should show her piety in a becoming manner by returning to her husband; that she had no excuse for leaving him, and that if she continued to desert him after this nothing could be recovered of him for her support. The circumstances in the case were not sufficient, in his mind, to warrant him in decreeing a divorce. Libel dismissed."

abstract: MR. RAREY's FAREWELL TO ENGLAND. -- On Saturday, Oct. 27, the great American horse-lamer, took final leave of his English friends at the Crystal Palace at Sydenham. The exhibition presented no feature of novelty, beyond the fact of its being a leave-taking, and the numerous audience which it attracted. The whole of the immense Handel Orchestra was crammed to the roof, and presented a most imposing appearance. The same may be said of every portion of the transept that was not railed off as an arona, whilst the first, second, and even third galleries, exhibited each its dense and eager rows of human faces. The Russian Ambassador and a numerous suite, occupied the Queen's gallery, and there were also scattered amongst the lower crowd an exceedingly numerous and conspicuous sprinkling of Orientals, Mr. RAREY began with Cruiser, who is now a model of docility and patience. Like Col. Crockett's squirrels, he comes down without the trouble of firing. He bends his knee for the strap, and falls, with case, if not with dignity, the moment it becomes his cue to do so. He looked thin on Saturday, and his coat was rough, but neither of those symptoms is uncommon with horses at this season of the year. Cruiser, who is now the property of Mr. RAREY, goes with him to America, to assist in disseminating the new philosophy of horse-taming. After him came a chestnut, which was, if possible, still more docile; but here the harmony of the arena terminated. When the chestnut had been duly hobbled, tumbled, and otherwise done for, the whole transept suddenly became vocal with the unearthly screams of the Irish mare, who was about to receive her first initiation into the restraints of a civilized manege. This animal and another horse of fierce disposition were brought into subjection, and then Mr. RAREY delivered his farewell, in a few simple, manly words, full of friendly regrets and good feeling. He acknowledged the unfailing kindness he had always received from the people of England, and the fair hearing which had been given to his rather novel theories. He hoped he had done some good in the cause of humanity, by pleading as he had done the cause of our best friend, the horse, and by showing, to the best of his humble ability, the means by which its usefulness might be preserved without those protracted and brutal systems of training which at present caused cruel and needless suffering. He (Mr. RAREY) was about leaving England, perhaps forever; but he should to his last moment retain a grateful recollection of the friends he had made and the kindness he had received during his rather protracted sojourn in the old country. This address was vehemently cheered, and its delivery brought the interesting farewell performance to a successful termination.

abstract: Two bids were opened yesterday at this office -- one for a sewer in Fifty fifth-street, between Third and Fourth avenues, which was awarded to Thomas Crimmins, at $5,602 45; the other for a sewer in Lewis-street, between Stanton and Hester streets, was awarded to Matthew Murray, at $1,378 50. As neither of these works can be carried to completion during the present season, the award of contract is a mere formality, and only made in compliance with the requirements of the Charter.

abstract: For a week past attention had been attracted to a schooner loading at one of the North River Piers, the character of her cargo being strongly suggestive of a slave voyage. On Monday, everything being ready, the vessel left her Pier, No. 5 North River, and came to anchor near Bedloe's Island, preparatory to leaving port, when Capt. FAUNCE, of the Revenue-cutter Harriet Lane, sent a portion of his crew on board under the direction of Surveyor HART, and took charge of the vessel, and had her towed to the Atlantic Dock, where she was placed in charge of a Government officer. Her cargo will be overhauled at an early day, when demonstrative proof, it is anticipated, will appear, of the intended illegal character of the voyage. Her destination, according to the statement of the officers and crew, was the West Coast of Africa. The schooner's name is the William L. Cogswell, formerly commanded by H.W. PENNY, 270 tons register, and owned by J.W. SMITH, of Northport, L.I. The captain asserted that he was bound on a trading voyage to the Coast.

abstract: The short supply last week, the apparently moderate receipts of cattle this week, together with a cool but pleasant day, made the cattle trade very lively yesterday. Although Wednesday is the cattle market-day of the week, by general agreement, yet about 2,500 of the 3,700 cattle yarded at Forty-fourth-street, were fold out yesterday, leaving only 1,200 for to-day's transactions. Additional droves, however, were expected in during the night, and the prospect is that there will be enough for all who have not yet purchased. The sales average about 1/4c. lb., net, below the average rates last week, good cattle selling at about the same figures, while poorer 1/2c. lower. Some premium catlte were ofered -- a novelty of late -- which were readily disposed of at 10c. lb. Prime beef brought 9c., and medium 8c., while very little went below 7c. A very large portion of the stock was in the hands of brokers who had bought at Buffalo and Albany, and on this account they were held pretty firmly. Sales were large at Bergen Hill on Monday.

abstract: In consequence of the entire safety of the Caloric Engine, the erection of one in any building does not effect the rate of insurance. A steam-engine raises the rate from two per cent. to a figure that amounts to an absolute prohibition. The saving on insurance will go far in a twelvemonth towards paying for a Caloric Engine in buildings where there is but a moderate amount of property.

abstract: -Judge PIERREPONT, having resigned his place upon the Bench, has returned to his old office, and formed a business connection with Messrs. abstract: -One of our Harrisburgh exchanges says: "Sheriff EYSTER levied upon all the property and rolling stock of the Pennsylvania Railroad Company to be found in this city on two executions, amounting in the aggregate to $163,454, issued at the instance of the Attorney-General, for tonnage-tax due the State, which the Company refuses to pay. The case was tried before Judge PEARSON, last Summer, and judgment given against the Company for the above amount. An appeal was taken to the Supreme Court and the judgment affirmed by that tribunal. We presume arrangements will be made to satisfy the Commonwealth and stop further proceedings."

lead_paragraph: In this Court, yesterday, fifty-one cases were disposed of as follows: Of twenty persons charged with assault and battery, four were discharged on account of non-appearance of witnesses against them, two were discharged by request of complainant, four were discharged under suspended judgment, one was remanded for sentence, two were fined, and seven were imprisoned. Of twenty-five persons charged with petty larceny, one was discharged because no witness appeared against him, two were discharged because no witness appeared against him, two were discharged by request of complainant, two were discharged under suspended judgment, five were acquitted, seven were remanded for sentence, and eight were imprisoned. One person convicted of malicious mischief was imprisoned. Five cases of illegal voting or registering were disposed of as follows: In the case of Thomas Trainor it appeared that the prisoner had been taken out of custody on a writ of habeas corpus. Henry Wilson did not appear when his case was called, and it was therefore postponed, his bail forfeited, and an attachment issued against him. John B. Jackson, whose trial we reported on Monday last, was sentenced one month to the Penitentiary. James Scoles, whose trial we also reported at the same time, received the same sentence. John Bryant, tried at the same time, and remanded until to-day for decision, was acquitted.
