lead_paragraph: -- In a letter recently addressed to Mr. JELLINGHAUS, President of the German Emigrant Protective Association, in reference to the extraordinary decision made by Judge RUSSELL in the emigrant-swindling cases of WARD and GILBERT, the District Attorney gave notice that he did not agree with the learned and eloquent Judge in his view of the statute passed last Winter to restrain this particular species of offence; and also that he would take the earliest opportunity to have that decision reviewed in some Court of higher character, and less liable to local influences than the Court of General Sessions.

abstract: The Comptroller has for some time been preparing his Budget for 1861. He still lacks the estimates from one Department, although it should have been sent in on the 1st of November. This delay arises from the neglect in the Mayor's office to send in the estimates of probable expenses for that important Department. It is not impossible that the Harlem Bridge expenses may have something to do with this delay, but certain it is that the financial budget of the City for 1861 is kept buck because the head of the City Government has not responded in due season to the calls made upon him for information as to the sum necessary for its support, which every other Department has long since presented.

abstract: -- The Comptroller, yesterday, had an interview with Messrs. BACHE and BLUNT, Pilot Commissioners, accompanied by their counsel, W.A. BUTLER, Esq., with reference to the encroachments of the mighty "Commodore" upon the harbor. It was decided that, for the present, the Pilot Commissioners, backed by the State, should do the legal fighting, (which has been commenced,) and that when occasion demanded the Comptroller should step in and assert the rights of the City. Mr. VANDERBILT, nothing daunted by the threats of injunctions, fines and prosecutions, resumed the work on his pier yesterday, and he will probably pay little heed to Courts or injunctions, but will build his pier, and secure official sancticn hereafter, and thus purchase exemption from all pains and penalties.

abstract: The most embarrassing duty which devolves upon the administrators of the Federal Government, results from the enforcement of the law for the return of "fugitives from labor." There are those who, by a strict and literal construction of the Constitution, pretend to deny that the clause providing for this object, refers to negro slaves; and much ingenuity has been expended in the maintenance of this evasive proposition.
lead_paragraph: The most embarrassing duty which devolves upon the administrators of the Federal Government, results from the enforcement of the law for the return of "fugitives from labor." There are those who, by a strict and literal construction of the Constitution, pretend to deny that the clause providing for this object, refers to negro slaves; and much ingenuity has been expended in the maintenance of this evasive proposition. But the great body of the American people, of all parties, accept the clause in question, in good faith, and insist that it devolves upon the Federal Government, or else upon the States, the duty of surrendering to their owners slaves who may run away from their service, and seek shelter in any of the States of the Union. The Southern States demand the rigid enforcement of this provision of the Constitution as an essential condition of Union. The free States admit the legal obligation, but the moral sense of their people revolts at its fulfillment, and it is easier to rally the posse comitatus in resistance to the law, than in aid of the Federal officers whose duty it is to execute it.

abstract: About two weeks ago, in the day-time, an aged man named Samuel Robinson, residing, at No. 192 West Thirty-first-street, stopped at an oyster-stand at the corner of West Broadway and Thames-street, and partook of a stew, after which he emptied his pockets of a quantity of silver change and undertook to count it. This action on his part was observed by two degraded fellows, one a while man named Wm. Sickles, and the other a colored person, known only as "Charley." who fell upon him with clubs, and having knocked him down, stole his money and escaped. The old gentleman, as soon as he was able, went home, and his injuries prevented him from informing the Police of the matter until Monday last. A description of both the highwaymen was then obtained from the keeper of the oyster-stand, and it resulted in the arrest of Sickles, who has been fully identified by the complainant. Justice WELSH yesterday committed him for trial in default of $1,000 bail. The negro, Charley, will probably be apprehended to-day.

lead_paragraph: Since the beginning of the present month there have been arraigned in the Special Sessions one hundred and six persons charged with the commission of assault and battery. Of these, thirty-five, or one-third, have been discharged, either by the request of complainants or their non-attendance as witnesses. At the common law, as every one is aware, a criminal prosecution cannot be instituted by a private individual Since the beginning of the present month there have been arraigned in the Special Sessions one hundred and six persons charged with the commission of assault and battery. Of these, thirty-five, or one-third, have been discharged, either by the request of complainants or their non-attendance as witnesses. At the common law, as every one is aware, a criminal prosecution cannot be instituted by a private individual, but only by the people. Private indemnity for injury sustained can be recovered only by suit in a civil Court. Though the statutes do not expressly abrogate this ancient and well-established principle of law, they have yet rendered it in some respects an utter absurdity. For while the people remain the party to a suit against a criminal, it is difficult to understand how a private individual can withdraw or compromise it. Yet the exercise of such a right derives its sanction from a statute now in force; and a prosecution brought for the vindication of the public justice, and public safety, may be arrested whenever the assailant shall be able to buy or bully or coax his accuser from his design.

lead_paragraph: An enterprising citizen of the First Ward, named JOHN E. ENRIGHT, has long attracted public attention by his bold and successful manoeuvres for the acquisition of property not his own, and the fury of his attacks upon whomsoever should be rash enough to attempt interrupting his "business." Again and again, month after month, and year after year, has he been paraded before the public as a professional emigrant swindler, a professional ticket swindler, and on incidental charges of assaults and batteries of every kind. So great, indeed, has been his fame in these accomplishments, that our worthy Mayor -- ever vigilant to foster, the seeds of democratic virtue -- not many months ago procured the appointment of this distinguished First Warder to a sinecure position under the City Inspector, with a salary attached thereto of twelve hundred dollars a year.

abstract: The Newark Mercury of yesterday announces that four Lincoln electors have been chosen in New-Jersey. Messrs. BREWER and WURTS, Bell and Breckinridge electors on the Fusion ticket, are beaten badly, the former by 1,123, and the latter by 1,470 plurality. The defeat of Messrs. VROOM and CONDIT is not certain, although the figures show that they lack 397 of the votes necessary to insure their election. So that New-Jersey will probably give four votes for LINCOLN and three for DOUGLAS.

abstract: -- There was a final hearing yesterday, before Alderman OGLE, in the case of R.H. LITTLE, charged with selling goods by sample, without a license. The accused was the agent for the New-York firm of JAMES HOULDWORTH & CO. There are four separate charges against him, the penalty in each of which is $300. The sale of the goods was not denied, but the defence was, that Messrs. HOULDWORTH & CO. had a place of business in Philadelphia, and that the sales were made under a mercantile tax license. The manufacturer, or other person not having his principal place of business within the State, to whom a license has not been granted." A license is only granted for a year, and the amount to be paid is $300. One half the penalty of $300 goes to the informer. Detective BARTHOLOMEW is the informer in the case referred to. Alderman OGLE will give his decision in a few days. -- Philadelphia Ledger, Nov. 13.

abstract: Some facts in regard to a seduction have come to our knowledge, which may be of interest to our readers. A few months ago, a traveling agent for one of the heavy dry-goods merchants in New-York City formed the acquaintance of the only daughter of one of the New-York bankers. The lady was young, accomplished, beautiful, but too susceptible. The traveling agent was smitten, as he avowed; took his "ladye-love" to the Opera, the theatre, and Japanese ball, and finally proposed an elopement. The lady objected, but, like many others, consented at last, and one evening, leaving the paternal roof with her lover, under the pretence of attending one of the theatres, they took the cars, and continuing their journey without delay, arrived in Detroit on the 14th of last month. Instead of going, as the lady desired, direct to a clergyman, to have the matrimonial knot tied, the seducer took his victim to a house in which he declared a relative of his resided, and there the ruin of the girl was consummated under promise of marriage. For nearly two weeks the young girl plead, but in vain, that her seducer should marry her, but he being relentless, she wrote to her parents, and on the morning of election day they both arrived, and, seeking the lost one, found her, and without a word of reproach took her to their arms and forgave her all. The next thing was to find the seducer, but he having heard of the arrival, fled, and has not since been seen in this vicinity. On Wednesday morning the reunited trio departed for New-York, and ere this the deceived but contrite girl is again surrounded by home influences. -- Detroit Tribune, Nov. 10.

abstract: -- REVIEW BY THE MAYOR. -- Company F National Guard, of Boston, Capt. JOHN F. HYDE, which has been on a visit to this City for the past three days, as the guests of the Eighth Regiment, was reviewed by the Mayor yesterday afternoon in the Park. The Company was escorted to the Park by Company B of the Eighth Regiment. The Mayor was accompanied in the review by Gen. BULLOCK, Quartermaster MORAN, and Major BEN PERLEY POORE, all of Boston. At the close of the review Capt. MOORE, of Company B. introduced Capt. HYDE to the Mayor, who expressed his gratification in being able to welcome a Boston Company to the City, and complimented the Captain upon the fine appearance of the men under his command. After going through with a variety of evolutions the Boston guests were escorted back to the Armory of the Eighth-Regiment. The National Guard returned home last night by the New-Haven steamer, being escorted thereto by the whole of the Eighth Regiment.

abstract: Hon. H.C. GOODWIN died at Hamilton, Madison county, on Monday night Mr. GOODWIN was born in De Ruyter on the 25th of June, 1824. He received an academic education, and was admitted to the bar in 1846. In 1847, he was elected District Attorney of Madison county, which post he held three years. He was elected as Representative from New-York to the second session of the Thirty-third Congress, and was reelected to the Thirty-fifth, serving as a member of the Committee on Claims.

abstract: -- On Monday afternoon, Mr. WILLIAM DAVIS, of No. 1,021 Broadway, was riding on the Bloomingdale road in a light wagon, accompanied by Miss WHITE, a lady acquaintance, and when near Fifty-ninth-street, an omnibus came into collision with the vehicle with such force as to smash it. Mr. DAVIS, consequently, was thrown violently to the ground, and received injuries of a dangerous character. Miss WHITE escaped with severe bruises. Persons witnessing the occurrence agreed in stating that it was intentionally brought about by WILLIAM BURNS, the driver of the stage, who, having been arrested, was yesterday taken before Justice QUACKENBUSH and commited for examination .... HENRY SHEFFIELD, driver of stage No. 111, of the Fourth-avenue line, while intoxicated on Monday evening, drove his vehicle recklessly through Broadway. Opposite Barnum's Museum he ran into a party consisting of Mr. SEBASTIAN MECKEL, his wife and son, and Miss NETTIE KLAYROTH, his wife's sister, visitors from Albany, who had witnessed the performances and were crossing over to the Astor House, where they boarded. Mrs. MECKEL's arm was broken above the elbow, and two fingers of Miss KLAYROTH's left hand were crushed. Officer CAIRNES, of the First Ward, arrested SHEFFIELD, and Justice WELSH held him to answer.

abstract: JAMES COLLYER, a farmer residing near the Cyprets Hills Plank Road, about one and a half miles east of East New-York, in New-Lotts, Queens County, was found dead in his own barn at an early hour yesterday morning, with his skull badly fractured, and there were other evidences that a murder had been committed. The deceased took a wagon-load of produce to the New-York market Monday afternoon, and returned home at about 6 o'clock in the evening, with between $100 and $200 in his pocket. Soon after supper he went to the store of Mr. J. TIERNEY, in the vicinity, where he transacted some business, had a pitcher filled with beer, and left for his stable. He paid a bill at the store, and, while doing this, exposed considerable money, when a man present remarked, "COLLFER, you are flush to-night." This attracted the particular attention of two German laborers present, -- father and son -- and it is said that they stepped forward and looked at the money. As soon as Mr. COLLYER left the store, the two Germans went out also, and as this was the last seen of Mr. COLLYER alive, it was at first supposed that the Germans had committed the murder. Detectives FROST and DENTON, of Brooklyn, yesterday afternoon arrested the two Germans in Williamsburgh, on suspicion, and committed them to the cells of the First Precinct Station-house; but the officers do not believe that they participated in the murder. They gave their names as JAMES and HENRY SPRATT. Late Monday evening. Mrs. COLLYER, the wife of deceased, feeling envious at me long absence of her husband, went to her door and looked towards the barn, which is about two hundred yards distant from the house, but seeing no light concluded that he had been detained at the store, and she retired for the night. She was much surprised at not finding her husband at home in the morning, and immediately went to the barn to ascertain if his team was there. The first object that attracted her attention upon entering the barn -- the doors of which were wide open -- was the dead body of her husband lying in a pool of blood. Her shrieks brought to her side several inmates of the house, and she was removed in a swoon to the house. The alarm was at once given, and the Coroner of Queens County (Mr. WOOD) was soon there. Upon examining the body, it was found that the skull was badly fractured -- evidently by a blunt instrument, such as the head of an axe, or something of that kind. His pockets were turned inside out, and all of his money and a gold watch were gone. The book attached to the chain of the watch was still remaining in the buttonhole of his vest, the murderes, in their hurry, evidently having broken the chain. A straw knife lying near the body, was besmeared with blond, and as the wound on the head, could not have been made with this instrument, it is supposed that deceased made a desperate resistance to the murderers before they accomplished their purpose.

abstract: The first impulse of thousands of good and true citizens of the South doubtless is to resist, in some decisive form, the accession to power of the head of the party which stands in an attitude of avowed hostility and offensive menace to the constitutional rights of the Slave States. Sensitive and chivalric, they see little difference between the utterances of a warm political contest, and the practical direction of legislation and the direct use of executive power to accomplish all of the revolution in the policy of the Government foreshadowed by the factious apostles of Republicanism.

abstract: A meeting of the Independent Democratic General Committee, composed of delegates from all the Wards of the City, met last evening at Military Hall, No. 195 Bowery, for the purpose of making nominations for the coming Charter election. Mr. J. ROSENBOURGH was President of the meeting, and Mr. MYER MASTEN officiated as Secretary. The President, in stating the objects of the meeting, adverted to the heavy vote given to the nominees of the Committee at the recent election as a proof of its power and influence. Mr. H. DAVIES denied the statement of several newspapers that this was a "Hebrew German Democratic Committee." It was, he stated, a Committee of Democrats acting together as citizens of New-York without regard to sect or nationality, having for their object solely the good of the people. He also alluded to the force they possessed in all the Wards of the City. The nomination of officers for the Charter election was then gone into.

abstract: The five-score young women, each of whom was defrauded of $5 by putting confidence in the promise of "Professor" Samuel W. Downing to teach them a process of transferring photographs and lithographs to oil-paintings on glass, will be gratified to learn that their deceiver is under arrest. It has transpired that Downing left the City on Sunday evening last for Boston, but his departure was so hurried that he forgot a portion of his property, consisting of clothing and papers. With the object of obtaining it, he yesterday returned to his former quarters, No. 54 East Broadway, not knowing at the time that an exposure of his swindling transactions had been thoroughly made in all the daily papers. His presence there was made known to Officer Eagleston, of the Seventh Precinct, who took him into custody, and Justice BRENNAN committed the accused for examination.

abstract: THE SUPPOSED WIFE POISONING CASE. -- The inquest upon the body of Mrs. JANE ABSOM, whose death is thought to have been caused by poisoning, was continued yesterday, at the Bull's Head Hotel, in Communipaw. Miss JULIA ANN KENNEDY was the only witness called. She had been a servant in the house, and Mr. ABSOM, it had been charged, had been over-attentive to her. She testified that she had lived in the family as a servant, and had never known Mr. ABSOM to treat his wife harshly, while she was in his employ. When the inquest had been adjourned for the day, JULIA was held as a witness when wanted.

abstract: From the National Capital, the intelligence Reaches us that a decidedly better feeling prevails in reference to the excitement in the South, the dispatches received there warranting the belief that the comparative calmness which will follow the first ebullition of feeling will bring with it a corresponding caution, which must prevent the commission of any act which would tend to precipitate disunion. Our dispatches from various points this morning will tend to confirm this view.
lead_paragraph: From the National Capital, the intelligence Reaches us that a decidedly better feeling prevails in reference to the excitement in the South, the dispatches received there warranting the belief that the comparative calmness which will follow the first ebullition of feeling will bring with it a corresponding caution, which must prevent the commission of any act which would tend to precipitate disunion. Our dispatches from various points this morning will tend to confirm this view. The last intemperate harangue of Mr. KEITT, the apostle of South Carolina Disunionism, is bearing its legitimate fruits, in "giving pause" to honest men. His assertion that President BUCHANAN is pledged to uphold secession, it will be seen, is flatly denied. Virginia is moving in the right direction. A grand mass meeting of all those opposed to disunion, without distinction of party, is to be held at Staunton, on Saturday, in which prominent men will take part. We publish an extract of a private letter from Mr. BOTTS to a gentleman in this City, in which he takes occasion to refute some of the ridiculous stories which have been put in circulation, in reference to the feeling in the Old Dominion.

abstract: The benevolent are appealed to on behalf of an old lady who is living friendless and alone, and in circumstances of great destitution, at No. 72 Sullivan-street. Mrs. HART, the lady referred to, is about eighty years of age. She has hitherto contrived to eke out a support for herself by doing ladies' fine needlework, but this employment now so greatly taxes her eye-sight and strength that she cannot earn sufficient to pay her basement rent, much less to provide the most scanty food. Our reporter, who visited the place yesterday to inquire into the case, found her without a morsel of food, save the remnants of a few cold potatoes from which she had subsisted for two days. She is a very intelligent and lady-like person, whose manner and coversation show that she must have seen far better days. Those who feel prompted to assist this worthy old lady, can do so by calling at her place in Sullivan-street, or by sending donations for her to this office.

abstract: In this Court, before Judge GOULD yesterday, the case of James Enright, indicted for ticket-swindling, was first called. Counsel for defence asked a postponement of the trial, on the ground that "one of the most influential public journals in this City had that morning published, no doubt with the best intentions, an article under the title of "Three Noble Brothers," of such a character as to make it impossible for his client to have a fair trial in the same community in which such an article was published on the morning of trial." The paper in question was proffered to the Judge, who retained it for perusal. He add that the publication of the article would not be a sufficient ground for postponement, but its perusal by a juror might be good ground for a challenge. The case must, therefore, be proceeded with.

lead_paragraph: We have received, by the last two mails from Panama, full particulars of the late unpleasant misunderstanding between the American and English Naval Commanders on the station, and are now able to form an opinion of the merits of the dispute. Our readers already know that the town of Panama was threatened, some weeks ago, with a repetition of the terrible massacre of 1856, and that, to avert the danger, a large force of British and American seamen and marines was landed from the ships-of-war in the harbor. So far, so good; for, in a time of such imminent peril, and in a country where the Government is notoriously unable to preserve order, American citizens would be as thankful for British protection as for the protection of their own flag. At any rate, the intervention was timely, as by its means the outbreak was checked.

abstract: -- The chivalrous KEITT is reported as inviting his constituents to fling their arms around the pillars of the Federal temple, and bring universal ruin upon the country. Mr. KEITT obviously borrows his metaphor from the story of Samson, and discovers analogies between the temple of Liberty and that of Dagon. But KEITT is hardly strong enough to bear away the gates of Gaza; and South Carolina is not by very long odds the Holy Land. The only thing fairly common in the parallel is the blindness of the two destroyers, in which perhaps the modern rather exceeds the scriptural hero. But the blindness of the Hebrew without his strength would never have worked the miracle; a fact that in the prevalent obscuration may have been lost sight of. It is nevertheless important.

abstract: -- The first person excluded from South Carolina, in its present non-intercourse temper, is a schoolmaster. Mr. WM.C. WOODS, of Maschusetts, had repaired to Charleston to fill a pedagogical engagement in the Barnwell District, but with that keen scent for men of his sort, which distinguishes the owners of souls, his mission was detected, and with astonishing lenity, considering the gravity of his contemplated offence, Mr. WOODS was merely returned to Boston by the following steamer. It is, indeed, high time that some check should be put upon the incendiary attempts of Massachusetts to enlighten those who sit in the shadow of the palmetto. From the time Commissioner HOARE was gently dismissed by the chivalry, notwithstanding the subversive nature of his errand, to this moment, more or less activity has existed upon that track of the underground railroad, which returns to the South in exchange for its runaway negros, fugitive school-masters from New-England. What the teaching and example of these men have bean, may be seen from a glance at the present attitude of the northern-most Slave States, who instead of sustaining South Carolina in its daring and defiant posture, disclose a painful willingness to wait and make sure what there is to dare, and what to defy. Such are not wanted in South Carolina. The demand is for drill-sergeants and tacticians, of which New-England is a tardy leader.

abstract: Private letters have been received in this City from the Secretary of War, announcing practically his acceptance, as a constitutional necessity, of the result of the late Presidential struggle; and stating that he would regard all attempts to dissolve the Union on account of Mr. LINCOLN's election, as measures, both premature in their time of initiation and only tending to throw discredit on those who would impeach and convict, in advance, a candidate who has received the suffrages of States representing a majority in the Electoral College of the United States. Gov. FLOYD's assurances are of the most decisive character, -- being accompanied by his declaration of a purpose to do everything in his power to prevent the success of disunion schemes.

abstract: Thomas Reilly vs. Chas. G. Cornell, Frederick Johnson and James McMann. -- The trial of this action now came on before Justice MONCRIEF at Special Term of the Superior Court. The particulars of the case were given in the TIMES of 23d March last, at which date it was before the Court, at Special Term, on a motion for an injunction against the defendants. The plaintiff was the owner of the property known as Hermitage Hall, situated on the corner of Houston and Allen streets, which is estimated to be worth $25,000. The defendant, Gornell, who was the late President of the Board of Aldermen, now holds an instrument which he claims is a deed of the property in question, pursuant to a purchase from a referee in a foreclosure suit. The plaintiff sets forth his case in a lengthy complaint, showing that, in March last, this property was sold under a foreclosure of mortgage thereon, and that by an agreement with the parties, he was to have the fight of redemption. He subsequently obtained a loan from the defendants. Cornell and Johnson, of $5,600, with which to discharge he foreclosure decree. As security for such loan, and security only, he alleges that he gave these gentlemen a transfer of the bid upon the sale of the Hall, and a deed absolute from the Referee, which they agreed by parole to hold as a mortgage only. The plaintiff avers that in September, 1859, he paid the defendants $446, as "interest, &c.," on said advance, and took a receipt therefor from their attorney -- $196 being interest, and $250 a shave, or bonus. At the expiration of three months he avers that he paid $99 as an additional installment of interest. It is then alleged that the defendant, Cornell, transferred the property to his father-in-law, and procured a resolution to be passed by the Common Council, directing the Comptroller to take a lease of the property, at a rental of $1,500 per annum, to be used as a Court-room. Plaintiff, in conclusion of this series of extraordinary charges, avers that he has since tendered the defendants the entire loan, with interest, which has been declined by them, they claiming absolute title, under the Referee's deed. He asks that the deed may be declared to be a mortgage only, and that the defendants be compelled to accept of the necessary sum to cancel the same.

At the expiration of three months he avers that he paid $99 as an additional installment of interest. It is then alleged that the defendant, Cornell, transferred the property to his father-in-law, and procured a resolution to be passed by the Common Council, directing the Comptroller to take a lease of the property, at a rental of $1,500 per annum, to be used as a Court-room. Plaintiff, in conclusion of this series of extraordinary charges, avers that he has since tendered the defendants the entire loan, with interest, which has been declined by them, they claiming absolute title, under the Referee's deed. He asks that the deed may be declared to be a mortgage only, and that the defendants be compelled to accept of the necessary sum to cancel the same.

abstract: The mother of ALEXANDER II. deserves a place among the noblest maternal heroines of history. She has rescued her son from a great peril, at the expense of her own comfort; for an Emperor cannot afford to become ridiculous, and the position of the Czar at Warsaw, in the company of the Prince Regent of Prussia and of the Emperor of Austria, was fast verging upon the absurd, when the Dowager Empress of Russia threw herself upon her sick-bed,telegraphed to her Imperial child that her life was in danger, and broke up the preposterous conference, into which he had so weakly suffered himself to be seduced. We all of us, alas, know what it is to meet by accident at the corner of the street somebody whom we know very well, for whom we care very little, with whom we have no sort of relations to maintain, and to whom consequently we have nothing in the world to say. The first moment of the collision passes off well enough. We shake hands, smile, are delighted to see one another, charmed or disgusted as the case may be with the weather, and each having just read the same newspaper, ardently inquire of each other as to the news of the day. Then comes a fearful pause. Each burns to escape; neither wishes to reveal his flame. We stand, and smile, and babble incoherent nonsense. In that supreme instant a hodman, carrying bricks to the top of a neighboring house, considerately drops from his ladder and is dashed to pieces at our feet, or a horse takes fright in a primitive van, and rushes, with a chaos of wheels, behind him, through a druggist's window. We are shocked at the calamity, but under cover of its friendly tumult our demon drops us; we shake hands once more, and slip relieved away, each about his own business. The Empress-Dowager of Russia has been the falling hodman and the runaway horse of the embarrassed Emperors at Warsaw.

abstract: Kansas has been as sedulously kept in the background during the Lincoln-Fusion campaign as it was prominently placed in the foreground during the last Presidential struggle. In the present campaign, questions of more tremendous import, affecting the integrity, if not the existence, of free constitutional government, have entirely overborne the murmurs of our hapless trans-Missourian sister, whose faintest shriek formerly reverberated.
lead_paragraph: Kansas has been as sedulously kept in the background during the Lincoln-Fusion campaign as it was prominently placed in the foreground during the last Presidential struggle. In the present campaign, questions of more tremendous import, affecting the integrity, if not the existence, of free constitutional government, have entirely overborne the murmurs of our hapless trans-Missourian sister, whose faintest shriek formerly reverberated throughout the Republic. But the political condition of Kansas at the present time, and during the past four years, furnishes a very forcible comment on the misconduct of the Administration. From 1856 till the present time Kansas has been in a chronic state of disaffection towards it, -- as virulent as its causes were outrageous. The feelings of her settlers toward Mr. BUCHANAN are those of positive personal hatred, and that, too, of an intensity that could have been produced only by long-continued injustice. They bear no resemblance in their nature to the disapproval of his general policy which is so universal in the Free States, nor to the chagrin of his life-long friends whom, when in power, he has forsaken and maligned, nor even to the somewhat intense enmity of the Forney and Saunders type; they are more akin to the feeling which PERIO and his compatriots maybe supposed to entertain for BOMBALINO, than anything for which the history of this country furnishes a parallel.

abstract: In the course or an article reviewing and condemning the course of the Breckinridge Democrats in the recent contest, the Mobile Register says its main purpose is to "warn the people against the effort surely to be made by the leaders of the Yancey school, of using the Breckinridge Party as the instrument for 'precipitating,' without consulting, the people of these States into a revolution. Comprising the majority of the professional politicians, this party, of course, has a majority in most of the Legislatures of the Southern States, and it is by acts of the several Legislatures and by individual acts that it is attempted to commit us, whether we will or not, in a manner which will array Southern pride and Southern patriotism against Southern judgment, well knowing that with our people that pride must and will overrule mere interest, just as a man will defend a friend for an act which in itself he disapproves. The slightest spark once thrown into a powder magazine, it is too late to talk of prudence and precautionary measures. Let, therefore, every true Alabamian insist on the calling of the Convention, for which the Legislature, in the exercise of its lawful powers, has provided. It is rumored that the Legislature will be convened to absolve the Governor from the necessity of calling that Convention, and will then proceed to take measures to place the State in an attitude of irreconcilable hostility. This timely exposure of the plot may serve to nip it in the bud. Let the Convention be called, let the questions involved in our future action be thoroughly discussed before the people, and then let every true man obey the will of the people in this their sovereign capacity, under penalty of being treated as a traitor to the land which gave him birth or shelter. We are not children to be 'precipitated,' but men who can and will resolve on a course in which to persist, come weal, come woe."

abstract: -- It is announced that the Burgesses Corps, of Albany, have resolved to attend LINCOLN's inauguration at Washington in their military capacity. We hope they will change their purpose. It has never been usual for organized bodies of this kind to take any part in the inauguration ceremonies, and the proclamation of such a purpose now can have no other effect than to exasperate the South and increase the sectional feeling which is already much too strong. If the members of this Corps desire to be present on the occasion, let them go as individual citizens, -- as civilians, and not as a military organization. No plan could be devised better calculated to lead to collision and strife than the gathering of such companies from different sections of the country. There is an implied menace in the announcement of their intention to go, which is wholly needless and mischievous. It is the duty of every Northern man to allay, rather than increase the existing excitement; and we trust that, upon reflection, the Burgesses Corps of Albany will see the propriety of doing nothing that shall augment the hostility which is likely to greet the incoming Administration.

abstract: It may  be well to anticipate the clamor which the recent negro escapade at Chicago will provoke among declared Disunionists, by having it distinctly understood that the fugitive involved had not escaped from any Slave State; but that she came from the Territory of Nebraska. While the constitutional obligation to return a slave who has fled from "a State" is accepted by the great body of Northern people, there is discovered neither constitutional...
lead_paragraph: It may be well to anticipate the clamor which the recent negro escapade at Chicago will provoke among declared Disunionists, by having it distinctly understood that the fugitive involved had not escaped from any Slave State; but that she came from the Territory of Nebraska. While the constitutional obligation to return a slave who has fled from "a State" is accepted by the great body of Northern people, there is discovered neither constitutional or legal requirement for returning a slave who has fled from a Territory -- and especially a Territory where Slavery has only an exceptional existence, without any claim to satisfying a popular want, or prevailing as a popular institution. And if there be one point upon which Northern sentiment is well settled, it is in regarding Slavery as the creature of local law, in the absence of which it can have no legal being; and Slavery, it is needles to say, has never been established by law in Nebraska. The distinction is not unnecessary; for in the dearth of any rational apprehension of the order of things to be established next year, this occurrence, following so soon after a Republican victory, may be absurdly and mischievously misinterpreted by the indifferently provided casuists of secession. The simple fact is, a negro held to service without warrant of law in a Territory escaping, there can be no warrant of law to recover him, where Slavery is positively illegal.

abstract: The City Hall was alive yesterday with rumors relative to the removal of Street Commissioner SMITH and the appointment of HENRY WOOD in his place. The friends of JOHN R. BRIGGS have not given up all hope for him yet, as it is all but certain that the Aldermen would confirm his name, if it were sent in; whereas they will require a very great deal of manipulation before doing the same thing for the Mayor's brother. Alderman BOOLE thinks that such close relationship between the Mayor and Street Commissioner might be detrimental to the public interests, and a majority of his fellows in the Board are of the same way of thinking. They are not willing to subject their party to such a storm of odium as was aroused by the DEVLIN administration, merely for the benefit of a single family. They say that with Mr. BEN. WOOD in Congress, and Mr. F. WOOD Mayor, an effort should be made between them not to centre the whole balance of City patronage round their domestic hearth-stone.

abstract: At 5 o'clock last evening, a fire, the origin of which is unknown, broke out in the paper box manufactory of LEGRAND SCHWAB, on the second floor of No. 23 Cedar-street, and communicating to the third floor, occupied by the same party, caused damage to the extent of $700. Said to be insured. The first floor was used as a salesroom by the Gutta Percha Roofing Company. Loss $100. Damage was done to the building to the amount of $300. Some cotton batting in the adjoining building also ignited, but by throwing it into the street no further damage was done.

abstract: The idea that a State can secede from the Union whenever a majority of its people see fit, for any cause, or for no cause, and with the passive acquiescence of the Federal Government, is the strangest folly of the day. Those who maintain this proposition, seem to overlook the fact that the President of the United States has taken an oath to support the Constitution, and see that the laws are faithfully executed. Among the duties of theExecutive, as defined in the second Article of the Constitution, it is declared that "he shall take care that the laws be faithfully executed." Article Sixth declares that "this Constitution, and the laws of the United States made in pursuance thereof; and all treaties made, or which shall be made, under the authority of the United States, shall be the supreme law of the land; and the judges in every State shall be bound thereby, anything in the Constitution or the laws of any State to the contrary notwithstanding." The next clause declares that "The Senators and Representatives before mentioned, and the members of the several State Legislatures, and all Executive and Judicial officers, both of the United States and of the several States, shall be bound by oath or affirmation to support this Constitution." The President, before entering upon the duties of his office, "shall take the following oath or affirmation: "I do solemnly swear (or affirm) that I will faithfully execute the office of President of the United States, and will to the best of my ability, preserve, protect and defend the Constitution of the United States."

abstract: In this Court, held yesterday by Judge RUSSELL, the Assistant District-Attorney came with an armful of papers, and remarked that he should "ask the Court to sit late to-day." As case after case was called, however, and no one was prepared to go on, it became evident that the Court would have very little, if any, business to transact. Out of about twenty cases called, disposition was made of only one, witnesses or counsel in all the others being absent.

abstract: BED-CLOTHING FOR THE NEWSBOYS. -- The premonitory advances of Winter are already felt at the Newsboys' Lodging-House by numbers of destitute boys, who are compelled to sleep on benches there, or to leave in search of barges, empty basements, stoops or ash-boxes, owing to the deficiency of bed-clothing at this Institution. To meet the wants of this numerous class of boys, another dormitory has just been fitted up, capable of accommodating sixty boys, in addition to seventy in the oriental bed-room; but the humane and considerate friends of these unfortunate children will do well to help them by contributing, what will be of inappreciable service to humanity, warm and comfortable bed-clothing, to make the Winter pass them less drearily than it has been their wont to experience in former years. By referring to the report of the Institution, it will be seen that nearly twenty thousand lodgings have been provided for these poor boys within a year, and that about fourteen thousand meals have been given to them. Several hundreds are now happily located in country homes, and many who have made the Lodging-House their permanent abode have acquired settled habits of industry and morality, which will subserve the future interests of society as well as their own. The work tells for itself, and those interested in it would do well to visit the Institution. Gifts of bed-clothing, and of such donations as the benevolent may deem suitable, will be thankfully received at the Newsboys' Lodging-House, No. 128 Fulton-street, C. O'CONNOR Superintendent; or they will be sent for to the address of the givers.

abstract: As some interest attaches at present to the complement of United States soldiers stationed South, we append a correct list of them. At Fort Monroe, Va., 8 Companies of Artillery; at Fayetteville Arsenal, N.C., 1 Company of Artillery; at Fort Moultrie, S.C., 2 Companies of Artillery; at Augusta, Ga., 1 Company of Artillery; Key West, Fa., 1 Company of Artillery; Barrancas Barracks, near Pensacola, Fla., 1 Company of Artillery; Baton Rouge, La., 1 Company of Artillery. Total about 800 men. There are about 120 U.S. marines at Norfolk and Pensacola. The recruiting station of Jefferson, Mo., and Louisville, have no full company garrisoning them just now.

abstract: A German lad, named Louis, aged 14 years, who, for two weeks past has been employed as errand-boy in the store of Jacob Geisman, dealer in laces and embroideries, corner of Broadway and Reade-street, yesterday absconded, taking with him a tin box containing about $70 in cash and valuable papers belonging to his employer. It was the custom of the firm to nightly deposit the cash on hand in the box alluded to, in an iron safe on another floor of the building, and the boy Louis usually brought it up stairs in the morning. Yesterday, however, he procured the tin box from the person having charge of the safe and went away with it. Mr. Geisman himself entered upon a search for the fugitive, and after inquiring all day about town he finally, in the evening, found the lad at an emigrant boarding-house in Albany-street. Upon charging him with the theft he said that he was guilty, and stated that $28 of the money had been expended in the purchase of a passage ticket to Bremen, per ship on Saturday, while with another portion he had provided himself with a suit of clothes. The balance he had with him, but the papers he had thrown away. Mr. Geisman delivered his prisoner into the custody of the Police, and to-day he will be taken before a magistrate.

abstract: -- KENNET, the showman, has a hippopotamus, which he has recently been exhibiting to the good folk of New-Orleans. They having been exceeding liberal in their patronage of his show, KENNET advertised that on the day of his departure he would lead the animal through the streets, en route for the depot. Vast crowds lined the way. Presently the shower and the showee made their appearance, to the great delight of the unwashed, who cheered and huzzahed most lustily. The hippopotamus, unaccustomed to so public a demonstration, eyed first one side, then the other, and suddenly standing on his hind legs, grunted out, "Ooachunckon," "ooachunckon!" in a sound and distinct manner. At first the populace laughed, but it being suggested by some one that he meant "Hurrah for LINCOLN," an attempt was made to kill him and mob his keeper -- an undertaking which would undoubtedly have been successful had not the keeper protested on his honor that the animal always did so when he was frightened, and that long before LINCOLN was heard of the hippopotami of all climes had indulged in the same remarkable dialect.

abstract: We ventured the other day a suggestion of a plan by which the sectional hostility, growing out of the non-execution of the Fugitive Slave law, might be appeased. The complaint on the part, of the South is that they are deprived of their property, by the refusal of the North to fulfill an explicit injunction of the Constitution. On the other hand the complaint of the North is, that they are required to perform an act repugnant to the moral sense and common humanity of every man who has a conscience and a heart -- namely, to seize and surrender to hopeless and perpetual Slavery a man who has escaped therefrom. Here is the "irrepressible conflict" --a claim of property on the one hand, a plea of conscience and humanity on the other.

abstract: THE FRIENDLESS OLD LADY IN SULLIVAN STREET. -- We are requested to state that a well-known druggist of this city placed some money in the hands of Mr. J.C. LAWTHIER, in behalf of the destitute old lady at 72 Sullivan street mentioned in yesterday's TIMES. Mr. LAWTHIER, called at the place with the donation, and found that a lady and her daughter had already forestalled the charity of others, and had made provision for removing the old woman to their own home, and making her comfortable for the rest of her days. This act of Christian benevolence is its own reward, and needs no comment. We are deeply grateful for the prompt response that has been made to the appeal in the TIMES, and we are happy in being able to announce that the worthy old woman for whom the appeal was made, is now amply provided for.

We are deeply grateful for the prompt response that has been made to the appeal in the TIMES, and we are happy in being able to announce that the worthy old woman for whom the appeal was made, is now amply provided for.

abstract: BROOKLYN INSTITUTE LECTURES. -- The first of the Winter course of lectures, before the Brooklyn Institute, was delivered last night by Rev. E.H. CHAPIN. He took for his subject: "Man and his Work," treating it under two heads: 1. Laws that Govern Labor and Action. 2. The estimate that is put upon it. He contended that every man had a special field of effort, and the law of balance, which limits the effort devoted to one object, to the exclusion of others, and which adjusts the thinking and executive faculties and the medium between too little work and overwork; the law of just measure under which man receives a just reward for his work, in proportion to his faithfulness; and the true and false estimate of success and failure -- the world's estimate, which was often superficial, and individual estimate, which often acknowledged failure, when the world called it success, were dilated upon. He said that nations oftentimes, as individuals, had a special work to do, and to this nation was intrusted, in a peculiar sense, vindication of the wisdom of our system of government, and never had the experiment of free government been more anxiously regarded than at this time.

abstract: Rebecca's dress was not quite ready, so "La Juive" has been postponed at the Academy from the 12th to the 26th or 30th, sooner or later, perhaps later. To-morrow and to-morrow. Precision in opening and shutting opera houses in Europe, where a manager would as soon leave the gay and festive world by suicide outright as to leave it in the lurch by a broken promise, is not calculated among the moralities of the Irving-place Muse. A general looseness of action, comporting with the indifference of the public, marks there the days and dates of harmonious matters and things. Mr. ULLMAN says he will begin such a date, and parades titles and singers, and much rhetoric, to set off his diamond stock; but the singers who have to cross the broad Atlantic may not arrive, or, having arrived, give a fresh turn to the financial screw, or wish for a little more security, or some serpent or other gets into the Paradise of music, and there is the devil to pay. Certainly, with the uncertainty of musical supplies from a distant transoceanic land, speaking a strange tongue and full of home-sick fancies, operatic management is no sinecure. Then again, the reserved right of prime donne and primi nomini to fall ill, to have liver and lights most dreadfully diseased at the shortest notice, interferes sadly with the managerial precisions, a thing not practicable abroad -- for when singers try to sham to that tune persistently, they go to Sing Sing until they recover. With these comparative anatomies, and this interpretation before us of the several effects of republican and monarchical institutions on the larynx, pharynx, glottis, epiglottis and lungs, we may appreciate the condition of a manager here as to ability or inability to get his troops into action with given certainty at any time. Then when the season does commence, we are promised several operas, almost as good as new, masterpieces demanding all the resources of the lyric stage. We wait and look for them, and are at last told that Signor Tamberlik or Signora Somebody is coming! So runs the operatic world away.

abstract: -It may be remembered that two of the Harbor-Masters of this port and one Deputy, were indicted some weeks since for alleged corruption in the duties of their office. We believe they all retain their positions, and are still engaged in the discharge of their official duties.

abstract: The fools are not all dead yet. We mention the fact for the consolation of our neighbor, the Herald, -- for if they were, that estimable sheet would have neither editor, correspondent nor readers. The race is immortal. It is "incapable to die." abstract: -- The Irish citizens of Boston yesterday held a meeting in sympathy with the Sixty-Ninth Regiment, in its refusal to parade in honor of the Prince of Wales. The whole of this business is postdated. The wrath of our own Hibernian military, founded on national grievances belonging to another age, which the reign of the actual sovereign of Great Britain has done the work of a century in removing, was therefore entirely too late in its ill-tempered application to the Prince of Wales. And to sympathize with this posthumous indignation after the Prince has actually left the country, and is probably at this moment, buried in books at classic Cambridge, is to carry the anachronism to the extreme of the ridiculous. The fact is, the default of Col. CORCORAN in not setting his squadron in the field is strictly a question of military ethics, in the determination of which the acutest sympathies will doubtless play an indifferent part. If that officer was legally justified in disregarding the orders of his senior, he will be so pronounced by the proper Court of Inquiry. If he lacked such justification, it will remain for the Governor to pass upon the case, which there is every reason to hope he will be inclined to do in the spirit of gentleness and conciliation. It deserves to be remembered that while our Irish population thus silently refrained from uniting in the general welcome, they also refrained from any demonstration of discourtesy and ill-will, which might else have marred the perfect success of the ovation. This forbearance entitles them to consideration with the Executive.

abstract: -- There is one very gratifying circumstance in all the secession movements of the South. The authority of the Federal Government is nowhere resisted. The Charleston Mercury denies very indignantly the report that Fort Moultrie is to be seized. The Collector of the port of Charleston denies that there has been any interruption of the ordinary process of collecting Federal duties, and clearing vessels. The people of Charleston call upon the Postmaster not to resign his place. And in every particular special care is taken not to oppose or disregard any law of Congress.

abstract: At the charter election which takes place during the first week of next month, our citizens will he called upon to choose nine Aldermen, twenty-four Councilmen, forty-four Constables, one Civil Justice for the Eighth District, together with a full staff of School Commissioners, School Trustees and School Inspectors. These are all important officers, and though their election will excite far less public clamor than was raised by the Fusion Committee, in its efforts to defeat the choice of a President and Vice-Presidant by the people, there can be little doubt, so far as regards the mere material interests of the City, that the issue of next December will be little less important to our tax-payers than was the result of the November struggle to the politicians and parties of the country.

abstract: The people of this country, particularly of the Northern part, are in a curious position at this moment. Having exercised an undoubted constitutional right in electing for President a man representing their views, and feeling in their inmost hearts that they have not in that act or in their own sentiments entertained any idea of unkindness or injustice to their fellow-countrymen, they nevertheless perceive that the citizens of the Southern States are terribly incensed, and in their anger are preparing for violent resistance. They see, moreover, in the whole Southern country a persistent misstatement of their principles, and that any attempt simply to rectify these misstatements is denounced as offensive. If any man in the South should publicly declare that the principles of Mr. LINCOLN and the Platform of the Republican Party are exactly what they are, that man would be ostracised, and, perhaps, subjected to physical maltreatment. This is not only now the fact, but has been so through the whole Presidential struggle, and we -- the Republicans -- are made responsible for opinions and principles we have never entertained, and are opposed with the same rancor as if we avowed and defended them. Even more than this; the leaders of Southern feeling insist that their followers shall pursue the same course as if these misstatements were true statements -- this course going to the extent of rebellion, secession, anarchy and bloodshed.

abstract: The intelligence which we continue to receive from the South is of a character similar to that which has reached us for two or three days past. There is evidently a strong sentiment in favor of the Union struggling to the surface throughout the Slave States, the evidence of which are found in the announcement that Mr. COBB, a Representative in Congress from Alabama, is strongly opposed to disunion, as are also Gen. MILLSON, Representative from Virginia, and various other prominent Southerners, from whom we have heard. The Press, too, of Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Louisiana, and other of the Southern States, is generally ranged against secession -- so long as there is any possible method of avoiding it. Gov. LETCHER, of Virginia, it will be seen, has been prevailed upon to call an extra session of the Legislature of that State, to consider the present condition of affairs. Keeping in recollection the action of the Virginia Legislature on the occasion of the visit of a Commissioner from South Carolina some time ago, there will be little apprehension as to the course which will be pursued in the present crisis. From Maryland we learn that the Governor will peremptorily refuse to call an extra session of the Legislature of that. State, unless such a movement shall become general throughout the South. He doubtless considers that the sentiment of Maryland is so clearly indicated as to render such a proceeding unnecessary. State Conventions are to be called in Georgia and Alabama -- in the latter State on the 6th of December. The date of the Georgia Convention is not indicated. The resignation of Senator HAMMOND, of South Carolina, is immediate. He does not choose to wait until the inauguration of Mr. LINCOLN takes place, but has already forwarded directions to Washington to have his personal effects there sent home. Meantime, preparations for great Union demonstrations in the Slave States continue. One is soon to be held in Missouri, in Boone or Randolph County. The announcement is made in our Washington dispatch, that Gov. WISE, the most strenuous advocate of disunion, in Virginia, is pronounced to be deranged.
lead_paragraph: The intelligence which we continue to receive from the South is of a character similar to that which has reached us for two or three days past. There is evidently a strong sentiment in favor of the Union struggling to the surface throughout the Slave States, the evidence of which are found in the announcement that Mr. COBB, a Representative in Congress from Alabama, is strongly opposed to disunion, as are also Gen. MILLSON, Representative from Virginia, and various other prominent Southerners, from whom we have heard. The Press, too, of Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Louisiana, and other of the Southern States, is generally ranged against secession -- so long as there is any possible method of avoiding it. abstract: The Art-Critic of a cotemporary speaks in most exalted terms of the success which has attended an eminent "animal painter" in finishing a group of buffaloes. There is a charming ambiguity about announcement. In the Western wilds there dwelleth an animal known in the local idiom as "painter" the which is eminent for veracity; yet it is questionable even that eminent animal, painter, could "finish" a group of buffaloes in the brief space alloted for the performance by the Arch Art-Critic. Or, it may be, that by animal painter, the A.C. of our contemporary alludes to the artistic REYNARD, who is noted for carrying a "brush," and dealing in sly effects. Had it been a group of poultry finished, the latter inference would be irresistible.

abstract: The only disunion indication of any special importance which we have this morning is a dispatch from Mobile, Ala., which states that a meeting of all parties was held there yesterday, which unanimously favored secession -- resolutions to await the action of other States being voted down and withdrawn. A dispatch from Augusta, Ga., states that there was nothing of interest to telegraph from important Southern centres. In fact, judging from our dispatches and newspaper extracts, the secession feeling is rapidly narrowing within a very circumscribed portion of the Southern States, and will most probably soon be confinedentirely to two or three of them at most. It will be seen that the extra session of the Virginia Legislature, for which Gov. LETCHER has issued his proclamation, is simply called one week earlier than it would have been in the ordinary course of events -- the business of the State requiring special legislation. The Republicans of Maryland have issued a manifesto, through the gentlemen who were their candidates for electors in the late election, in which they strongly advise firmness and adhesion to the Republican principles. They entertain no fears for the ultimate safety of the Union. The statement made in our letter from Columbia, S.C., published yesterday morning, that a prominent New-York Captain has offered his services to GEO. GIST, with a large body of men, is repeated in our Baltimore dispatch this morning, on the strength of a telegram received in that city. There will doubtless be some curiosity to know who the "prominent New-York Captain" is. Everything remains quiet at the National Capital. All apprehension there appears to have died out. Meantime members of Congress are beginning to arrive and preparations for the approaching session will soon make the city busy.

abstract: The conduct of the Federal officials in South Carolina and Georgia presents a singular question for casuists. It seems that public opinion in those chivalrous States can no longer tolerate the thought of subjection to the Federal Government; and by way of asserting their independence, all the officials whose business it is to collect the revenue, or to enforce the payment of debts due to Northern merchants, have been compelled to resign. But the Postmasters, it seems, although swearing allegiance, like the others, to the Federal Government, are advised to hold on to their offices. The reason for this toleration of Federal Postmasters may be explained by the fact that the tranmission of the mails through these States costs the Federal Government about three times as much as it derives from postage.

abstract: The Board of County Canvassers resumed their sitting at 10 o'clock yesterday morning, and the lobby at once filled up, much interest being felt in the vote of the Eleventh and Seventeenth Wards -- which are the most populous Wards of the City -- the returns from which were the special order for the day. Before taking up those returns, however, the Board finished up the returns from the Fifteenth Ward, excepting the Second District, which gave no record for Assemblyman. The question of this deficiency was referred to Supervisor BLUNT, and the Canvassers of the District were ordered to be summoned before the Board to-day.

abstract: The United States ship Savannah arrived off the Navy-yand yesterday afternoon, twenty-eight days from Vera Cruz, having left there at 6 A.M. on the 19th October. She had very light and unfavorable winds until reaching the latitude of Charleston, S. C., when the wind shifted to the southward and eastward, and from thence almost immediately round to the westward and northward, blowing for several days a succession of strong gales, at times quite heavy.

lead_paragraph: In addition to our own very interesting letter, which we publish this morning, we copy also from the special correspondence of the London Times a graphic description of the important battles that have recently taken place on the banks of the Pei-ho. The result, as every one anticipated, has been highly favorable to the Anglo-French arms. Though the Chinese fought with courage, skill and determination, they fought without the slightest chance of ultimate success against a splendidly appointed army, equipped with the greatest care, armed with the latest inventions of science, and composed of the elite of the French and English services.

abstract: The American ship Africa, Capt. JORDAN, from Cardiff, Wales, April 28, for Woosung, with a cargo of coal; was totally lost on Friday, Aug. 31, on Jilaka Shoals; Jilaka Island bore by compass S.S.E., one and a half miles. She struck at high water, and ran out forward five feet. The flow of the tide being only 1 1/2 feet, found it impossible to get her off, although assisted by the crew of the Dutch ship Era Johanna and Dutch bark Henrika. At 7 o'clock P.M., Capt. JORDAN, seeing the hopeless condition of his vessel, and being surrounded by Malays, (or pirates,) concluded, for the safety of himself and crew, to abandon the ship, which was accordingly done; and he proceeded on board the bark Hendrika. On the way to that vessel, at 7 1/2 P.M., and when but a short distance from the Africa, he discovered she was on fire, supposed to have been the work of the Malays. The ship continued burning until 4 A.M. the following morning, when, after burning to the water's edge, she slipped off the rock, and at daylight no vestige of her was to be seen. Capt. JORDON and crew arrived at Singapore in the bark Hendrika. The Africa was built in 1854 at Brunswick, Me., rated A Nov. 1 1/2.

JORDAN, seeing the hopeless condition of his vessel, and being surrounded by Malays, (or pirates,) concluded, for the safety of himself and crew, to abandon the ship, which was accordingly done; and he proceeded on board the bark Hendrika. On the way to that vessel, at 7 1/2 P.M., and when but a short distance from the Africa, he discovered she was on fire, supposed to have been the work of the Malays. The ship continued burning until 4 A.M. the following morning, when, after burning to the water's edge, she slipped off the rock, and at daylight no vestige of her was to be seen. Capt. JORDON and crew arrived at Singapore in the bark Hendrika. The Africa was built in 1854 at Brunswick, Me., rated A Nov. 1 1/2.

abstract: Without the least inclination to under-estimate the eloquence of Judge DOUGLAS, or the weight of his personal address, we cannot but think that he is putting himself to much needless trouble in the quantity and frequency of the speeches he is delivering in favor of the Union through certain portions of the Southern States. Perhaps it is that the eloquent ex-candidate for the Presidency does not as yet sufficiently realize the value of Dr. FAUST's discovery. He will not understand that any paper, even of average Southern circulation, would place his thoughts eventually, and in permanent form, before a larger number of readers than could possibly be collected within sound of his voice. His speeches, unless he will insist on drugging the market with them, are matters of public interest, and as such are copied into other journals. But by his present course of talking incessantly, and talking everywhere, he is very seriously impairing his capacities for public usefulness, while utterly destroying that eagerness which a great portion of the American people have heretofore evinced to know and weigh his opinions.

abstract: The progress of the Board of Canvassers is watched with an interest only second to that attending the election. With reference to two seats in Congress, two or three seats in the Assembly, the Registership and the Supervisorship, the votes which apparently elected Republicans are perilously close, and a variation of a very few figures in the returns from the several election districts may turn the scale in favor of the opposite candidates. Such variations are found to occur with unusual and alarming frequency, in one case unseating a Republican Assemblyman, supposed to be safely elected.

abstract: By a vote of the Fifth Company, Seventh Regiment, during the last year, the member who should introduce the largest number of acceptable recruits for the Company was to receive a gold medal. On Thursday evening the medal was awarded to Mr. ABRAM SELIG, and was presented by the Captain of the Company. The medal is of solid, eighteen-carats gold, bearing on one side the coat of arms of the Regiment, surmounted by the American Eagle. A drummer on one side, and a private in uniform on the other stand sentry. On the obverse it is inscribed: "Recruit Medal, Fifth Company, Seventh Regiment. Amarded to ABRAM SELIG, Oct. 18, 1860."

abstract: The general drift of Southern sentiment, so far as we can judge from the latest advices, is towards a convention of all the Slave-holding States. South Carolina seems obstinately opposed to such a course, but every other Southern State apparently favors it. In Virginia, and other Border States, particularly, the feeling is very strong, that if anything is to be done in this matter, it must be done by the united action of all the aggrieved parties. The most ardent; Disunionists in Virginia. -- even the Richmond Examiner, -- denounce the scheme of allowing the Cotton States, or any one of them, to decide this issue for themselves. They claim a right to participate in all such counsels, and will not readily consent to be excluded.

abstract: The day for the trial of Col. MICHAEL CORCORAN, of the Sixty-ninth Regiment, for disobedience of orders in neglecting to direct his command to parade on the occasion of the reception of the Prince of Wales, is not yet fixed. The charges against him were formally preferred to Gen. EWEN, commanding the Fourth-Brigade, to which the regiment is attached, by Col. MORRELL, Acting Division Inspector. Gen. EWEN sent Col. CORCORAN notice of arrest day before yesterday, and yesterday transmitted to Major-Gen. SANDFORD the papers in the case and the warrant of arrest. The law directs that within thirty days after receiving the papers the Major-General must order the Court-martial, and that the officer arrested shall not be brought to trial until ten days after he is notified of the names of the officers detailed to form the Court. It only remains for Gen. SANDFORD to constitute the Court, which must consists of a General officer and two officers of the same rank with the accused. Until he does so the day of the trial cannot be specified. Col. MEAD, the Judge Advocate of the First Division, Deputy Collector of the port, will conduct the prosecution.

abstract: The idea of a Constitutional right in the States to secede from the Union, is an absurdity on its face; since it amounts in substance to a declaration that the people of a State are under no obligation to obey a law, if a majority of them were opposed to its enactment. The Constitution, thus interpreted, would be a mere rope of sand, and the laws passed in pursuance of its provisions would have no more anthority than the resolutions of a public meeting. The Nullifiers of 1832only claimed the right of resisting the enforcement of acts of Congress which are clearly unconstitutional, but the Secessionists of the present day insist upon an unqualified right of secession for any cause, or for no cause. They dislike Mr. LINCOLN's politics, and without waiting to see whether he will invade their constitutional rights, they propose to secede from the Union, and invite their sister States of the South to follow their example.

lead_paragraph: Any good deed of the Aldermen has peculiar claims to recognition. One such was recorded yesterday, in the shape of a resolution assigning to the Superior Court a suite of rooms in the brown-stone building at the corner of Chambers and Centre streets apartments free from all the sanitary objections to which its present accommodations are subject. The change is important, not merely as affecting the health and longevity of suitors, jurors and barristers, but as rendering it physically possible for eminent legal talent to reconcile itself to the duties of the tribunal. The resignation of Judge PIERREPONT was a forcible intimation that accomplished jurists cannot be expected to give in exchange for the meagre salaries attached to judicial positions health and life, as well as the thorough attainments which such positions exact. There is nothing of honor or reward in the service to repay the sacrifice.

abstract: On Thursday Detectives McDougall and Bennett saw two men, whom they suspected to be thieves, in Greenwich-avenue, carrying a box of soap. Bennett arrested one of them, who gave the name of Thomas Neely, and McDougall entered upon a cross-examination of the other. Finding these interrogatories of too searching a character, McDougall's man, who held the soap, dropped it and ran into an alley in Eighth-street, the officer following him closely.
lead_paragraph: On Thursday Detectives McDougall and Bennett saw two men, whom they suspected to be thieves, in Greenwich-avenue, carrying a box of soap. Bennett arrested one of them, who gave the name of Thomas Neely, and McDougall entered upon a cross-examination of the other. Finding these interrogatories of too searching a character, McDougall's man, who held the soap, dropped it and ran into an alley in Eighth-street, the officer following him closely. As soon, however, as the latter entered the alley, he was assaulted by some person unknown, in so severe a manner as to make him for a few moments insensible. When he recovered himself, his assailants had escaped as well as the man whom he had pursued. It was subsequently ascertained that the soap had been stolen from Claus Fink, corner of Sixth-avenue and Eleventh-street, and Neely was committed by Justice QUACKENBUSH to answer for the theft.

abstract: The statement to the effect that Mr. BUCHANAN, touched with the sufferings of Kansas, had given a hundred dollars for their relief, is evidently deemed so improbable as to demand more than ordinary proof.
lead_paragraph: The statement to the effect that Mr. BUCHANAN, touched with the sufferings of Kansas, had given a hundred dollars for their relief, is evidently deemed so improbable as to demand more than ordinary proof. We are accordingly furnished with an authoritative assertion of the fact, strengthened with an actual copy of the order upon which the money was obtained. Less than this would not have answered. That the inveterate and remorseless malignity with which the President has pursued that injured people, should have yielded to any more placable sentiment is not the only reflection that must have carried doubt to the mind of the reader. In the sunset of his Administration, with so much light thrown back upon his public career as to show how profitless has been his tortuous Territorial policy, it is within the limits of credibility that the mistaken Chief may appreciate his errors, and yearn to make some amends for the wrong they inflicted, especially as so valuable an aid to reflection as the result of the Presidential canvass is added to his material of judgment.

abstract: About 3 o'clock on Saturday morning smoke was seen arising from the lager-bier saloon in the basement of No. 212 Division street, kept by Frederick Freund and his wife, both Germans, who slept in in the premises. An alarm was given, and upon breaking the door open it was found that a fire had been kindled in four different places. The matter was at once brought the notice of the Fire Mashal, who caused the arrest of Freund and his wife, and Justice BREENAN committed them to prison, pending an examination. When the accused were first seen after the discovery of the fire both were fully dressed, and each had about their persons jewelry, clothing and other articles, which it does not seem likely that they would have been able to save without having had ample time in which to pack them up. Freund had his property insured for $500 in the Wall-street Insurance Company, and at the time of his arrest he had the policy with him.

abstract: John Thompson, otherwise called Jeremiah Flannagan, was put on trial charged with the murder of Capt. Prentice, of the schooner California. But one witness was called, who was a seaman on board. There were four men on board, the captain, the mate, the witness and the prisoner. The captain and the prisoner were on watch during the night. The witness was called up by the prisoner, why said that the captain had fallen overboard, and he had, thrown a plank over to him. Efforts were made to save him, but in vain. Some marks of blood were found on deck, and some hair, but what hair it was did not appear. There was no other evidence, and the Jury thereupon acquitted the accused.

abstract: The chivalry of South Carolina, it would seem, are not without influential sympathizers in the Empire City. The telegraph announces that "a distinguished officer" of New-York has offered Gov. GIST to enlist under the Palmetto flag "at the head of twelve hundred fighting New-Yorkers."
lead_paragraph: The chivalry of South Carolina, it would seem, are not without influential sympathizers in the Empire City. The telegraph announces that "a distinguished officer" of New-York has offered Gov. GIST to enlist under the Palmetto flag "at the head of twelve hundred fighting New-Yorkers." The name of the officer is not given, but another dispatch describes him as "a prominent New-York Captain." This points directly to Marshal RYNDERS as the only prominent "Captain" among us who could be capable of any such piece of treasonable folly. The fact that the census has been finished, and that the Slave-trade has, of late, been seriously interfered with at this port, together with the near approach of March, 1861, -- must naturally make the illustrious Captain desirous of securing a new field of profitable operations. Let South Carolina only relieve our City of his presence, and the evils of her secession will not be without, at least, one item of compensation.

abstract: The late Republican electoral candidates in Maryland have issued an address. They set forth the principles which they hold as Republicans, by way of introduction. Slavery they recognize as a social and political evil, which local law defends, and with which they would not interfere directly or indirectly.
lead_paragraph: The late Republican electoral candidates in Maryland have issued an address. They set forth the principles which they hold as Republicans, by way of introduction. Slavery they recognize as a social and political evil, which local law defends, and with which they would not interfere directly or indirectly. They bow to the supremacy of the Fugitive Slave law, as growing out of the Constitution, and resistance to it they hold to be as unjust and as immoral as the violation of any other obligation of the political compact Congress, they think, has the right to legislate for the territories which, of right, belong to the freemen of the United States. In these doctrines they see nothing which can be stigmatized as sectional; on the contrary they are identical with the principles maintained by the founders of the Government. The address concludes as follows:
