abstract: To the few confiding souls who still retain faith in the Academy of Music's operatic announcements, it may be fit to mention that "La Juive" is promised on Monday, the 26th. Miss HINCKLEY, the Albanian songstress has arrived.
lead_paragraph: To the few confiding souls who still retain faith in the Academy of Music's operatic announcements, it may be fit to mention that "La Juive" is promised on Monday, the 26th. Miss HINCKLEY, the Albanian songstress has arrived. Mr. MAX MARETZEK, the conductor of the operatic orchestra, whose movements have recently been the subject of much anxiety to many inquiring friends, in one of those gay freaks which occasionally overtake this indomitable gentleman, departed suddenly on Thursday, without notice for the Havana, where he proposes organizing a corps for the musical invasion of Mexico. His baton has passed into the hands of Mr. CARL ANSCHUTZ. FORMES, FABBBI & Co. have been concertizing during the past week with great success at Baltimore, Washington and Richmond. The MUZIO division, under the direction of the affable GROW, give a Concert with "Don Pasquale," to follow at the Brooklyn Athenaeum on Friday, the 23d.

abstract: On Monday night last, Naval Officer LAURENS spoke at Institute Hall, Charleston, together with Judge MAGRATH and others. After some remarks on the general subject, Mr. LAURENS took occasion to explain his position as an officer of the Federal Government.
lead_paragraph: On Monday night last, Naval Officer LAURENS spoke at Institute Hall, Charleston, together with Judge MAGRATH and others. After some remarks on the general subject, Mr. LAURENS took occasion to explain his position as an officer of the Federal Government. Many of my fellow-citizens, said he, view the Custom-house as an institution for the purpose of collecting the revenue of Government. This is true, as far as it goes; and if it were the sole object and duty of the institution, then the Custom-house might be closed, now and forever, without detriment to the State; but it has other and higher responsibility than this. If the port of Charleston were declared a free port of entry, that all goods might be landed on her wharves free of any taxation, still there would be a necessity, an absolute necessity, for a Custom or Clearing House. It is the law of all civilized nations that the nationality of a vessel must be proven by the official papers and seal of the Government under whose flag she sails, or else, by the said law, she is viewed as an unlawful cruiser, herself and cargo a lawful prize, her captain and crew pirates. Close the doors of the United States Customhouse before South Carolina establishes one of her own, and you blockade your own port more thoroughly and effectually than all the combined navies of the world could do. The cotton, rice, and other produce now on our wharves, in storehouses, and elsewhere, must seek another port; all vessels not cleared must rot at our wharves, or run the risk of confiscation in another port. It was in view of this embarrassment to our city -- the emporium of our State -- that my letter of the 7th November was written and published. Amid the tumult of that day's excitement I fear my action may not have been clearly understood by all, and I hope the present exposition may prove satisfactory.

abstract: Great delight has been aroused amongst the lower strata of the Democratic factions, by a proposition gravely made through a prominent Republican journal, to the effect that no nominations for the City of ficers to be filled next December should be made by the Republican organization.
lead_paragraph: Great delight has been aroused amongst the lower strata of the Democratic factions, by a proposition gravely made through a prominent Republican journal, to the effect that no nominations for the City of ficers to be filled next December should be made by the Republican organization. It is everywhere regarded by Democrats of the muscular and porterhouse persuasions as the very "biggest thing" that has turned up for their benefit for some years. If the Republicans are to support "People's Nominations," the muscular and porterhouse politicians of Mozart Hall and the Pewter Mug will see that they have no lack of popular candidates. The Mozart men, in particular, are active in the matter, most of them following politics for a living, and all of them having either promises or hopes of appointments in the Street or City Inspector's Departments, provided Mayor WOOD can secure a Board of Aldermen who will turn out the present incumbents and confirm his nominees in their places.

abstract: My name is Ellen C. Bennett; lived in Chicago, Ill.; went there about seven years...
lead_paragraph: My name is Ellen C. Clark; father's is William Meyers; am forty years old the 25th of this month; was born in New-York State; my mother is living there; think she is sixty-nine years old; I am single; my first husband was named Aaron W. Bennett; lived in Chicago, Ill.; went there about seven years ago; now live at No. 107 Morgan-street, in this city; have lived here since 8th of October last; in Chicago I lived on the west side of Jefferson-street, between Harrison and Polk streets, opposite Cedar-street; lived there between March and November, 1857; the house was a brown cottage, with four rooms and closets, and had a dressmaking sign on it; I rented it from Heath & Hurd, paint and oil dealers; have been married twice, the second time to James M. Clark, on the last day of July, six years ago, by a Baptist minister, and at Chicago; my first husband is living; my second died in a town near Chicago, in a year and ten days after we were married; at Chicago, my business most of the time was nursing; lived at the Clarendon House, on Randolph and Market streets, and at the Homoeopathic Hospital, Nos. 18 and 20 Kinzie-street; made my home at the latter place while I worked out; then went to housekeeping on Lake-street, between Halstead and Green streets; afterwards, successively, on Jefferson, on Harrison, and Polk street, and on Madison, between Green and Peoria streets; could not tell how long at each; nursed small-pox patients; married Clarke at the hospital, on Lake-street; took in the sick and took care of them; next stopped at Union Hospital, between Carroll and Fulton streets; afterwards lived at various places, going from house to house, nursing or sewing, and taking care of the sick at home; have kept houses of ill-fame, and been an inmate of one other such house; kept one a portion of eighteen months, including the brown cottage on Jefferson-street, in Chicago; also, one on Madison-street, there; also, one at the corner, of Morgan-street and Broadway, in this city, and at No. 322 Broadway; was an inmate of such house at No. 16 O'Fallon-street: at the brown cottage in Chicago, I boarded only one, Mary Starkey, who sewed and received money from a gentleman.

abstract: Our readers will remember what a hue and cry was raised recently when the State Legislature enacted a law for the suppression of theatrical performances in this City on Sunday.
lead_paragraph: Our readers will remember what a hue and cry was raised recently when the State Legislature enacted a law for the suppression of theatrical performances in this City on Sunday. Crowds of Germans assembled in the public halls and parks, and listened to inflamed phillipies from Doctors whose names exhausted the consonants of a dozen alphabets; the "Sensation Press" was laden to the margin with denunciations of the despotic rulers who invaded the rights of conscience and the freedom of religious belief, which the letter and spirit of our institutions had secured to all; -- the unconstitutionality of the law was proclaimed, and one united German guttural of defiance went up from a thousand throats. The proprietors of German theatres determined to test the constitutionality of the statute; but with a seeming prescience of the failure that would crown their efforts against it in the legal tribunals, they resorted to a very silly subterfuge, and established a new religious order or sect, the public devotional exercises of which consisted of theatrical performances on Sunday, while the individual virtues it inculcated were smoking tobacco in meerschaum pipes, and the copious guzzling of lager-beer. Infatuated with a belief that the profanity, which christened such folly with the name of religion, would secure them immunity from the penalties of the law, the proprietors of various beer-gardens and theatres continued their Sunday performances in defiance of the enactment. Several of their number were indicted, one of whom, GUSTAVE LINDENMULLER, on Saturday last was tried before Judge GOULD, in the Oyer and Terminer.

abstract: The popular movement towards secession in the South is watched with profound anxiety in this City. In the rural sections of the North it excites as yet but very little feeling. The people of the interior, as a general thing, regard it merely with curiosity.
lead_paragraph: The popular movement towards secession in the South is watched with profound anxiety in this City. In the rural sections of the North it excites as yet but very little feeling. The people of the interior, as a general thing, regard it merely with curiosity. Their interests are not directly involved, and their own attachment to the Union is so unquestioning and sincere, that they do not realize the possibility of anybody's really wishing to destroy it. They go quite as much too far in one direction, as our excitable City population go in the other. They do not believe the South at all in earnest; they look upon the whole movement as factitious and empty -- as aiming merely at political results, and certain to end in smoke. In the City, on the contrary, the apprehensions of disunion are so excessive as to leave little room for cool judgment and common sense. Men await every hour's fresh news from the South as if it were to seal the fate of the nation. Stocks go up or down, as matters look bright or gloomy, from one day to another. The whole public mind is feverish -- apprehensive, alarmed; and as a matter of course, the smallest incidents assume gigantic proportions in the public eye.

abstract: We must dissent in toto from the suggestion made in a quarter certainly entitled to some authority, that the Republican organizations of our City should make no regular nominations for the various important offices to be filled at the December Election.
lead_paragraph: We must dissent in toto from the suggestion made in a quarter certainly entitled to some authority, that the Republican organizations of our City should make no regular nominations for the various important offices to be filled at the December Election. Such abstinence on the side of the Republicans would be simply a surrender of the City Government, without contest, into the clutches of one or other of the contending Democratic factions. It would have even yet worse results; for the Democratic factions, freed from any fear of Republican competition, would of necessity have to vie with each other in appeals to the sympathies of the very lowest class of voters, by nominating candidates directly selected out of that class. It is to the fear of Republican rivalry that we now owe any respectable nominations made by the Democratic Party. Once let this fear be removed, and we shall see Enrights and Devlins put in nomination from one end of the City to the other.

abstract: LAUNGH. -- The hull of the steam tug Thomas Freeborn was successfully launched Saturday afternoon at 1 o'clock, from the yard of her builders, Messrs. LAWRENCE & FOULKES, at Williamsburgh. Her dimensions are, length of keel 140 feet, 26 feet beam, and 9 feet depth of hold, 50 feet outside the guards. Her hull is built entirely of well seasoned cak, the ceiling of yellow pine; she has a 14-inch kelson running the length of her and two of 7 inches on her bilge. Has 9 feet dead wood forward, and 7 feet aft, every deck beam is kneed, and bolted, and she is every way built in the most substantial manner. Her engine will be put in at the Allaire Works. She will have a 40-inch cylinder and 8 feet stroke -- about 350 horse power. It will be a beam engine, with all the useful improvements. Her total cost will not be far from $30,000; is owned by Mr. RICHARD SQUIRES, and others of this City, and will be commanded by that experienced pilot and great favorite OTIS F. MORRELL. She is named after one of our Sandy Hook pilots, who lost his life while in the discharge of his duty on board the ship John Minturn, some nineteen years ago, on the Jersey coast. She will be ready for service about the 1st of January.

abstract: -- Mr. MCLANE's resignation of the Mexican mission will surprise nobody. That it came no sooner is the only warrant for surprise. Selected for acknowledged intelligence and ability to arrange a treaty with that Republic, demanded not only by obvious public expediency, but by the common voice of the country, Mr. MCLANE brought back from Mexico a convention, the conditions of which were infinitely more favorable to our interests than there had been any reason to anticipate. He also brought more reliable information as to the state of parties and affairs in that distracted Republic than either the Government or the public had previously possessed. The rejection of this treaty by the Senate, and the refusal of the President to take any further steps in the matter, rendered Mr. MCLANE's mission comparatively useless, and he has accordingly resigned. In the present condition of affairs in that country, however, the pesence of a representative of this country is greatly to be desired.

abstract: M. BERGER'S FAREWELL. This celebrated billiard-player takes his departure for Boston to-day, having inaugurated a great taste for the French threeball carom game of billiards.
lead_paragraph: M. BERGER'S FAREWELL. This celebrated billiard-player takes his departure for Boston to-day, having inaugurated a great taste for the French threeball carom game of billiards. He gave his last exhibition New-York at PHELAN's, on Saturday evening, and excelled himself in the brilliancy of his fancy and masse shots, before a large audience. He played his twenty-fifth even game with professional players, by beating Mr. WHITE 58 in 100. His victories over professionals -- whom he has beaten every game -- have averaged 56 points in 100; and his victories in 21 discount games with amateurs have averaged 70 points in 100. abstract: DEATH AND SUSPICION OF FOUL PLAY. -- An inquest was commenced on Saturday at Hudson City, before Coroner ACKERMAN and a Jury, upon the body of a man named PATRICK CORCORAN, a laborer in the tunnel, who died on Friday morning from injuries received by falling or being thrown down shaft No. 7, at the bottom of which he was found in an insensible condition, and expired soon after being removed. From the testimony elicited on the investigation, it appeared that the deceased had a difficulty with some of his fellow-workmen on the night previous, which fact aroused suspicion that he had been foully dealt with. As several important witnesses could not be found, the inquest was adjourned till this morning at 10 o'clock. PATRICK DAVIS, a man suspected of knowing all about the occurrence, was held as a witness by the Coroner, and in default of ball, committed to the County Jail.

abstract: By the steamship Vanderbilt, which arrived at this port yesterday, we receive four days' later European advices. The Italian news is important, and, summed up briefly, announces the total defeat of the Bourbon army, and the polling of one million three hundred thousand Neapolitan votes in favor of annexation to Sardinia.
lead_paragraph: By the steamship Vanderbilt, which arrived at this port yesterday, we receive four days' later European advices. The Italian news is important, and, summed up briefly, announces the total defeat of the Bourbon army, and the polling of one million three hundred thousand Neapolitan votes in favor of annexation to Sardinia. The Piedmontese and Garibaldian army, under the command of King VICTOR EMANUEL, crossed the Garigliano on the 3d, and attacked the Royalists, gaining a most complete victory. The Royalists dispersed, and left baggage, ammunition and an immense number of prisoners in the hands of the conquerors. They were pursued to Gaeta, and, at latest accounts, the Piedmontese had occupied positions commanding that town. King VICTOR EMANUEL was to enter Naples on the 6th inst. It is now said that the Austrians have suddenly ceased to send troops towards the Lombard frontier, and it is surmised that, since his failure to obtain promises of aid from Russia and Prussia at Warsaw, the Emperor has relinquished his aggressive designs. Count RECHBERG has addressed to the representatives of Austria abroad a circular, note, in which he makes it clearly understood that non-intervention in the affairs of Italy was agreed upon, and that the three Northern Courts would do nothing which might provoke a war. An official decree, signed by GARIBALDI, confiscates the property of the Ex-King of Naples. Among the miscellaneous news received by this arrival is the announcement of the death of Admiral Sir CHARLES NAPIER. A dispatch from LORD ELGIN, British Ambassador to China, states that the Emperor of China desires peace, though he is not yet prepared to concede all the Allied demands.

abstract: The first advices from the election on the Pacific shore came to hand yesterday. They announce a most unexpected development of the Republican vote in California, rendering the contest an exceedingly close one between the Douglas and Lincoln tickets; though the latest reports accord the State to the former.
lead_paragraph: -- The first advices from the election on the Pacific shore came to hand yesterday. They announce a most unexpected development of the Republican vote in California, rendering the contest an exceedingly close one between the Douglas and Lincoln tickets; though the latest reports accord the State to the former. Mr. BRECKINRIDGE lags sadly behind his leading competitors, while BELL might as well be dropped from the count. The result, beyond its testimony to the growing popularity of the Republican creed, even without the circle of our Eastern influences, is only important in its bearing upon the question of the United States Senatorship. The term of Dr. GWIN -- a most active and subservient adherent of the Buchanan Administration -- will expire on the 4th of March next. Determined to compel a reelection, GWIN has stumped the State, and freely spent his fortune, to secure a favorable Legislature -- one that would overlook his delinquencies in regard to the Overland mail and Lime Point, and in defiance of a distinctly-uttered public opinion give him another prolonged opportunity to misrepresent the State. The attempt has failed. The Legislature will be controlled by the Douglas party, who, there is reason to believe, will prefer to make a selection as agreeable to the Republicans as the choice of Col. BAKER in Oregon, rather than alienate so powerful a minority as the Republicans will be in that body. At all events, the suppression of GWIN is a victory in itself. The slaughter of these personal friends of the Executive is not likely to find sympathy anywhere outside of the White House.

abstract: Among the mass of questionable dispatches from the South, is one to the effect that the secession mania, is rampant in Texas, and that the popular feeling vents itself in raising the Lone Star flag, and in clamor for independence.
lead_paragraph: Among the mass of questionable dispatches from the South, is one to the effect that the secession mania is rampant in Texas, and that the popular feeling vents itself in raising the Lone Star flag, and in clamor for independence. We must say this is peculiarly graceless on the part of Texas. It was only the other day we incorporated that Commonwealth in the Union, at the cost of a war, which has left its monument in a debt of more than sixty millions of dollars, upon which we are faithfully paying, and are likely to continue to pay, a quite formidable interest. We also assumed the debt of the new comer; took its navy off its hands; adjusted its boundary to its satisfaction; gave it lands for its railroads; and have connived at a snug little business in the way of Slave-trading, among the islands and bayous about Indianola. Having secured all these advantages from its Federal relations, now to step out of the Union bearing them along, and leaving the widowed sisterhood remaining to foot the bill, smacks strongly of ingratitude; and, we repeat, Texas in merely proposing such a course, ought to be deeply ashamed of herself. The fact casts suspicion upon her motives in originally seeking admission to the Union. If its brief association with the rest is not to be accounted for by these selfish considerations, we shall be at a loss to reason upon it; and can only exclaim with the epitaph:

abstract: To-day extensive preparations will be made at Governor's Island to dispatch a large force of United States soldiers to California. They are to strengthen the First Regiment of United States Dragoons and the Sixth Regiment of Infantry.
lead_paragraph: To-day extensive preparations will be made at Governor's Island to dispatch a large force of United States soldiers to California. They are to strengthen the First Regiment of United States Dragoons and the Sixth Regiment of Infantry. The steamship Pacific will take them out. The soldiers will consist of two hundred men, who are to be distributed among the short companies of the Regiments named. They will be officered as follows: Lieut.-Col. MERCHANT will be in command, assisted by Capts. WHITTLESEY and DAVIDSON, Lieuts. MCKEE, BAKER, WORTH and RILEY, Sixth Infantry, Lieut. QUATTLEBAUM. Ninth Infantry, and Assistant Surgeon SHORT. On the arrival of the recruits at San Francisco Lieut.-Col. MERCHANT will resume command of the Third Artillery at the Presidio, when Lieut.-Col. NAUMAN will repair to Fort Vancouver, W.T., to command the Artillery School of Practice. On his arrival there the headquarters of the Fourth Infantry will be removed to Fort Dallas.

abstract: Fifty-one vessels arrive at this port during the quarantine season recently closed which had cases of yellow fever on board, either on the voyage home or at ports from which they sailed. One hundred and nineteen cases of sickness were reported in the ports of clearance, and deaths in port twenty-eight, besides a large number of cases sent to hospital.
lead_paragraph: Fifty-one vessels arrive at this port during the quarantine season recently closed which had cases of yellow fever on board, either on the voyage home or at ports from which they sailed. One hundred and nineteen cases of sickness were reported in the ports of clearance, and deaths in port twenty-eight, besides a large number of cases sent to hospital. There were eighty cases of sickness on the homeward passage, of which thirty-four died. Ten cases of yellow fever were sent to the floating hospital, all of whom are reported to have recovered except one. The infected ports were principally Rio Janeiro, Bahia, Pernambuco, Para, Aspinwall, Curacoa, Buen Ayres (a small island in the Caribbean Sea,) Belize, San Juan, and Ponce, P.R.; Havana, Matanzas, and one or two small ports in Cuba, and one case of yellow fever from Charleston, S.C. This patient died just prior to the arrival of the vessel, and the body was buried on Staten Island.

abstract: "It may be assumed confidently that the delegations from all the Southern States will be fully represented, as usual. They intend to make it a stirring session, and the Secessionists entertain the hope of raising such an issue as will consolidate the South in a compact column, to be moved under the orders of the leaders, who are now engaged in a race of ultraism with each other, in order to secure the ultimate command of this sectional movement. There is no excess of which some of them are not capable, and the public need not be surprised if revolutionary proceedings should be adopted to prevent the formal declaration of Mr. LINCOLN's election. The resolution offered in the Georgia Legislature, instructing her representatives in Congress to resist the counting of the votes of nine States alleged to have nullified the Fugitive Slave law, was doubtless suggested by Mr. Toombs, and is only a part of the programme concocted by the Disunionists in Congress, in the expected contingency of Mr. FREMONT's election, namely -- to withdraw the South from the hall of the House of Representatives when the votes of the Electoral College were to be counted. That conspiracy was deliberately planned here, and the parties engaged in it entered into an agreement, as they did at the last session, to resist Mr. SHERMAN's election as Speaker. The leaders were just as desperate then as now, and regarded the possible loss of power and patronage with equal resentment. There was no 'irrepressible conflict,' or 'John Brown affair' then, but still they had other pretexts which would have been made to serve the same end."

abstract: LA ROCHEFOUCAULD assures us that there is always something gratifying in the mishaps of our best friends; and whether the maxim of the social sage be sound or not in the relatians of man with man, it has an undeniable application to the intercourse of States.
lead_paragraph: LA ROCHEFOUCAULD assures us that there is always something gratifying in the mishaps of our best friends; and whether the maxim of the social sage be sound or not in the relatians of man with man, it has an undeniable application to the intercourse of States. We are extremely fond, for example, of our English cousins, and have the utmost confidence in their equal regard for ourselves. We have just entertained their royal boy with the best of homage and of honor that our rude democracy had to offer, and we make no doubt that in return the tidings of the sore trouble which has overtaken our Southern borders will be received with decorous lamentations and respectable sympathy by the British public. And yet it is not in human nature -- at least, not in the nature of the human body politic -- that we should forbear a grim smile of satisfaction over the lame and impotent conclusion which seems about to overtake the haughty and heroic diplomacy of our British friends in China. They must think no harm of us if we laugh at them a little in the face of the commentary with which they are now favoring us upon that ancient ballad wherein we read that "The King of France, with forty thousand men, Marched up the hill, -- and then marched down again."

abstract: BROOKLYN COMMON COUNCIL. -- A regular meeting of the Board of Aldermen was held last evening. President KALBFLEISCH in the chair. Under the "special order" a report of the Finance Committee was called up from the table, in favor of authorizing the Comptroller, under direction of the Finance Committee, to borrow, from time to time, upon the credit of the city, such moneys as may be necessary to pay 70 per cent. on all contracts for street improvements, when certified to as having been completed, and the assessments for the same are confirmed by the Common Council, and that he, in like manner, be authorized to issue the bonds of the city in payment thereof, said bonds to be called "Assessment Bonds," and to be redeemed in the manner provided in the act of April 16, 1860. Some discussion was had as to the policy of ordering the issue of bonds, to be made as required for use, with the special purpose named, but all amendments were voted down, and the original resolution was adopted. A furlough of four months was granted to the Street Commissioner, on account of ill health. Considerable routine business was transacted, when the Board adjourned till Wednesday evening next.

abstract: WINTER GARDER. TOBIN'S comedy, "The Honeymoon," is seldom placed upon the stage now-adays, although it is one of those last century triumphs That our grandames and grandsires enjoyed immensely. It is good of its kind, but not the best. When it is revived once in three or four years, it is played often enough.
lead_paragraph: WINTER GARDER. -- TOBIN's comedy, "The Honeymoon," is seldom placed upon the stage now-a-days, although it is one of those last century triumphs that our grandames and grandsires enjoyed immensely. It is good of its kind, but not the best. When it is revived once in three or four years, it is played often enough. But when a great actress appears in the part of Juliana, all habitues of the theatre are sure to be there, and novices, who have never seen the comedy, cannot resist the temptation to judge for themselves. Consequently, notwithstanding the rain, we were not surprised, last night, to find the Winter Garden crowded. As nearly as we can recollect, it is about seven years since that Miss CUSHMAN, at the Broadway Theatre, last sustained the part of Juliana. In this character, as in all others she has played during her present engagement, she has not improved -- that were out of the question -- but she has shown herself to be equal to her best self in her best days. And in proof of that assertion it needs only to be stated that her present engagement, which will close with this week, is the most successful since her return from that first engagement in England, fifteen years ago, which gave her the renown of being then the finest actress in the two countries. She will play Meg Merrilies to-night, and repeat the part of Juliana in the "Honeymoon" to-morrow.

abstract: We have nothing new of special importance from the South this morning, with reference to the question of secession. Matters are reported to be quiet at all the principal points from which we naturally look for exciting dispatches.
lead_paragraph: We have nothing new of special importance from the South this morning, with reference to the question of secession. Matters are reported to be quiet at all the principal points from which we naturally look for exciting dispatches. We perceive the announcement that Gov. MOORE, of Louisiana, will convene the Legislature of that State on the 10th of December, but whether the announcement is made authoritatively or not does not appear. A telegram from Charleston states that the report that President BUCHANAN intends to take a decided stand against seceding States, is generally regarded as a joke. Judging from the tenor of our correspondent's letter from Washington, however, the Charlestonians will find it rather a serious joke. Our dispatches assert that a distinguished Southern Senator now at the National Capital -- possibly Mr. SLIDELL, of Louisiana, -- not only denies the right of secession, but thinks that the President is to blame in not giving the refractory States to understand immediately that the whole power of the Federal Government will be used against them in the event of any attempt to place the Federal laws at defiance. Another important indication on the side of the Union may be found in the fact that Judge WAYNE, of the Supreme Court, has written a letter in which he says that four-fifths of the citizens of Savannah are opposed to secession. We publish this morning a number of letters and communications from various sources having a bearing upon the matter, which be found interesting.

abstract: Fate gives to almost every public man who survives and continues in power for six months after the commission of any folly or offence, some special opportunity of redeeming his character and atoning for the injuries inflicted.
lead_paragraph: Fate gives to almost every public man who survives and continues in power for six months after the commission of any folly or offence, some special opportunity of redeeming his character and atoning for the injuries inflicted. The errors of public men are not of the kind that slumber; they are incessantly in motion, parading up and down the columns of newspapers, or swelling to yet greater, proportions amidst the heat and exaggeration of partisan assemblages. It must be willful and deliberate blindness which fails to see the point of departure from the right road; it must be criminal and determined obstinacy which refuses to retrace any steps in a wrong direction once taken. The American people are liberal, almost to a fault, in their judgments of public men. At the first evidence of repentance or a desire to pursue a juster course in future, it would seem as if a popular Act of Oblivion were suddenly passed, and the illustrious wrong-doer becomes a recipient of gratitude from those whom he no longer harasses. These truths are now likely to receive illustration from the closing scenes of Mr. BUCHANAN's term. On all sides there would appear a disposition to forget his share in producing the dangers which threaten and the injuries which afflict us. Let him but now be true to the Union, which four years ago intrusted him with its destinies, and it is yet possible that his name may live in our history as that of a President who, despite some grave and protracted errors in the commencement of his official career, atoned nobly for all mistakes towards its close by his firmness and wisdom in suppressing the greatest danger which has ever threatened our national existence.

abstract: The official returns of the election in Pennsylvania are now complete, with the exception of the small County of Forest, which gave CURTIN a majority of sixty.
lead_paragraph: -- The official returns of the election in Pennsylvania are now complete, with the exception of the small County of Forest, which gave CURTIN a majority of sixty. The result is simply amazing. The entire vote is 475,000, a figure so slightly exceeding that of 1856, as to supply a just basis of comparison. The majority of LINCON over the Fusion ticket is a fraction less than ninety-three thousand; over DOUGLAS, 251,168; over BELL, 255,764; over all opposition, 62,518. The majority against the Republicans in 1856 was 165,011; and we therefore learn that at least 175,000 voters who were opposed at that time to the Republicans, have united themselves to that party, and assisted in raising Mr. LINCOLN to the Presidency. So extraordinary a change, embracing as it does little less than one-half the voting population of the State, has no precedent in political history. If the seal of condemnation were wanting to the record of Mr. BUCHANAN's Administration, it is surely affixed by this marvelous revulsion of feeling against him in his own State.

lead_paragraph: While some of our own States are demonstrating their higher civilization by cries of secession, the weak little States of Central America, which have had such a disastrous experience of disunion, are earnestly looking forward to the reverse as the balm for all their wounds and the cure for all their sorrows. The States of Central America have been hitherto kept separate by that same spirit of political demagogueism and ambition that is now seeking to withdraw South Carolina from the North American Confederation; for in Central America, where the people are far less instructed and less sensible than they are here, demagogues have been allowed to lead them as they please.

abstract: As it is just possible that a few of our readers may not know what or where the building is, an account of whose formal opening is to form the subject matter of this paragraph, we will briefly tell them. Although staggering beneath pyramidical piles of brick and mortar, and crowned with castles for the abode of any and everything else, New-York has long lacked one thing to complete its metropolitan character, and this was a home for the arts. People wereprivileged to drink gin in palaces, but compelled to worship art in "garrets." Mr. H.W. DERBY, a gentleman well known to the public as proprietor of a collection of paintings, commonly called Mr. Dusseldorf's Gallery, shrewdly guessed at this want, and determined to meet it. Opposite to Laura Keene's Theatre, and lettered No. 625 Broadway, stood an old tumble-down building; around this Mr. Aladdin DERBY drew a magic circle of dollars; waved his hand once, twice, thrice; whispered in an architect's car, and lo! the old bricks took unto themselves wings, vanished like pebbles in water, or dew in air, and in their stead arose a marble palace, several stories in height and running back in the rear to a fabulous length. Into this wonder of a night, Mr. DERBY whisked Mr. Dusseldorf's Gallery, along with Mr. JARVES' collection, and now these pictures have a local habitation as well as a name. Not only this, but New-York has an Art Exchange and a literary lounging-place for all time. It is pleasant to go thither in these troublous times and hob-a-nob with the unruffled countenances that gaze from the velveted walls. There Othello, unmindful of the additions to his audience, stirs Desdemona's blood with tales of the dangers he has passed; and grand JOHN HUSS, with clasped hands and face upturned in prayer, kneels to receive the crown of martyrdom, sending a prayer to Heaven for his murderers, before his soul is borne thither on the winged flames to accuse them. Turning from Mr. Dusseldorf's collection, which occupies the main body of the hall, we enter an octagonal vestibule, and are in the presence of the old masters. Those queer, quaint pictures in fantastic frames, many of them limned on wood, and with back-grounds of gold, were painted long, long years ago, when Art was in its infancy and Venice was in the hands of the Doges. Many of their figures in their angularity look as though they might have been drawn by Egyptian or Chinese artists, yet they are the work of the old Italian masters, and that little 6x6 thing which you were scarce willing to hang in your parlor would be cheap at 15,000 francs. Just notice the tints; as warm and fresh as though laid on yesterday, and yet their backs are dim with the dust that gathered on them when WILLIAM the Conqueror was King. You have a framed history of Art, in its dawn and progress, in the pictures which hang upon those octagonal walls.
lead_paragraph: As it is just possible that a few of our readers may not know what or where the building is, an account of whose formal opening is to form the subject matter of this paragraph, we will briefly tell them. Although staggering beneath pyramidical piles of brick and mortar, and crowned with castles for the abode of any and everything else, New-York has long lacked one thing to complete its metropolitan character, and this was a home for the arts. People wereprivileged to drink gin in palaces, but compelled to worship art in "garrets." Mr. H.W. DERBY, a gentleman well known to the public as proprietor of a collection of paintings, commonly called Mr. Dusseldorf's Gallery, shrewdly guessed at this want, and determined to meet it. Opposite to Laura Keene's Theatre, and lettered No. 625 Broadway, stood an old tumble-down building; around this Mr. Aladdin DERBY drew a magic circle of dollars; waved his hand once, twice, thrice; whispered in an architect's car, and lo! the old bricks took unto themselves wings, vanished like pebbles in water, or dew in air, and in their stead arose a marble palace, several stories in height and running back in the rear to a fabulous length. Into this wonder of a night, Mr. DERBY whisked Mr. Dusseldorf's Gallery, along with Mr. JARVES' collection, and now these pictures have a local habitation as well as a name. Not only this, but New-York has an Art Exchange and a literary lounging-place for all time. It is pleasant to go thither in these troublous times and hob-a-nob with the unruffled countenances that gaze from the velveted walls. abstract: Whatever mere partisan politicians may say, no reflecting man can dismiss the secession movement at the South as of trifling consequence. In spite of prejudice, all are compelled to acknowledge that it is a great popular movement, impressive on account of its unanimity and evident sincerity, and important by reason of its bearing upon the destinies,
lead_paragraph: Whatever mere partisan politicians may say, no reflecting man can dismiss the secession movement at the South as of trifling consequence. In spite of prejudice, all are compelled to acknowledge that it is a great popular movement, -- impressive on account of its unanimity and evident sincerity, and important by reason of its bearing upon the destinies, social and political, of our common country. As we have more than once said, we are not surprised at the fact of a disunion movement. We have anticipated it for months. We saw clearly enough that the political leaders of the South, -- especially those of the Breckinridge party, were so thoroughly committed, that they could not possibly permit the election of LINCOLN to pass without an attempt to arouse the South to resistance. Such an attempt we expected; -- and we were quite prepared to see it quite as vigorous and violent, and even more rapid in its practical steps, than it has proved to be.

abstract: MR. TASISTRO's RECITALS OF SHAKESPEARE FROM MEMORY. -- At Clinton Hall, Astor-place, this evening, Mr. FITZGERALD TASISTRO will recite the play of "Othello" entirely from memory, under the auspices of the Mercantile Library Association. The recitation, also from memory, of the entire play of "Hamlet," by this gentleman, last week, was a wonderful example of memonic power, and gave evidence also of considerable histrionic ability. Many actors and actresses of note have added to their laurels by their recitations of SHAKESPEARE, with the text before them; but Mr. TASISTRO relies entirely upon memory, discarding the aid of a book altogether, and never varies from the text.

abstract: Chamberlain PLATT has refused, on technical grounds, to appear before the Special Committee appointed by the Board of Aldermen "with power to investigate and report all necessary information concected with the custody and safe-keeping of the City funds, the amount of interest, paid thereon by the institution in which such funds are deposited, together with such other information as, in the opinion of the Committee.
lead_paragraph: Chamberlain PLATT has refused, on technical grounds, to appear before the Special Committee appointed by the Board of Aldermen "with power to investigate and report all necessary information concected with the custody and safe-keeping of the City funds, the amount of interest, paid thereon by the institution in which such funds are deposited, together with such other information as, in the opinion of the Committee, the interests of the City or the public may require." Mr. PLATT, through Mr. JAMES R. WHITING, his counsel, denies the authority of the Committee to compel his attendance, and cavalierly refers them to the Comptroller for any information they may desire, thereby practically refusing himself to appear or to answer any questions in reference to the public funds under his control. The reference to the Comptroller is palpably absurd -- that officer, in the first place, having no knowledge of the subject-matter, nor any possibility of obtaining it, except through statements volunteered to him by Mr. PLATT; and, secondly, the special Committee of the Board of Aldermen most assuredly having no power to compel the attendance of the Comptroller to answer questions properly belonging to the Chamberlain's Department.

lead_paragraph: The accounts that reach us from Syria represent, that the Christians of that country are still in the most deplorable state of suffering and destitution. Thanks to the efficiency of French intervention, they are no longer in dread of perishing by the sword, but the no less, alarming fate of perishing by famine appears now to be staring many of them in the face. Through the charity of Christians in Europe and America, a vast amount of actual suffering has been alleviated; but a great deal of the money that was collected has been expended, and the approach of the rainy season offers the most dreary prospect for many thousands of houseless wanderers.

abstract: There are other things, it seems, beside chickens and curses which come home to roost. The State Department at Washington, under the benign Administration of Mr. BUCHANAN and his immediate predecessor, has flooded the four quarters of the world with diplomatic agents of the United States, who were sent this one to Timbuctoo and that to Spitzbergen, not because the United States had any earthly business to transact with Timbuctoo or Spitzbergen, but simply because the agents aforesaid were hungry jackals of the Democratic horde whose howls made life unendurable to the Government, and for whom some prey must be provided at all risks. These exiles, for their country's harm, have fulfilled their mission. They have vexed the souls of decent Americans more than all other incidents of travel, and they have contributed almost as much as the imbecility of the Cabinet policy itself to the degradation of our influence abroad. It is a satisfaction to know that they are returning to plague their principals. One of them, a person of no particular origin or nationality, who had been sent to protect our extensive interests in Moldo-Wallachia, has just been ejected by the police from the Bureau of Foreign Affairs for pertinaciously haunting that eyry of diplomacy with clamors for compensation for "services rendered."

abstract: REPUBLICAN PRIMARY ELECTIONS.-The election, by the Republican Party, of delegates to the various nominating Conventions for the coming Charter election, took place last evening. The polls were held at the head-quarters of the Republican Associations of each Ward, and were kept open from 7  to 9  P.M. Considerable interest was manifested in this election, and a large vote was polled, although there was no exciting contest between rival delegates in any of the Wards.
lead_paragraph: REPUBLICAN PRIMARY ELECTIONS. -- The election, by the Republican Party, of delegates to the various nominating Conventions for the coming Charter election, took place last evening. The polls were held at the head-quarters of the Republican Associations of each Ward, and were kept open from 7 to 9 P.M. Considerable interest was manifested in this election, and a large vote was polled, although there was no exciting contest between rival delegates in any of the Wards. The policy urged upon the Republican Party by a certain morning paper, of making no independent nominations for the Charter election, but of selecting candidates from the nominees of other parties, appears to meet wtth no favor; but on the contrary, so far as the prevailing sentiment could be gathered from conversations around the polls last evening, it appears to be the determination of the Republicans to make their own nominations, to support them with their own strength, and, so far as possible, to elect them with their own votes.

abstract: The markets are rather depressed this week. With 4,000 beeves on sale at Forty-fourth-street, yesterday, and more expected to-day, the prospect for drovers was not flattering. It will be recollected the market was overstocked last week, and butchers laid in freely, besides leaving some cattle unsold. Of course their wants were not great yesterday, and a smaller number than usual were sold on Tuesday at a decline of about 1/4c., net weight, from last week. A few of the best, which were really fine, although not ranking as premiums, brought 9 1/2c., but very nice fat steers could be had, with very little searching for them, at 9c. Common grades went off slowly at 7 1/2c.@8c. There will be a sufficient number of cattle in the yards to-day to satisfy the wants of all, and quite likely lower prices will prevail. There was a disposition on the part of holders to crowd off all they could the first day, but it was up-hill work.

abstract: A great Republican jubilee was held yesterday at Springfield, Ill., the home of Mr. LINCOLN. It was intended primarily as a congratulatory county meeting, but it unexpectedly assumed vast proportions, and was attended with demonstrations of the greatest significance. The town of Springfield was illuminated last night in the most brilliant manner, and the most intense enthusiasm was displayed.
lead_paragraph: A great Republican jubilee was held yesterday at Springfield, Ill., the home of Mr. LINCOLN. It was intended primarily as a congratulatory county meeting, but it unexpectedly assumed vast proportions, and was attended with demonstrations of the greatest significance. The town of Springfield was illuminated last night in the most brilliant manner, and the most intense enthusiasm was displayed. The Wide-Awakes formed in procession, and proceeding to the house of Mr. LINCOLN, he was forced to appear before them and make a short address. The words he spoke were few, but their import, so far as they had a bearing upon the present agitation, were extremely conciliatory. A verbatim report of them will be found elsewhere. Speeches were also made at the Wigwam by Senator TRUMBULL, Don PLATT and others. Mr. TRUMBULL's speech, a synopsis of which we also give, was listened to with the most eager curiosity, as it was conceived to be an exposition of the policy which would govern the incoming Administration. Regarded in this light, it was a most important address, and Mr. TRUMBULL seems to have been fully alive to the responsibilities of the occasion. The South will find very little to cavil at in the sentiments uttered.

lead_paragraph: Ira B. Davis et al. vs. Five Hundred and Seventy-four Bags of Coffee. -- The libelants were the owners of tho schooner G. H. Townsend. In June, 1859, the master of the vessel chartered her to Christian Thomsen, for a voyage from this port to Rio Janeiro and back. The charter party contained the usual clause binding the vessel and the cargo to be laden on board for the faithful performance of the agreement. The vessel arrived in Rio, and Schroeder & Co., for whom Thomsen executed the charter party, shipped on board the coffee in question, for which the master executed a bill of lading, by which it was consigned to Troost, Schroeder & Co., on payment of freight. No reference was made to the charter party in the bill of lading, On the arrival of the vessel in New-York, the master demanded the amount of charter money then due, being $3,224 54 before he would deliver the coffee. The consignees offered to pay $270 21, the amount of freight due by the bill of lading, and thereupon the libel in this case was filed to recover the charter money.

abstract: HAYTIAN SCRIP. -- The trial of ADRIAN B. HARCQ, for issuing counterfeit Haytian Scrip of the denomination of $2, was brought to a close in the Kings County Court of Sessions, before Judge GARRISON, and resuited in the Jury finding the accused guilty of forgery in the third degree, the punishment for which is five years' imprisonment or less, at the discretion of the Court. HARCQ was arrested in July last by Detective Officers RAYNOR and VAN WAGNER, just after he had disposed of $15,000 worth of the counterfeit for $500 to Mr. WOOD, mate of the brig Baltimore, then about to sail for Porte-au-Prince. At the residence of accused the officers recovered scrip nominally valued at about $100,000, and subsequently secured in Germany all the implements used in the manufacture of the counterfeit. Detective RAYNOR will proceed to Hayti on Saturday next to deliver the counterfeit money and materials for making it, to that Government.

abstract: -It is evident that somebody is engaged largely in the business of inventing reports calculated to increase the feelings of sectional hostility that, already damage the business, disturb the peace, and threaten the safety of our country. The story that the steamer Augusta was not allowed to land her passengers at Savannah, is an instance in point. It was circulated through the City, and published in the evening papers yesterday, -- and yet it is pronounced by the owners of the steamer to have been a fabrication from beginning to end. A large proportion of the telegraphic dispatches from the South are of the same character, and sent for the same malicious purpose.

abstract: The meeting of congratulation, which was, at first, intended for a county jubilee, has, unexpectedly, assumed gigantic proportions. An immense and excited crowd is in attendance, and the illumination is nearly universal and brilliant beyond anything ever seen in the West. All the public buildings and a vast number of stores and dwellings are ablaze with fantastic devices. In the dome of the State-House four locomotive head lights are blazing, clearly visible for many miles.

lead_paragraph: Whether the Roman Emperor NERO was or was not an incendiary as will as a fiddler may be held, perhaps, to be an open question by that large class of philanthropists who take a deep interest in the reputation of every historical scoundrel. Practically all the world agrees in believing that this accomplished Caesar first set fire to his capital and then serenaded himself during the conflagration; and we are accordingly at liberty to charge that his soul has passed, by metempsychosis, into the New-York Common Council. These enlightened patriots have just enlivened the panic of the City and the perturbation of the whole country by a graceful little excursion into the serene realms of Art. Whether urged by their brilliant social successes in the matter of yellow kid gloves and Japanese balls, or simply inspired by that soul of beauty which we are bound to suppose may dwell in things hideous, does not appear, the Fathers of the City at their session of Monday evening voted themselves to be a company of critics and connoisseurs, and in that capacity forthwith proceeded to appropriate some thousands of dollars of the civic funds to the Muses. The development was unexpected, but its direction, we are happy to say, was eminently characteristic. Sculpture and Painting having both engaged their attention, these new Medici of the West selected a statue of the late GEORGE WASHINGTON, and a portrait of the living HARRY HOWARD, as the objects of their refined expenditure. The statue already exists, the portrait is to be.

abstract: The first trial in this Court, before Judge RUSSELL, yesterday, was that of William Sickles and Charles Parrinchiff, indicted for the robbery of Samuel Robinson, on the 30th of October last, of the sum of $3. Robinson was standing in front of an oyster-bench, where he was eating, at the corner of Thomas-street and West Broadway, when he was knocked down and his money taken from him by the prisoners. The proof was very clear, and a verdict of guilty was returned. Prisoners were persons of very bad character, and the Court sentenced them to Sing Sing -- Parrinchiff for eleven years and six months, and Sickles for twelve years and six months.

abstract: There is no mistaking the motives, however various, of those journals which so promptly denounced our suggested compromise of the only remaining subject of controversy between the North and South the Fugitive Slave law.
lead_paragraph: There is no mistaking the motives, however various, of those journals which so promptly denounced our suggested compromise of the only remaining subject of controversy between the North and South -- the Fugitive Slave law. These virtuous devotees of principle, who are shocked at the idea of soothing sectional animosities, and satisfying constitutional obligations, by paying the injured parties in money, rather than by a specific return of their lost property, belong to three or four different parties. First, there are the Disunionists, who would deprecate any settlement of the vexed question, and who delight in nothing so much as the circulation of inflammatory appeals to passion, whether they proceed from the North or South; while they carefully conceal or studiously pervert every attempt on the part of Republicans and friends of the Union, to pour oil upon the troubled waters.

abstract: THE CHILDRENS'S AID SOCIETY A LARGE PARTY OF BOYS FOR THE WEST The hospitable people of the Western States continue to receive, with open arms and affectionate welcome, the numerous companies of poor destitute children, sent out to better their fortunes by the generous benevolence of the Christian philanthropists of New-York, through the operations...
lead_paragraph: THE CHILDRENS's AID SOCIETY -- A LARGE PARTY OF BOYS FOR THE WEST. -- The hospitable people of the Western States continue to receive, with open arms and affectionate welcome, the numerous companies of poor destitute children, sent out to better their fortunes by the generous benevolence of the Christian philanthropists of New-York, through the operations of the Children's Aid Society. A company of fifty-three children, mostly boys, ranging from 7 to 16 years, left New-York yesterday afternoon from the office of this institution, under the charge of Mr. H. FRIEDGEN, who has given some hundreds of additional young inmates to the households of Indiana. They were neatly dressed, and all presented bright and happy ta[???]es which reflected joyous feelings. The Newsboy's Lodging House sent forth a little band of its lodgers -- their motto. "Ho! for the West." The stages which conveyed the children to the depot drew up before the Metropolitan Bank, where a meeting of the Trustees of the Children's Aid Society was being held. The children were addressed in brief by Mr. BRACE and by Mr. C.C. TRACY, who gave them some good advice in respect to their future, which they promised to keep faithfully.

abstract: Boston has its panic! abstract: -- The Lancaster Express says: "We notice that a Washington correspondent now and then amuses himself by speculating in regard to the future home of President Buchanan -- some positively asserting that after the fourth of March he will make his home in Virginia. To save the Washington letter-writer any further trouble on this point, we feel disposed to settle it by stating that Wheatland, the Mecca of the political pilgrims in 1856, is to remain the home of Ex-President Buchanan. Some weeks ago a couple of  the subordinates of the White House came on here, and under the instructions of Mr. Buchanan, proceeded to put the premises in proper order for reoccupancy. Next Summer Wheatland will be a more attractive residence than ever, and, indeed, no more beautiful retreat for a retired President could be found in the country than Wheatland. There Mr. Buchanan will have a fine opportunity amid the inspiration afforded by a quiet, invigorating, picturesque rural retreat, to pursue the literary labors to which, it is understood, he proposes to devote the remainder of his days, after vacating the White House.

abstract: It seems to be generally understood that President BUCHANAN does not assent to the theory of peaceful secession. He holds with every man of national reputation, who has ever expressed his opinion upon the subject, that the Constitution is binding upon the several States, and that no one State has a right to abolish it.
lead_paragraph: It seems to be generally understood that President BUCHANAN does not assent to the theory of peaceful secession. He holds with every man of national reputation, who has ever expressed his opinion upon the subject, that the Constitution is binding upon the several States, and that no one State has a right to abolish it. It is stated with confidence that he will present this view of the case in his Message, and will declare his purpose to enforce the laws of Congress. No one can be surprised at this, -- for it is not easy to see how he could possibly do otherwise without utterly repudiating the oath he has taken to support the Constitution and execute the laws made in pursuance thereof.

abstract: It is hardly probable that South Carolina will be allowed by the Border States to leave the Confederacy, and drag with her those of the extreme Southern States which most immediately sympathize with her, without at least a strenuous effort to obtain a General Convention of the South, for the purpose of discussing the grave matters involved.
lead_paragraph: It is hardly probable that South Carolina will be allowed by the Border States to leave the Confederacy, and drag with her those of the extreme Southern States which most immediately sympathize with her, without at least a strenuous effort to obtain a General Convention of the South, for the purpose of discussing the grave matters involved. The people of Maryland, it will be seen from our dispatches, are beginning to move in this matter, and the feeling that South Carolina has no right to secede, without a consultation, will probably assume the form of a demand that she shall respect a wish so generally expressed. Virginia, too, is striving for the same end, and may possibly be successful. A rumor prevailed yesterday, in Baltimore, that a conference recently took place between prominent South Carolinians and Virginians -- one of the latter said to be Senator HUNTER -- which it is hoped may result in the attainment of the desired end -- especially as several distinguished Georgians and Alabamians are said to be in the secret. A letter from Gov. LETCHER appears in one of the Richmond papers of yesterday, in answer to a somewhat impertinent one from a gentleman in Pennsylvania, which is generally conservative in its tone. He insists, however, that the only way by which disunion can be prevented is through the repeal of obnoxious laws', in Northern States, which are intended to conflict with the Fugitive Slave law. A bill has unanimously passed both branches of the Georgia Legislature which provides for the calling of a State Convention -- at what time does not appear. From South Carolina, of course, the talk is still of secession. Meantime, the money stringency continues, and bank suspensions are becoming common. Following the lead of the Farmers' Bank, all the others in Richmond, and also those of Petersburgh, suspended yesterday; and those of Baltimore have taken the same course.

abstract: The first business before Judge GOULD, yesterday, was the disposal of the case of John F. Williams, indicted for the murder of his wife. He had previously pleaded not guilty, but now withdrew his plea and changed it to guilty of manslaughter in the first degree. Counsel asked that the Court would deal leniently with the prisoner, as his intellect had been impaired by the previous habits of his life.
lead_paragraph: The first business before Judge GOULD, yesterday, was the disposal of the case of John F. Williams, indicted for the murder of his wife. He had previously pleaded not guilty, but now withdrew his plea and changed it to guilty of manslaughter in the first degree. Counsel asked that the Court would deal leniently with the prisoner, as his intellect had been impaired by the previous habits of his life. He had for a long time labored under the impression that somebody was going to murder him, and, therefore, he had often gone about with an open knife. He had a knife in this manner on the present occasion, but did not recollect at all what he had done.

abstract: The Rochester Union, of Tuesday, says: "A very valuable fugitive slave belonging to a Georgian, passed through this city to Canada on Wednesday night. His master took his servant to Baltimore on business a few days previous. The slave was a bookkeeper and confidential clerk.
lead_paragraph: -- The Rochester Union, of Tuesday, says: "A very valuable fugitive slave belonging to a Georgian, passed through this city to Canada on Wednesday night. His master took his servant to Baltimore on business a few days previous. The slave was a bookkeeper and confidential clerk. His master shut him up securely every night; but the darkey one evening suggested that he had one more bill to settle, whereupon the master told him to go and close it up. The slave went straight to the Philadelphia boat and asked employment. He exhibited free (forged) papers and hired out as a stoker. Arriving at Philadelphia, he started for Canada, where he now is."

abstract: UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPT TO BREAK OUT OF THE TOMBS. -- On Wednesday night, JOHN C. ADAMS, convicted of highway robbery, and EDWARD NETHERCUTT, under sentence for burglary, occupants of a cell on the lower corridor of the Tombs, attempted to escape by making a hole through the outer wall of the prison. Messrs. FINLAY and KELLOCK, the night keepers, on making the usual inspection of the cell, observed that a pocket handkerchief had been spread out against the wall. The prisoner ADAMS was orderedto take it down, but instead of doing so, he caught up the iron cover of the waste-pipe and attempted to knock Mr. FINLAY down. He was unable to effect his object, and after a severe struggle both he and his companion were secured, and confined separately. On examining the cell, it was found that the prisoners had broken the cross-piece from their iron bedstead, and used it as an instrument for making a breach in the wall, but they had not made much progress in carrying out their design. The prisoner ADAMS is the same person who escaped from the Jefferson Market Prison a few weeks ago, through the carelessness of one of the keepers. He and NETHERCUTT were yesterday both transferred to Sing Sing.

lead_paragraph: The public will do well to resume a habit much practiced three or four years ago, of discounting some sixty per cent. of rumors coming from Kansas. That we are on the eve of a repetition of the drama which at that time so agitated the country there is reason to apprehend. The opening scenes have much the same character. As then, the provoking causes originated at Washington; as then, the forms of law have been carefully used to screen the real aggressors; while the party which those inexorable forms have driven to desperation is paraded before the country as the wanton perpetrators of acts at once illegal and inhuman. In order to place the subject in a perfectly just light, it may be well to restate the facts.

abstract: We have received a great many communications denouncing the Herald for its systematic endeavors to aggravate the existing sectional and financial excitements of the country. We must decline to publish them. It is quite as much as we can do to manage our own journal, without undertaking, in addition, the management of our neighbor's.
lead_paragraph: We have received a great many communications denouncing the Herald for its systematic endeavors to aggravate the existing sectional and financial excitements of the country. We must decline to publish them. It is quite as much as we can do to manage our own journal, without undertaking, in addition, the management of our neighbor's. Besides this, we have very little respect for the judgment of any man who expects to accomplish anything by denunciations of the Herald, so long as it receives the support of the very parties whom it injures most. That paper is only doing now precisely what it has been doing from the first day of its existence. It has lived and prospered by feeding every flame that accident or design might kindle in the community. It has but one rule of conduct, and that is to minister to every excitement that seizes at any time upon the public mind, no matter how much damage it may inflict on individuals or communities.

abstract: Coroner WOOD, of Queens County, continued the investigation as to the murder of J.D. COLYER, at Shaw's Hotel, on Wednesday. District Attorney ARMSTRONG, who has taken a deep interest in this investigation from the first, conducted the examination. At 1 1/2 o'clock yesterday afternoon, officer LATURVILLE, of the Fifth Precinct Police, Brooklyn, brought JOSEPH LAMBERT, arrested on suspicion of having murdered Mr. COLYER, before the Coroner. LAMBERT manifested but little interest in the proceedings, and seemed in excellent spirits. He nodded to acquaintances with a smile, and his geueral conduct was that of an innocent man, if not, at least of one who did not realize the enormity of the offence with which he is charged.

abstract: A VIRAGO. -- A woman, named BARBARA FRY, on Tuesday night last, in a fit of jealousy, turned a pot of hot coffee into the face of her husband while he was asleep. A portion of the coffee poured down his throat, and, in the opinion of his medical attendant, he is fatally injured. On Thursday night Mrs. FRY was so excited by remorse at what she had done, that she jumped into the East River at the foot of South Third-street, with a view of ending her troubles in this world. Fortunately, she was rescued by Officer VAN DYKE, and she was yesterday committed to the cells by Justice CORNWELL to await the result of the injuries to her husband.

abstract: In this Court yesterday, before Judge RUSSELL, Walter A. Storia was arraigned on a charge of having obtained money upon false pretences. In July last
lead_paragraph: In this Court yesterday, before Judge RUSSELL, Walter A. Storia was arraigned on a charge of having obtained money upon false pretences. In July last he prepared a communication for the TIMES, which was published in our columns, appealing to the charitable for help, and representing himself to be a man of education, with a starving wife and child. He obtained in this manner a small sum. Upon investigation, his case was found to be only a pretended one, and himself an impostor. He was arrested and committed to the City Prison, where he had remained till yesterday, the Grand Jury having found no bill against him until the present term. He now pleaded guilty; and as he had already suffered nearly four months' confinement, his sentence was suspended, and he was discharged.

lead_paragraph: The most important news which we have this morning in connection with the secession movement, is of a financial character. It is announced that the Banks of Washington and Philadelphia, following the lead of those of Richmond and Baltimore, have suspended specie payments. This movement is generally commended in the localities immediately interested, and has had the effect to give more confidence in business circles. The Banks of Baltimore yesterday discounted to the amount of nearly a million dollars, and the merchants were correspondingly relieved. The suspension of the Banks in Philadelphia was on account of a run commenced upon them, and is in direct contravention of a State law. The hope is expressed, however, that the Governor will convene the Legislature in order that a special law may be passed to meet the exigency. One suspension took place in Charleston, South Carolina, yesterday -- that of the Farmers' and Mechanics' Bank. In Virginia, further suspensions took place in Norfolk, Portsmouth and Wheeling. From Boston we learn that should the emergency require it, the Banks there propose to discount to the extent of five millions. The sensation dispatches published in this City relative to the condition of the Cabinet on the question of secession, are now flatly contradicted on the very best authority. There may be, of course, differences of opinion relative to the right of a State to secede, but the propriety of the President's course in enforcing his own views, will not be questioned by any Cabinet officer. An evidence of the fact that Georgia is not disposed to blindly follow the lead of South Carolina, may be found in the fact that the Legislature of that State to-morrow, at the suggestion of Gov. BROWN in a special Message, will proceed to choose Presidential Electors. South Carolina maintains her extreme position of hostility towards the North, one evidence of which may be seen in the announcement that all the steerage passengers which reach Charleston on board the steamers from the Northern ports are immediately sent back. Meantime it is stated as an interesting fact, in our Washington dispatches, that no census returns have been received from that State -- they having all been withheld.

abstract: James Hogan, Thomas Maloney and James Flynn, all men about the age of twenty-one, were taken into custody yesterday by Officer Phillips, of the Twelfth Ward, on a warrant issued by Justice BROWNELL, charging them with arson.
lead_paragraph: James Hogan, Thomas Maloney and James Flynn, all men about the age of twenty-one, were taken into custody yesterday by Officer Phillips, of the Twelfth Ward, on a warrant issued by Justice BROWNELL, charging them with arson. On the night of the 11th inst. a fire was kindled under the stoop of a new frame building, situated on Third-avenue, between One Hundred and Eleventh and One Hundred and Twelfth streets, but it was soon extinguished by a Mr. Tiernan, who discovered it before it had attained much headway. The prisoners had been loitering about the premises, and they hurriedly left just previous to the breaking out of the flames. These acts having been elicited at an investigation of the circumstances by the Fire Marshal, Justice BROWNELL required the prisoners to furnish bail, each in the sum of $560, for further examination. The house was owned by a Mrs. Hazelton, and was valued at $1,500.

abstract: A few days since JOHN W. DODD, Esq., Auditor General of the State of Indiana, came to this City in the hope of securing the arrest of A.W. SPOONER, the President, and JOHN W. SWEET, the projector and manager of the "wild cat" banking concern, called the Boone County Bank, of Lebanon, Ind., which exploded early in the present month, with its notes in circulation to the amount of nearly half a million dollars. The banking enterprise was started by the parties mentioned, and their swindle is alleged to have been perpetrated by causing ten thousand genuine impressions of their notes (representing $280,000) to be Struck off, in addition to impressions for $50,000. These latter were sent to Indianapolis, where securities having been lodged with the State Auditor, they received his signature, and were put in the market. The other notes were also put in circulation, the name of the Auditor and the Register first having been fraudulently attached to them. As soon as the fraud was discovered, an official investigation was made, and the evidence against the projectors and officers of the concern appearing clear, all of them were arrested save SPOONER and SWEET, both of whom fled to this City. Detectives YOUNG, ELDER and MCCORD were engaged to look up the fugitives, and yesterday they succeeded in arresting SWEET at his residence in this City. A requisition upon Gov. MORGAN from the Executive of Indiana had already been presented for the return of the prisoner to that State, and last evening the former functionary announced his purpose to comply with the summons, if upon examination into the case to-day he shall find the facts to warrant him in so doing.

abstract: THE GREAT ROWING MATCH. The great rowing match with shell-boats, between Wm. H. DECKER and ANDREW FAY, took place yesterday afternoon, from the Jersey City Yacht Club House, foot of Van Vorststreet, in which Fay came out victorious. Between two and three thousand persons a large proportion of them from New-York and Brooklyn were present. It was a match for $250 a side.
lead_paragraph: THE GREAT ROWING MATCH. The great rowing match with shell-boats, between Wm. H. DECKER and ANDREW FAY, took place yesterday afternoon, from the Jersey City Yacht Club House, foot of Van Vorststreet, in which Fay came out victorious. Between two and three thousand persons a large proportion of them from New-York and Brooklyn were present. It was a match for $250 a side. Offers of $100 to $50, $75 to $20, and $10 to $1 on FAY, found no takers. The men got the word to start at 18 minutes past 3 o'clock, when DECKER took the lead, rounding the stake boat about two miles distant, about two lengths ahead; FAY came up gradually, and the two kept alongside for some distance, when FAY took the lead until nearing the Judges' stand, when he slacked up, allowing the bow of DECKER's boat to come up to the stern of his own, and then, with a few powerful strokes, shot ahead, coming in about one length in advance. Time, 25 minutes and 30 seconds; distance, about four miles. During the progress of the race about 30 feet of a bridge, constructed of old canal boats, gave way and a number of persons were partially immersed in the water.

abstract: From whatever cause arising, it is an undoubted fact that great difficulty has been experienced for the last three or four years in obtaining convictions against prisoners charged with receiving stolen goods. Some few of
lead_paragraph: From whatever cause arising, it is an undoubted fact that great difficulty has been experienced for the last three or four years in obtaining convictions against prisoners charged with receiving stolen goods. Some few of the petty order of junk-dealers have been found guilty and sentenced, in one or two cases, on evidence certainly admitting some possibilities of their innocence. But with the larger order of criminals engaged in the trade of making thieves and keeping them employed, all efforts to obtain convictions and sentence, even upon proofs the most ample, appear in some mysterious manner to have been thwarted. No portion of the blame for this failure of justice can extend to the public prosecutor or the General Superintendent of Police, both these officers having on all occasions manifested the most eager and active desire to secure the punishment of this class of offenders, who are the parent-sources of the whole family of larcenies -- a majority of the large burglaries committed being pre-arranged in the stores of those who afterwards dispose of the booty.

abstract: A curious swindle was recently perpetrated at Elizabeth City, N.J. Large numbers of tickets were sold at the various places designated, and un
lead_paragraph: -- A curious swindle was recently perpetrated at Elizabeth City, N.J. A man, of venerable appearance, on Thursday last, engaged Library Hall for a lecture on, "The Character of Benjamin Franklin;" by Hon. Edward Everett. Large numbers of tickets were sold at the various places designated, and on Friday evening quite a large audience was in attendance at the Hall, to enjoy the promised treat; but Mr. Everett did not come, and anxious inquirers learned that the money for the tickets sold at the drug store had been collected by the man pretending to be his agent. Those who had been taken in immediately started for the railroad depot, where they found the swindler. His appearance was somewhat changed, for he had discarded his gray locks in favor of a jet black moustache and whiskers; but he was detected, nevertheless, and speedily found his way to jail. At one time the indignation ran so high that there was a prospect of his receiving a lynching.
