lead_paragraph: The first business in this Court yesterday was the case of Franz Hoffman, indicted for murder. The jury had been impanneled on Wednesday, but the District-Attorney now consented to the withdrawal of a juror, and the case went off. The reasons for this course were given by Mr. Brady, who had been assigned as the prisoner's counsel. Until recently he had not had an opportunity to advise with his client, who does not speak English. A day or two ago, however, by the aid of the Court interpreter, he had learned that the prisoner, in the German wars, while a soldier in the regular army, had received a sabre wound in his head, of which the scar still gave evidence. Medical advice had been obtained concerning his sanity, and the result, communicated to the District-Attorney, had been such as to induce the prosecution to giant a delay, until, if necessary, a commission may be issued to take testimony in Germany, where all the prisoner's relatives and friends reside, and where the officer is under whom he served at the time of recovery from his wound.

abstract: We have already admitted the serious character of the secession movement, and the duty of every citizen to do everything in his power to allay public excitement, North and South, and bring the public mind into a proper mood for canvassing the question on its merits. We
lead_paragraph: We have already admitted the serious character of the secession movement, and the duty of every citizen to do everything in his power to allay public excitement, North and South, and bring the public mind into a proper mood for canvassing the question on its merits. We have also very freely acknowledged that it is the duty of Republicans everywhere to exercise a magnanimous forbearance alike in their discussions and their acts, upon this subject. They have taken upon themselves the responsibilities of the Government, and they are under solemn obligations to discharge them in the spirit of conciliation and with a sincere desire to harmonize conflicting interests, and restore confidence and peace to the country.

lead_paragraph: Since the loss of the Connaught we have intelligence of the loss of the Granada at San Francisco, and of the Arctic, the Edinburgh, the Moscow, the Thor, and the Viscount Lambton, with all on board, in the North Sea or in the Baltic. The Golden Fleece, which took the place of the Connaught on one voyage, is also reported missing. As far as we know anything about it, all this loss of life and property might have been prevented. When the Granada ran upon a reef, she at once filled and broke her back. The five British ships next mentioned were piled with enormous Summer deck loads for a Fall passage; but to the Connaught we wish particularly to refer.

abstract: THE JUVENILE CONCERT AT THE ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The Academy of Music, where GAZZANIGA has warbled, PICCOLOMINI sung, PATTI trilled and CORTESI carolled, "saw another sight" last night, when a thousand juveniles blended their voices in song. Critics, viewing the performance solely as a musical exhibition, would very likely refuse to exchange one prima donna's note for all that were there uttered last evening, but we are perfectly willing to indorse every note which the juveniles issued. The attendance was good, yet not quite as large as might have been expected from the charitable object for which the concert was given, the benefit of City Missions. That the audience was fair is scarcely to be wondered at, if a thousand children sung, since it is safe to say that each child had an average of one parent, one aunt and one uncle, who would feel a natural interest in the occasion, and attend. The little performers were so tastefully attired that the sight would have been a most pleasing one to the eyes, even had not the sound been eminently pleasing to the ears; and the applause which the little company received would have been sufficient to make MARETZEK, on a similar occasion, stand on his head in grateful acknowledgment, if not to bring back the ghost of JULLIEN.

abstract: As a means of throwing some possible light over the mysterious disappearance of fifty thousand dollars from the treasury of the Artisans' Bank a few days prior to that action by the Mayor and Board of Aldermen which transferred the City funds into the keeping of said Bank, we propose to submit, with names and dates, the facts in an action now pending before the Supreme Court of this City, in which Mr. WM. MONTEITH, late a School Commissioner of the Twentieth Ward, appears by his Attorneys, Messrs. SHELDON and THAYER, of 150 Nassau-street, and demands judgment for $200 against Mr. ZACHARIAH E. SIMMONS, of Broadway, said sum being claimed as commission, at one per cent., on a loan of $20,000, which Mr. MONTEITH alleges that he procured for Mr. SIMMONS. If Mr. MONTEITH's statements be correct, and he is a man who has occupied a prominent position in the political world and a fair one in the social, we shall have at last arrived at the definite solution of many mysteries in City Democratic politics.

abstract: WINTER GARDEN. -- It is scarcely necessary to remind the public that Miss CHARLOTTE CUSHMAN's present engagement, -- one of the most successful she has ever played, -- will terminate to-night. The entertainments are of a liberal and varied kind; being, first, Miss CUSHMAM's great personation of Meg Merrilies, to be followed by the new Comedietta, "A Lesson of the Heart," with "The Loan of a Lover," and the "Rendezvous," in which the young debutante, Miss POWELL, will appear. Throughout her long engagement, with scarcely an exception, the house has been crowded to its fullest capacity, but to-night, whether the weather is propitious or not, it will undoubtedly be crammed to overflowing.

abstract: Demarest vs. Timpson. -- The plaintiff in this action sought to recover a balance of salary due him for service rendered while in the employ of defendant. It appeared that defendant kept a store, carrying on chiefly a commission business. He employed plaintiff as a clerk in the store. These facts were conceded, the case turning on the question what plaintiff was entitled to receive. The plaintiff testified the agreement was, he was to have a salary of $60 per month; and, in addition, he was to have the privilege of buying goods, as he found opportunity in the market to be sold at defendant's store; and the profits of these sales were to be equally divided between himself and the defendant. He also testified that a separate account was kept in the store of the purchases and sales made under this arrangement and that defendant had paid $50 on account of the balance due him of the profits. It was admitted that the whole of the monthly salary of $60 had been paid.

abstract: FATAL AFFRAY IN NASSAU-STREET. -- Coroner SCHIRMER was yesterday notified to hold an inquest upon the body of WILLIAM BUND, an Englishman, 58 years of age, whose death occurred at the New-York Hospital, on Thursday night, in consequence of violence received on Tuesday last, it is said at the hands of JOHN CROWLEY, a tinsmith, living at No. 64 Nassau-street. The Coroner was unable yesterday to procure the attendance of the witnesses in the case, and the investigation was postponed until to-day. The circumstances of the assault are said, however, to be as follows: Both men worked for Mr. J. GILHOLEY, keeper of a stove-store at No. 78 Nassau-street, and on Tuesday morning last BUND went into the shop apparently under the influence of liquor. His employer remarked to him that he had been drinking, but he denied that he had, and accused CROWLEY, who stood by, with having carried tales to Mr. GILHOOLEY, when angry words passed between them. CROWLEY presently became very much excited, and picking up a mallet, he struck BUND a severe blow upon the head. Mr. GILHOOLEY then interfered to prevent further violence, after which BUND went to the grocery-store, No. 80 Nassau-street, and called for a glass of beer. Before he could drink it, however, he tottered to a chair and sunk down insensible, remaining in that condition for at least 24 hours, at the expiration of which time the matter was reported to the Second Ward Police, and the injured man was removed from the grocery to the Hospital, where it was ascertained that the base of his skull was fractured. The efforts made to restore him to consciousness proved unavailing, and his death resulted as stated. Meantime, CROWLEY, having heard that BUND was likely to die, fled, and so far he has escaped arrest. The parties had previously been on good terms, and it is supposed that CROWLEY, who is represented to be of a very passionate disposition, committed the deed on the impulse of the moment, without intending to take BUND's life.

abstract: --The great commercial Power which is to spring into existence in the Cotton States, upon the consummation of disunion, will be exposed to one difficulty, the absence of seaports. South Carolina has no outlet save Charleston, and the harbor of Charleston is within a bar, which forbids the approach of any but small vessels, and only those aided by a pilot familiar with narrow and circuitous channels, the position of which shifts constantly with the shifting of the sands. Even the steamers which ply twice weekly between Northern ports and that city, never venture to enter without taking aboard a pilot who has the very latest advices from the bottom. In these days, when the exigencies of trade require shipping of the largest tonnage and the deepest draft, a port, where at low water, vessels drawing no more than eleven feet can alone find admission, is not at all likely to become a modern Tyre.

abstract: In this Court yesterday, before Judge GOULD, the first trial was that of John McGough and his wife, Ann McGough, jointly indicted for the murder of David O'Rorke, on the 25th of September last, at No. 319 Water-street, by stabbing him with a knife. A jury was impanneled with very little difficulty, and the trial proceeded. Col. Michael Doheny, having been assigned by the Court as counsel for defence, desired that a colleague might be assigned with himself. By request of the Court, therefore, Mr. James T. Brady, who happened to be present on other business, undertook the conduct of the defence, and occupied his entire day in the generous discharge of the duty.

abstract: Had any man ventured ten years since to predict the consolidation of Italian liberty by the spontaneous action of the Italian people, he would have been regarded as a madman or a fool. Those who most keenly felt the impossibility of the situation created for Italy by the Holy Alliance, never questioned for a moment the diplomatic doctrine that the relief of this anomalous condition of things must come from Cabinets and Ministers, and could not be anticipated from the popular brain and heart. Centuries of alienation and estrangement, resulting from dynastic intrigues and from commercial rivalries, were supposed to have molded the various branches of the Italian family each into a separate people, fixed and defined within bounds of local tradition, and marked by local qualities of character so absolute and unconquerable that no one could reasonably look to see them abrogated from within. The Genoese, the "Yankees of Italy," were thus held to be forever irreconcilable with their nearest neighbors of Piedmont, and the Venetian seemed to have as little of natural sympathy with the Neapolitan as the Chinese has with the Sikh, or the Pole with the Portuguese. MAZZINI himself, that hero of the impracticable, hailed the prospect of Italian unity with enthusiasm, mainly because he saw no way to it save over the ruins of all existing organizations in the Peninsula. His notion of a regenerated Italy began with conspiracy against the only Italian Government which deserved or received the respect of mankind, and it was his life's consummate purpose to sweep down from the Alps to the Trinacrian Sea every form of authority, so to reconstitute from the heights of the Roman Capitol an ideal and absolute Republic -- a new bottle for the old wine of his race.

abstract: The additional suspensions which we have to report this morning are those of the two Banks in Trenton, New-Jersey, the Pittsburgh (Pa.) Bank, and the long-established private banking-house of SAMUEL HARRIS & SONS, in Baltimore. Relative to the secession movements, there is very little new of importance. Our advices partake of much the same character as heretofore. As an indication of the condition of sentiment in Georgia, a series of resolutions offered in the Legislature are telegraphed, which insist, as the condition of the State remaining in the Union, upon the repeal of those laws in the Northern States, nullifying the Fugitive Slave law, and the enactment of laws by Congress, enabling Southern men to carry their Slaves into the Territories. Retaliatory measures against the North, it seems, have already commenced, and the first demonstrations made are against the free negroes who visit Southern ports in the capacity of sailors. A dispatch from Savannah states that six have been taken from one vessel at that port, and three from another at Fernandina, Fla., and conveyed to parts unknown. The refusal of South Carolina to assent to the proposition of Virginia and other Southern States, that a Convention should be held for the purpose of discussing calmly the question of secession, is severely commented upon by the Virginia journals. The opinion seems to be gaining ground that the South Carolinians are altogether too fast in their proposal to drag all the Slave States after, them whether they are inclined to go or not. A significant commentary upon the outcry against the North for refusing to enforce the provisions of the Fugitive Slave Law, may be found in the fact that two Deputy Marshals arrived in Richmond on Wednesday from New-York, having in their custody a runaway from Kentucky, whom they took measures to deliver to his master. A dispatch from Norfolk states that Gov. WISE has offered his services to Gov. GIST, of South Carolina, in case they are not wanted by Virginia. Some people may consider this an indication that the report relative to his insanity was very near the truth. From South Carolina, we have a reiteration of the assertion that a prominent military man has offered the services of himself and his command to Gov. GIST, in case any fighting is to be done. The name is not given, but the individual may be sufficiently indicated by the statement that he is a distinguished graduate of West Point, and that his father has been a Captain in the United States Army.

lead_paragraph: The President's organ, the Constitution, is determined that the excitement at the South shall not flag for lack of fuel. Its columns are filled every day with demonstrations of the identity between the Republicans and Abolitionists. Senator TRUMBULL'S speech is the red rag which it is just now flouting in the face of the excited and angry South. "All that the South has ever feared, all that the Democracy have indicated as the consequences of LINCOLN's election," says the Constitution, "is here specifically proclaimed by one speaking confessedly in behalf of the President elect." That this assertion is utterly untrue, no one who has read that speech needs to be informed. Mr. TRUMBULL's speech contained nothing whatever that could warrant any such inference, -- and it is only by the grossest and most wanton perversions of his language that any such interpretation can be put upon it.

abstract: I have been in this city long enough, I believe, to ascertain the true feeling of the people. I have conversed freely with gentlemen who have hitherto entertained diverse political opinions. There is no use in being longer deceived as to the real state of public sentiment here in regard to secession. It is wiser for the people of the North to understand, and, if possible, to avoid the consequences of disunion.
lead_paragraph: SAVANNAH, Wednesday, Nov. 21, 1860.

abstract: Our Civil and Criminal Courts have numerous cases on their calendars arising under the recent act against Sunday theatricals. As they come to trial the motive for resistance becomes apparent in the fact that the German theatres depend on their Sunday receipts to make up the losses of the week -- the income on that day being equal to that of all the other days. The lager-beer interest is involved in the same measure in perpetuating the abuse. These two interests are united in the Association formed for the avowed purpose of resisting and overthrowing the law. Perhaps they might accomplish their object, were the matter left solely with our Criminal Courts. But, happily, the law provides adequate civil penalties; and the whole system of dramatic performances on Sunday has already been suppressed by the intervention of the higher Courts.

abstract: William D. Warren, appellant vs. Daniel F. Eddy et al., respondent. -- This action was tried at a Circuit in this City, before Justice Wright, June 24, 1860, and judgment rendered for the plaintiff for $644 51. The case was defended by J.W. Culver, Esq., who appealed and gave the undertaking to stay proceedings, July 2, 1858. Amendments to the case were served on Culver, July 27, 1858, and at the time they were served. Culver notified the person serving them that the defendant, Eddy, for whom he appeared, died in Philadelphia, July 23, 1858, and that he would take no further proceedings in the case. Messrs. Clark and Cornwall were the plaintiff's Attorneys in the original action, but on the appeal E.P. Clark appeared for the respondent without a formal Substitution.

abstract: PADDOCK, the defeated combatant in the pugilistic contest which took place on Tuesday, the 6th inst., is now in London, and considerable apprehensions are entertained as to his recovery from the effects of the severe blow he received in the last round with his powerful opponent, the "Staleybridge Infant." It has been ascertained that PADDOCK's ribs are fractured, and he is suffering greatly from internal injuries; and as his constitution is much impaired by previous illness, he having been a short time since under medical treatment in Middlesex Hospital for paralysis of the lower extremities, his condition is rendered more precarious. Under the most favorable circumstances, the result of this fight will bring to a close PADDOCK's career in the prize ring.

abstract: This case,  which has been on trial in the Supreme Court before Judge LOTT and a jury for several days past, presents some curious,features. The plaintiff, ALFRED BEARDS
lead_paragraph: This case, which has been on trial in the Supreme Court before Judge LOTT and a jury for several days past, presents some curious,features. The plaintiff, ALFRED BEARDSLEY, and defendant, MARY E. BEARDSLEY, were united in marriage in 1849, and lived together until about 1855 without anything special happening to mar their married life. In 1854, it is alleged, Mrs. BEARDSLEY formed, the acquaintance of Dr. FRANCIS MAHAN, under the following peculiar circumstances, as drawn from the Doctor himself, on the witness stand: One pleasant afternoon he was seated in Thompson's Saloon, Broadway, New-York, when he saw defendant, in company with a Miss GREENWOOD, seated at an opposite table. The Doctor and defendant cast furtive glances at each other. Smiles and nods were interchanged. The ladies soon left the saloon. The Doctor followed them. Mrs. BEARDSLEY dropped a flower upon the sidewalk; the Doctor rescued and preserved it until reaching Barnum's Museum, where they all entered, when he restored the lost treasure, and received the smiles and thanks of its fair owner. Suffice it to say that "the acquaintance" thus auspiciously commenced ripened into friendship, and there being but one step from friendship to love, that was easily taken, and resulted in a private marriage in 1855. The ceremony was performed by Rev. Father MALONE, of St. Paul's Church, E.D., under a dispensation granted by Bishop LOUGHLIN. This was rendered necessary by the fact that the parties desired -- for reasons which will hereafter appear -- that the usual bands should not be publishen. Dr. MAHAN swears that up to the marriage he only knew Mrs. BEARDSLEY as MARY EVELINE SEYMOUR, daughter of Admiral SEYMOUR, of Nova Scotia, and it was not until they had been married several months that he discovered she was the wife of another man. She represented to him that she resided with a relative on Brooklyn Heights, and wished their marriage to be kept a secret until after she was twenty-one years of age, because if it was known before that time, she would forfeit a large amount of property to which she would then be entitled. The marriage was consummated at the Brandreth House, International Hotel, at the Drs. office in Wooster-street, and at various other places.

abstract: A fire, involving the destruction of property, valued in the aggregate at over half a million of dollars, broke out soon alter midnight of Saturday, in the large brown stone warehouse at the corner of Church street, extending the entire length of the block from Warren to Murray streets.
lead_paragraph: A fire, involving the destruction of property, valued in the aggregate at over half a million of dollars, broke out soon alter midnight of Saturday, in the large brown stone warehouse at the corner of Church street, extending the entire length of the block from Warren to Murray streets. The premises in which it EXTENSIVE IN THE THIRD WARD, originated were occupied by E. STONE & Co., dry goods dealers and importers, and the flames were first discovered by Police Officer HOYT, issuing from the third story of the building. A number of fire companies were at the moment passing through Broadway, on their return from a fire in Front street, and as quickly as possible they got to work. The intense cold, however, made their operations exceedingly difficult, as the hydrants had frozen, and considerable time elapsed before water could be obtained. Meantime the flames had burst out of every window in the upper story of the building on Church street side, and had thence communicated to the adjoining premises on Warren-street, from which it extended to the building in the rear, fronting on Murray-street, making an area of fire two hundred feet in length by fifty in width, upon which the firemen had to work. In addition to the labor of working to subdue the flames at those buildings, the high wind threw masses of burning cinders and pieces of burning timber upon the roofs of stores in the vicinity, making it necessary for the exercise of great precaution to prevent the destruction of the buildings which were thus endangered. After ten hours hard labor, however, the fire was extinguished, it having been confined to the two large warehouses already mentioned, of which the walls alone remained standing.

abstract: The steamship Ariel, nine days from Aspinwall, arrived at this port yesterday. She brings over a  million in treasure and the San Francisco mails of the 1st inst. Her California advices, however,
lead_paragraph: The steamship Ariel, nine days from Aspinwall, arrived at this port yesterday. She brings over a million in treasure and the San Francisco mails of the 1st inst. Her California advices, however, have been anticipated by the Overland Express. Later news is received from the Isthmus and South America. The long-threatened diplomatic rupture between Peru and the United States has at length occurred, and Mr. CLAY, our Minister, has received his passports. He was to leave Callao on the 12th inst. for New-York, via Panama. We have already given in detail the merits of the dispute, and present to-day the Peruvian version, which appears in the form of a circular sent by the Peruvian Minister of Foreign Affairs to the Diplomatic Corps on the occasion of the suspension of diplomatic intercourse between the two countries. The general news from Peru and Chili is unimportant. From Bolivia we learn that the brief tranquillity which the Republic has lately enjoyed is again disturbed by attempted revolution, and that a more serious danger to the actual Government exists in a threatened invasion by Peru. Fresh fuel has been added to the revolutionary fire in New-Granada, and all hopes of peace seem to have been quenched for the present. The usual number of skirmishes are reported, and the Revolutionists, of course, claim to have been successful; but the truth is that neither party is strong enough to overcome its adversary, and so the resources of the country are being gradually exhausted by this ruinous and reckless civil war. There is a report, indorsed by a Carthagena journal, that the cargo of an American can vessel at Santa Martha had been seized by the authorities for the support of the troops, and also that an American citizen, formerly United States Consul at Carthagena, had been arrested and imprisoned. It is extremely probable that the stories are true, as American interests, here and elsewhere, are entirely without protection. The attempt to find a practicable route for a railroad across the Isthmus, between Chiriqui and the Gulf of Dolce, has been a total failure. So writes a well-informed correspondent.

abstract: The surviving officers and crew of the ill-fated steamer arrived in Louisviile at an early hour yesterday morning, and from them the following information of the disaster has been obtained: On Saturday
lead_paragraph: The surviving officers and crew of the ill-fated steamer arrived in Louisviile at an early hour yesterday morning, and from them the following information of the disaster has been obtained: On Saturday evening the Pacific left Louisville for New-Orleans. She stopped at New-Albany for some freight and a few patsengens, and then proceeded on her way, calling at Cannelton, Evansville and Henderson. She arrived at Uniontown on Sunday evening, about 6 1/2 o'clock. It was then dark, and coal was being received on, when a quantity of hay in the vicinity of the boilers was discovered to be on fire. They broke out the ignited bales, but too late to prevent the spread of the flames and the dreadful casualty.

abstract: DEAR OLD UNCLE ABE: Don't let your foes frighten nor your friends fool you into making a pronounceymenter, (that's Mexican for telling what you're goin' to do in hifalutin style,) to p[???]sify the South. You just keep as quiet us KARY and as dumb as LOUY NAPOLEON, and it 'ill all come round right. Let 'em rare and pitch a little; you're on the box and have got hold of the ribbons. After snortin' and kickin' awhile they'll settle down into the traces and go right straight along. If you do come to a steep pitch, them old wheelers, Virginia and Kentucky, will keep the team steady. Above all, don't check 'em too sudden, but keep 'em in the road, and let 'em run till they begin to blow; then take 'em up easy and they'll go along quiet for a good long spell. Ef you follow my advice I expect to hear folks say of you what old GYSOTT said of the two BONEYPARTS. The success of Old ABE makes us wonder whether "Old Hickory" was really a genus.

abstract: Charles Layton was the next witness called by the complaintant. He testified I have lived in Chicago since May, 1856; have known Mr. Burch since June, 25, 1856; The wanted a gardener; I went down to see him; he hired me to take care of
lead_paragraph: Charles Layton was the next witness called by the complaintant. He testified I have lived in Chicago since May, 1856; have known Mr. Burch since June, 25, 1856; The wanted a gardener; I went down to see him; he hired me to take care of his garden and his horse, and do other chores about the house; I went there July 13, 1856; lived with him to Nov. 13, 1859; I took care of the garden, grapery and horse, went to market to bring things for the house, &c., first became acquainted with Mrs. Burch in October of that year, on her return from the East; know David Stuart; have seen him at Mr. Burch's house; the first time I saw him there was in January, 1657; saw him first in the parlor; I went in the parlor -- some things came by express and Mrs. Burch sent for me to come up stairs to unpack them; when I went to the parlor door Mrs. Burch said I was to unpack those things, and Mr. Stuart would help me which he did; it was a clock and some bronzes; Mr. Stuart kept telling me what to do all the time in unpacking the things and taking them out -- which way I was to do it; when we were putting the clock on the mantel-piece, he told me to lift my end of the clock up, and I told him to lift his up, and that he was not my employer; Mrs. Burch told me not to speak to him so, and I said he should not talk to me so; Mrs. Burch told me to go down stairs, which I did; I say him there in the evening when I shut the house up; I could see Mr. Stuart in the room; my habit was to shut up the house at ten o'clock when there was no company there; if there was company, I was to wait until they were gone; I went up a second time, and Mrs. Burch called to me, and told me I could shut up the house, and go to bed, which I did; Mrs. Burch and Mr. Stuart were playing checkers or backgammon with a board on their knees; my bed is on the second floor from the main floor; the back of the front door was such that being opened in the ordinary way it could be heard at any part of the house; at that time Mr. Burch was away East, at least he was away -- I do not know where; [witness described the process of shutting up the house:] it would take fifteen or twenty minutes to shut up the house; saw Mr. Stuart at the house I think the next evening; would not be positive think he went away while I was shutting up the house; there were no other persons in the room with Mr. Stuart and Mrs. Burch on this or the previous evening when I shut up the house: Mr. Burch was gone three or four weeks at this time, I think, during which time I should think I saw Mr. Stuart there five or six times; two other; times he was there when I closed up; on one occasion they were playing checkers in a bedroom; and another time they were sitting in the library side by side reading; did not hear them say anything; do not know at what time Mr. Stuart left when I went to bed leaving him there; should have heard the front door close if shut before I went to sleep; one night Mrs. Burch told me to shut up the house, that I need not wait for Mr. Stuart, but if anyone else was there I could wait until he had gone; after Mr. Burch's return did not see Mr. Stuart there; the first time he came and brought some rose bushes; Mr. Burch was there then; I took them out in the yarn, or in the grapery; the next occasion he came on some railroad business, talking with Mr. Burch in the library; I heard them mention railroads; this was the fore part of 1857; the next time I saw Mr. Stuart there was either in the forenoon or afternoon, when Mr. Burch was not home; he came in that way two or three times alone in the Spring of 1857; think I saw him come once or twice from down-town with Mr. Burch in the forenoon, about eleven o'clock; I saw him there in the library; one time I went into the grapery, and found some one had been breaking the laterals off the vines; I saw somebody had been breaking them off, and I knew no one could get in; I asked the girl, and she told me that Mr. Stuart and Mrs. Burch had been there; I asked, who had been breaking the vines, and Mrs. Burch said Mr. Stuart had; I told him that it was none of his business; that when the vines wanted pruning I would do it, and that if I caught him at it I would put him out of the place; do not recollect that Mr. Stuart said any thing; Mrs. Burch told me to go down stairs, and I did; I went into the room in a great hurry; Mrs. Burch and Mr. Stuart were standing up against the library table; Mr. Turner came down stairs when he came home to dinner, and said -- [objected to;] Mr. Turner was Mrs. Burch's brother; this was in 1857; saw Mr. Stuart next there at the time of the bank panic, in the latter part of the Summer of 1857; Mrs. Burch came down and told me that I need not tell Mr. Burch about the vines; that she would tell him herself; I told her that I would tell Mr. Burch, and I did so; when Mr. Burch was gone three or four weeks, I think I saw Mr. Stuart there as many as five or six different times; I think the same night or the next after Mr. Burch went away; think he was in the library with Mrs. Burch alone when I finished closing the house; saw him there on Sunday evening; think they were in the parlor; Mr. Turner was living in the house at that time; I know I saw Mr. Stuart there during Mr. Burch's absence two or three times when I shut up the house; saw him there one time when Mr. Burch was gone to Michigan; he was sometimes in the parlor, or the library, alone with Mrs. Burch; recollect the two young ladies (the piece and Miss Spaulding) coming from the East early in 1858; the night of their arrival Mr. Stuart and Mrs. Burch were in the library playing bacgammon or checkers; Mrs. Burch told me to go down and receive the young ladies at the midnight train; I noticed that Mrs. Burch had on a different dress than usual; thought she looked redder than usual last evening; when I came back from the depot, about 10 A. M., Mr. Stuart had gone; Mr. Burch was away; Mrs. Burch had changed her dress, and told the young ladies that she had been sitting up waiting for them; on the evening of Mr. Stuart's visit, when the young ladies arrived, I heard the servant, Margaret, make a remark; it was right away after she came down stairs; she had been up to the door (when Mrs. Farnam called.)

abstract: The explosion of the Mohawk, and of the Globe, lake steamers, within a few days, instantly killing 18 persons, in addition to the six similar disasters within a little over a fortnight, very seriously suggests the question of a better
lead_paragraph: The explosion of the Mohawk, and of the Globe, lake steamers, within a few days, instantly killing 18 persons, in addition to the six similar disasters within a little over a fortnight, very seriously suggests the question of a better boiler material -- at least better than cast iron, the failure of which, in the boiler of the H.R.W. Hill, last week, cost forty persons their lives. Meanwhile, from motives of economy, thick wrought-iron plate is objected to as being expensive and heavy. The Albany Iron Works are furnishing boiler-steel warranted to stand a third to a half more pressure than first-class iron, at the price of first-class iron. Several English manufacturers are doing the same. Why is not steel employed?

abstract: The country is again threatened with very serious dangers from Kansas. lead_paragraph: The country is again threatened with very serious dangers from Kansas. The movements of Capt, MONTGOMERY, -- in themselves sufficiently exasperating, -- are likely to be sohandled by desperate and reckless politicians as greatly to add to the sectional excitement and increase the difficulties of restoring peace. He is represented by the current reports as waging a war of Abolition, and as threatening and actually taking the lives of Pro-Slavery men in his vicinity. On the other hand, it is asserted that the question of Slavery has nothing to do with the movement, -- but that the people who have been driven from their homes and despoiled of their property, by authority of the Federal Government, have taken up arms in their own defence.

abstract: The indictment, a short time since, of three harbor-masters, appointees of Gov. MORGAN, for taking illegal fees, excited no little comment, and became the occasion of severe attacks, in the political Press, on the system of
lead_paragraph: -- The indictment, a short time since, of three harbor-masters, -- appointees of Gov. MORGAN, -- for taking illegal fees, excited no little comment, and became the occasion of severe attacks, in the political Press, on the system of Executive appointment, as administered by the present incumbent of the Executive chair. The accused professed themselves anxious for the investigation, and a Democratic District-Attorney promised them speedy and entire satisfaction in this respect. The public, therefore, expected, with considerable interest, the development of the case, and held its judgment in suspense until a jury should decide the issue. But the best laid "plans of men and mice gang aft astray;" and in the Court of Oyer and Terminer, on Saturday, the indictments against the accused officials came to a natural death, the result of constitutional defects, existing from their birth.

abstract: TRIBUTE TO  WORTH. The Herald misunderstands us. We had no thought of disparaging its influence or of hurting its feelings.
lead_paragraph: -- TRIBUTE TO WORTH. -- The Herald misunderstands us. We had no thought of disparaging its influence or of hurting its feelings. We acknowledge, moreover, the becoming modesty which prompts it to disclaim having so much power to create business panics, and to ruin private character and credit, as some of its neighbors, moved thereto doubtless by jealousy, are inclined to ascribe to it. Instances of such self-depreciation are sometimes met with in other walks of life. A man who creates a temporary panic in the Fire Department, and sets all the fire-bells in the City ringing a general alarm, by the mere use of a lucifer match, seldom obtrudes his "power" and "influence" upon public notice. The man who throws a Ward into commotion by committing a murder in it, is quite apt to hide his great faculties in retirement -- and even that great artist who dispatched Dr. BURDELL, and threw the whole community into an excitement which the Herald's finest efforts have seldom equaled, has modestly put aside all public recognition of his greatness, and claimed neither the honors nor the rewards which the public would gladly pay.

abstract: The arrival of the Spanish frigate Berenguela, in our harbor, attracted considerable notice, and a large number of our citizens were anxious to visit her as soon as she dropped anchor. Like all other strangers, she desired to don her best dress, put on her best behavior, and be equipped to the uttermost advantage, before she was placed under surveillance by a scrutinising public. The report which went abroad, and which we unintentionally assisted to disseminate, that visitors would not be admitted without "passes" is unfounded. Capt. RODRIGUEZ and his officers will be glad to receive and entertain every respectable citizen who may present himself at the ship's side for admission. No passes are required, and American machinists are especially invited to come "on board." The Spanish Captain says, with true liberality, "come one and all, and we will treat you well."

abstract: Mr. ULLMAN has lifted his little head once more above the troubled waters in which he has tumbled the past two months. The hope so long deferred
lead_paragraph: Mr. ULLMAN has lifted his little head once more above the troubled waters in which he has tumbled the past two months. The hope so long deferred which has made sick the operatic heart has come at last. "La Juive" is to be brought out to-night with even greater circumstance and crowds than distinguished its production at the Winter Garden last Spring, where the perfume of two hundred super "dignitaries" at 10 cents each a night absolutely fumed everyone out of the house. Even still the vase retains somewhat of their fragrance. Mr. ULLMAN promises us, we perceive, in addition to a variety of acolytes and people of that class, no less than two cardinals, three archbishops and four bishops, which, considering that this commodity is becoming scarce on the other side, is extremely liberal. The cast includes, in addition to FABBRI and STIGELLI, who appeared in this opera at the Winter Garden, FORMES and ANNA BISHOP. The same leader, ANSCHUTZ, reigns over the orchestra -- MAX MARETZEK not having yet returned from the Havana. The Muzio troupe open also to-night at the Academy of Music at Philadelphia.

abstract: The accounts received from vessels arriving at this port, as well as dispatches from the East, represent the easterly gale of Friday night as very severe along our whole coast, and it is very probable that we shall yet hear of serious disasters to vessels which were exposed to its fury.
lead_paragraph: The accounts received from vessels arriving at this port, as well as dispatches from the East, represent the easterly gale of Friday night as very severe along our whole coast, and it is very probable that we shall yet hear of serious disasters to vessels which were exposed to its fury. Towards midnight of Friday the gale begun to moderate, and at daylight on Saturday morning the wind had changed to the Northwest, from which direction it continued to blow throughout the day with even more fury than it had prevailed from the opposite quarter. With the change of wind, there was also a sudden and corresponding change of temperature of more than twenty degrees, giving the first earnest instalment of Winter which we have yet experienced. The shores of the Bay and inlets were yesterday fridged with ice, and navigation on the canals must have already been closed. With the exception of some vessels which had anchored under the lee of Sandy Hook during the easterly gale, and which were suddenly caught on a lee shore when the wind changed, and thus suffered somewhat, we hear of no particular damage done to the shipping in our harbor.

abstract: Another attempt on the part of the police authorities at suppressing the Sunday traffic in liquors, was initiated on Saturday last. Since Mr. KENNEDY has occupied the position of Superintendent of Police, no active measures have been adopted for the punishment of the violators of the law, the operations of the police having been confined merely to the reporting of the offenders every Monday morning at the office of the District Attorney. In this way nearly ten thousand complaints have accumulated on the shelves of the Public Prosecutor since the commencement of Mr. KENNEDY's appointment, making, with the addition of those reported previously, a grand total of abou thirty thousand cases upon which no judicial action has been taken; a few hundred of the cases only having been brought to judgment. In view of this discouraging state of things, and the District-Attorney having announced his intention to wait the result of an appeal in one of the cases, before attempting to prosecute any of the others, it has recently been determined to arrest the offenders by a summary process, and try the effect of confining them at least for one night in the cell of a Station-house. Accordingly, on Saturday, the various Police Captains were summoned at Headquarters, and informed that as their present efforts for suppressing the Sunday liquor traffic had resulted in no good whatever, in future the other method was to be enforced. Directions were then given to notify the liquor-dealers that yesterday would be the last day in which they would be suffered to proceed in their open violation of law without being arrested, and every Sabbath hereafter, not only the proprietors of the liquor-shops, but also their bar-keepers, or substitutes, who might be found engaged in the public sale of intoxicating drinks, were to be taken into custody. This information having been generally given, its effect was yesterday very marked. Most of the dram-shops were closed, and the total number of arrests of intoxicated persons in every Precinct of the City was but 50 -- 34 of whom were males and 10 females, being a decrease of at least three-fourths from the usual number. The Sunday theatres are also to fall under the ban of the authorities, and yesterday the first move towards preventing representations in them was made. At 8 o'clock last evening Inspector CARPENTER, Capt. MCKELVEY,of the Twenty-second Ward, and a force of men visited the Blume Turn Halle, No. 198 West Thirty-sixth-street, where a large audience of both sexes was witnessing theatrical performance. Inspector CARPENTER went upon the stage and addressed the crowd, who dispersed, at his request, while six of the actors were taken into custody and locked up for the night. The names of the prisoners are SIMON BRENNER, GEORGE MANN, WM. KIESLER, ANTHONY KESSEL, PHILIP ANDREAS and CHAS. LANG.
lead_paragraph: Another attempt on the part of the police authorities at suppressing the Sunday traffic in liquors, was initiated on Saturday last. Since Mr. KENNEDY has occupied the position of Superintendent of Police, no active measures have been adopted for the punishment of the violators of the law, the operations of the police having been confined merely to the reporting of the offenders every Monday morning at the office of the District Attorney. In this way nearly ten thousand complaints have accumulated on the shelves of the Public Prosecutor since the commencement of Mr. KENNEDY's appointment, making, with the addition of those reported previously, a grand total of abou thirty thousand cases upon which no judicial action has been taken; a few hundred of the cases only having been brought to judgment. In view of this discouraging state of things, and the District-Attorney having announced his intention to wait the result of an appeal in one of the cases, before attempting to prosecute any of the others, it has recently been determined to arrest the offenders by a summary process, and try the effect of confining them at least for one night in the cell of a Station-house. Accordingly, on Saturday, the various Police Captains were summoned at Headquarters, and informed that as their present efforts for suppressing the Sunday liquor traffic had resulted in no good whatever, in future the other method was to be enforced. Directions were then given to notify the liquor-dealers that yesterday would be the last day in which they would be suffered to proceed in their open violation of law without being arrested, and every Sabbath hereafter, not only the proprietors of the liquor-shops, but also their bar-keepers, or substitutes, who might be found engaged in the public sale of intoxicating drinks, were to be taken into custody. This information having been generally given, its effect was yesterday very marked. Most of the dram-shops were closed, and the total number of arrests of intoxicated persons in every Precinct of the City was but 50 -- 34 of whom were males and 10 females, being a decrease of at least three-fourths from the usual number. The Sunday theatres are also to fall under the ban of the authorities, and yesterday the first move towards preventing representations in them was made. At 8 o'clock last evening Inspector CARPENTER, Capt. MCKELVEY,of the Twenty-second Ward, and a force of men visited the Blume Turn Halle, No. 198 West Thirty-sixth-street, where a large audience of both sexes was witnessing theatrical performance. Inspector CARPENTER went upon the stage and addressed the crowd, who dispersed, at his request, while six of the actors were taken into custody and locked up for the night. The names of the prisoners are SIMON BRENNER, GEORGE MANN, WM. KIESLER, ANTHONY KESSEL, PHILIP ANDREAS and CHAS. LANG.

abstract: we have always held tne "Personal Liberty laws" and other leged obstructions thrown in the way of the rendition of fugitive slaves to be useless and pernicious. To present this view now may be misinterpreted into a pusillanimous yielding to Southern clamor. But no matter; it is magnanimous to confess and repair a wrong, and it the Free States have been wrong in this matter, it will be honorable in them to correct the error. We do not suppose it will be done under the present excitement, because it will look like an attempt to conciliate the Disunionists; but there is no harm in looking at facts as they are, and preparing to act when the proper time comes. It is very well understood that on this point alone is the South able to make out a prema facie case, either of violation of the Constitution or of injustice to the Slave States on the part of the North. And here they do make it out. It is of no use to quibble about it, and attempt to force another construction upon the language of the Constitution; there is no shadow of doubt that the framers of the Constitution intended to provide and did provide for the rendition of slaves, and although the present Fugitive Slave law contains provisions repugnant to all the established principles of law, and repulsive to all the sentiments of humane and Christian [???]n, it is constitutional in its intent and scope, and is so pronounced by all competent judicial authorities. It is not strange that a law so barbarous in its spirit and so it gardless in some of its provisions of the rights of the race exposed to its influence should encounter resistance, and that men and women everywhere should use all the means within their power to shield and protect the fugitive negroes. This feeling, so universal in the Free States, will prevent, as it always has, the return of any considerable number of ogitives who have once touched free soil. The personal liberty laws were not needed to make this fact certain, and they do not in the slightest degree contribute to it; on the contrary, they hinder it, by promoting the slave owners to a more obstinate determination torecover their property, and by counting the more energetic efforts of the General Government. Under the most stringent of these" personal liberty" laws negroes proved to be slaves are just as inevitably returned to their masters, and the only difference is that they make the process more expensive and annoying. These Northern retaliatory laws, therefore while they do not prevent the return of a single negro to slavery, have the effect to exasperate the South, and give her occasion to complain that we refuse to fulfill an article of the compact most essential to them.

abstract: Mayor WOOD'S proclamation for Thanksgiving Day is about as dismal a bit of literature as we have met for a long time.
lead_paragraph: Mayor WOOD'S proclamation for Thanksgiving Day is about as dismal a bit of literature as we have met for a long time. It sounds more like a chapter from Lamentations, or from the querulous questionings of JOB, than a summons from the Chief Magistrate of a Christian City, to the grateful duty of rendering thanks to the Giver of all our blessings. The Mayor protests that he can see nothing to be thankful for. Freedom from pestilence and from war, bountiful harvests, employed and rewarded industry, the health and happiness of a great people, -- all these count for nothing in his catalogue of blessings. These he seems to consider as only his due, -- things not to be grateful for, but only to be growled over as utterly inadequate to his expectations and deserts.

abstract: There are wars and rumors of wars in the inner circles of our City Democracy. Nothing less than a regularly organized conspiracy on the part of the "outs" to get in; while those who are "in" display no particular desire to continue so, but are resolved that the conspiratorial "outs" shall not be their successors. In the dire conflict now raging, the old Wigwam of Tammany Hall rocks and reels upon its foundations. Such heavy artillery was never before brought to bear against it as is now firing hot-shot, bombshells, grape, shrapnels and asphyxiating balls under the distinguished superintendency of GEORGE H. PURSER, THOMAS BYRNES, JOHN NESBITT, WILLIAM MINER, ISAIAH RYNDERS, and some dozen others of equally high character and popularity.

abstract: From the best information which could be obtained, on which to base an estimate of the losses by the fire in Warren and Murray streets, on Saturday night, it was thought that over half a million dollars worth of property had been consumed.
lead_paragraph: From the best information which could be obtained, on which to base an estimate of the losses by the fire in Warren and Murray streets, on Saturday night, it was thought that over half a million dollars worth of property had been consumed. Further inquiry yesterday, however, shows that the loss has been somewhat over-estimated, and that the probable amount of damage does not exceed $400,000. We append a revised list of the occupants, and a statement of the insurances. It is now thought that the fire broke out on the second floor of No. 33 Warren-street.

abstract: ATTEMPT BY BURGLARS TO BLOW OPEN A SAFE. On Saturday night the coal office of RANDALL  MORRELL, at the foot of Grand-street, Jersey City, was entered by burglars, and an attempt was made to blow open the safe.
lead_paragraph: ATTEMPT BY BURGLARS TO BLOW OPEN A SAFE. -- On Saturday night the coal office of RANDALL & MORRELL, at the foot of Grand-street, Jersey City, was entered by burglars, and an attempt was made to blow open the safe. Overturning the safe, with the lock upwards, they filled the keyhole with powder, and laid a safety fuse therefrom to a pile of paper a few feet off, which they set on fire. For some reason this arrangement did not work, when the rascals returned, and attempted to ignite the powder by placing near it a sperm candle; but again they were doomed to disappointment. The candle not being properly placed, the matted sperm dropped upon the powder and prevented it from taking fire. Finding their labor in vain, the burglars left the premises without further search.

abstract: Our Kansas correspondent gives a very emphatic contradiction to the alarming reports that have reached us from Southern Kansas.
lead_paragraph: Our Kansas correspondent gives a very emphatic contradiction to the alarming reports that have reached us from Southern Kansas. He denies that any such acts of violence have been committed as were reported, and brands the whole story as a fiction from beginning to end. We scarcely know what to make of these extraordinary contradictions. Our correspondent is a resident of Kansas, reliable and likely to be well informed; and, on the other hand, it seems scarcely possible that such statements should have been fabricated for any purpose whatever.

abstract: Indications to-day are decidedly in favor of an early change in the Cabinet. The state of affairs in Georgia, and the position of Secretary COBB has so affected him as to lay him up sick in bed.
lead_paragraph: Indications to-day are decidedly in favor of an early change in the Cabinet. The state of affairs in Georgia, and the position of Secretary COBB has so affected him as to lay him up sick in bed. In the meantime, his family are packing up for home, and will be ready to leave in a few days. Mr. COBB now alleges that ill health precludes the possibility of his continuing in his laborious position. Secretary THOMPSON will no doubt follow suit, in view of the late action of the Mississippi Senators and Representatives, though without the pretext of ill health.

abstract: We were somewhat mistaken in attributing the original suggestion of the idea of paying for fugitive slaves to Mr. BADGER, of North Carolina.
lead_paragraph: We were somewhat mistaken in attributing the original suggestion of the idea of paying for fugitive slaves to Mr. BADGER, of North Carolina. By referring to the Appendix to the Congressional Globe, first session of the Thirty-first Congress, where the whole debate on the subject may be found, it will be seen that the proposition originated with a Senator from Maryland, Mr. PRATT. On the 20th of August, 1850, Mr. PRATT moved to amend the pending bill for the reclamation of fugitive slaves by the addition of several sections, in which it is provided that if the fugitive, after being identified, and proven to be the property of the claimant, be not delivered up within a specified time, the latter may bring suit against the District-Attorney, before the Circuit or District Court, for the recovery of the value of the slave.

abstract: The fact that the South is not altogether given over to the Secessionists will be gathered from our dispatches this morning. Hon. ALEXANDER H.
lead_paragraph: The fact that the South is not altogether given over to the Secessionists will be gathered from our dispatches this morning. Hon. ALEXANDER H. STEPHENS, it will be seen, has been unanimously nominated by the citizens of Taliaferro County, Ga., as Delegate to the State Convention which is soon to meet to discuss the grave questions now agitating the country. Those who read his speech, published in the TIMES last week, will have no difficulty in believing that at least one conservative voice will be raised in warning against precipitation. In Baltimore, yesterday, the secession spirit was rebuked in a significant manner. A palmetto flag was displayed by an association calling themselves the "Southern Volunteers," and it provoked only groans and hisses from a large crowd which collected around it. And the captain of a vessel in the harbor, who displayed the same flag at his masthead, was rebuked immediately by the display of the stars and stripes from all the other vessels in port. Hon. EDMUND RUFFIN, of Virginia, as we learn from our Richmond correspondent, has returned from South Carolina, having failed in his efforts to identify the "Old Dominion," with the secession movement. From Washington, we continue to receive rumors relative to changes in the Cabinet. It is now somewhat positively asserted that Secretary COBB, and probably Secretary THOMPSON, will soon resign their places. There seems, however, to be no certainty about it yet. A report that Judge TANEY had resigned his seat on the Bench of the Supreme Court, is pronounced to be premature. He will not vacate his seat until the question of his successor is definitely settled. He has no idea of allowing the appointment to go into the hands of the Republicans. The steamship Columbia, which arrived yesterday from Charleston, brought back forty-seven more steerage passengers, and -- what is somewhat unusual -- a consignment of $16,800 specie.

abstract: This case was continued before Judge LOTT, in the Supreme Court, yesterday. Samuel L. Caverly was the first witness sworn. He testified to visiting several places of bad repute accompanied by plaintiff and others.
lead_paragraph: This case was continued before Judge LOTT, in the Supreme Court, yesterday. Samuel L. Caverly was the first witness sworn. He testified to visiting several places of bad repute accompanied by plaintiff and others. Rev. Joseph Law, Sr., father of the defendant, was next placed on the stand. He testified that he united plaintiff and defendant in marriage in the Spring of 1849; they went to Rhinebeck and remained until September, when they came to his house and stayed until the next Spring; then went to board at the house of H.S. Law, in South Ninth-street, E.D.; lived there about two years: they then kept house in Wilson-street about two years; from there defendant went to the house of witness to reside; that was in 1857. The balance of the testimony of this witness was intended to show that defendant was not the woman married to Dr. Mahan by Father Malone, and seemed to convey the idea that Miss Greenwood was the woman married at that time; he could not identify the handwriting of several notes shown, as that of his daughter; (these notes were received by Dr. Mahan, and he swore that he received them from defendant;) Mahan had told witness that it was Miss Greenwood he had married, and fully contradicted several other statements of the Dr. on the stand.

abstract: The chartered steamers of the Paraguay expedition are turning out as was anticipated. Every month extensive and costly repairs have to be effected on them.
lead_paragraph: The chartered steamers of the Paraguay expedition are turning out as was anticipated. Every month extensive and costly repairs have to be effected on them. They break down in hull and machinery in the most unexpected manner. The Mohawk and the Crusader on the home station, and the Mystic on the Coast of Africa, are said to be in a miserable state; and the Wyandotte and Sumpter are little better. They have already cost the country more money than as many more gunboats of twice their tonage would have done.

abstract: DISTRESSING SUICIDE OF A MARRIED LADY. Coroner SCHIRMER On Sunday afternoon held an inquest at the house No. 137 Second-avenue, upon the body of Mrs. CAROLINE OLMSTEAD, a young married lady, who had been found dead in her bedroom on Saturday last.
lead_paragraph: DISTRESSING SUICIDE OF A MARRIED LADY. -- Coroner SCHIRMER On Sunday afternoon held an inquest at the house No. 137 Second-avenue, upon the body of Mrs. CAROLINE OLMSTEAD, a young married lady, who had been found dead in her bedroom on Saturday last. The husband of deceased testified that he left his home about 10 o'clock on Saturday morning last to go to his place of business; his wife, when he parted from her, appeared to be in a cheerful frame of mind and in perfect health. About 6 o'clock in the evening he returned home, and on going to his apartment he was surprised to find the door locked. Receiving no response to his repeated calls for admission, he procured a duplicate key from the landlady and unlocked the door. On entering the room, the first object that he saw was his wife, who lay upon the floor, her head beneath a chair, and her body perfectly cold and lifeless. A physician was called but he said Mrs. OLMSTEAD had been dead several hours. Witness further testified that a few years ago his wife had frequently threatened, when laboring under fits of despondency, to poison herself, and on several occasions he had taken laudanum from her, which he believed she had purchased with the object of committing self-destruction. Recently, however, she seemed to be more easy in her mind, and he had not heard her make any threats against her life. He knew of no reason which could have prompted the act, except that deceased had recently felt greatly mortified because one of her brothers had been convicted of an offence and was in prison at the Tombs. Dr. GEORGE B. BOUTON made a post-mortem examination of the body and found in the stomach a quantity of stramonium seeds, which, in his opinion, had produced death. The jury rendered a verdict to that effect. Deceased was a native of this City, 26 years of age.

abstract: As we approach more closely to the Charter Election, and see more clearly the calibre of the candidates selected by the various Nominating Conventions, we are more and more impressed with the necessity for some radical
lead_paragraph: As we approach more closely to the Charter Election, and see more clearly the calibre of the candidates selected by the various Nominating Conventions, we are more and more impressed with the necessity for some radical change in our present system of City Government. We cannot submit forever to be represented in the Common Council by men who have no other object in seeking public trust than to betray and plunder their constituencies and pocket the profits of corruption. A City of intelligence, honesty, commercial honor and wealth, should have men representing these traits in her senior and junior boards of municipal legislation; but while the present district-system of election is allowed to continue, it must be vain to hope for any serious or marked improvement in the average of men selected to act as members of the Common Council.

As they despair of securing a restoration of this traffic within the Union, they are determined to try their chances outside.

abstract: Justices CONNOLLY, KELLY and STEERS on Saturday disposed of the ordinary number of petty cases, none of them having any special interest. Of twenty-one persons charged, with assault and battery, six were discharged, no witnesses appearing against them, two were discharged by request of complainant, three were discharged under suspended sentence, four were allowed postponement, three were fined, and three imprisoned. Of forty-one persons charged with petty larceny, six were discharged, no witnesses appearing; eight were discharged under suspended sentence, four were allowed postponement, five were remanded, seventeen were imprisoned and one acquitted. One person charged with embezzlement, was acquitted. The case of one charged with keeping a disorderly house, was postponed, and the same disposition was made of four cases for gambling.

abstract: -The schooner Forest King, of New-Haven, from Rio Janeiro Oct. 13, reports that when beating out of the bay she fell in with the bark Meaco, of Charleston, Capt. JOSE, for New-Orleans, with colors union down, returning to Rio, from whence she had sailed four days previous. The Forest King sent on board and found the bark in charge of the second officer, the Captain having been stabbed by the chief mate, a young man who had been shipped a few days previous, Aug. 25, on the outward passage.

abstract: -- The venerable Chief Justice TANEY has arrived at a period of life making repose and the absence of undue excitement essential to his continuance in health. It is not right -- it is absolutely cruel -- to keep an old public servant, who has long passed the allotted term of three score years and ten, in perpetual doubt, hesitation and hot water as to whether he is or is not any longer an incumbent of the honorable office which has grown familiar to him through so many years of occupation.

abstract: -SUPREME COURT, BEFORE JUDGE LOTT. -- The testimony in this case was closed yesterday. Several witnesses were placed on the stand, who testified to the good character of Dr. MAHAN, and that they would believe a statement made by him under oath or not under oath. Rev. Father MALONE, who, it is alleged, united defendant and Dr. MAHAN in marriage, was recalled. He testified that he had seen Miss GREENWOOD yesterday, and she was not the woman whom he married to Dr. MAHAN. The testimony was closed at about 2 o'clock P.M., when the Court allowed the counsel three hours on each side in which to sum up the case. Mr. SHAFFER for the defense occupied his full time, and at 5 o'clock was followed by Mr. BUSTEED. At the conclusion of Mr. BUSTEED's speech, the Court announced that he would charge the jury at 10 o'clock this morning, to which time the Court was then adjourned.

abstract: Yester  day morning a melancholy accident occurred at HERRING'S gutta-percha comb-factory, No. 163 West
lead_paragraph: Twenty-seventh-street, causing the death of ELLEN JANE CUSH, a child, 14 years of age, who was employed in the establishment. She had just gone to work, and happening to pass close to a revolving belt, used for driving the polishing machines, her dress was caught, and she was whirled up to the shaft, where her head was crushed between the pulleys and the ceiling. When extricated, life was extinct, and the body was removed to the residence of her parents, No. 115 West Twenty-eighth-street, where an inquest will be held.

abstract: To-night Mr. ULLMAN proposes to repeat to us, at the Academy of Music, one of the most remarkable musical triumphs of the year. We trust that in this
lead_paragraph: repetition he may be happily enabled to include the splendors of the audience as well as the effects of the stage, for not the least striking feature of the performance of "La Juive," in Irving-place, on Monday night, was the holiday appearance of the house, crowded from pit to gallery, and with a distinctly operatic monde. Let us add that this audience was thrown into unusual and exhilarating relief by a really brilliant illumination. The lights of the Academy commonly serve to make visible the darkness of the boxes. They discourage fresh toilettes among the ladies, and new gloves among the gentlemen, and in this way dampen very considerably the legitimate atmosphere of the Opera, which is, or ought to be, that of a refined social Capua, winning men and women both away, for a few brief hours, from the excitements, passions and anxieties of the "garish day." Under the blaze of Monday evening, the whole house assumed a festive air, altogether unexpected by the oldest habitue, and the new proscenium boxes, which complete the tier of the lower balconies, and most agreeably replaces the hideous vomitoria of the old regime, with their oscillating hordes of lounging Philistines, were inaugurated most successfully. Never did the New-York Opera House seem so truly a house of opera as on Monday. The management, perhaps with delicate eye to future economies, announce that the luminous magnificence of this occasion, was only a reminiscence of the Prince of Wales' ball, intended to delight the souls of all the uncivilized thousands who found no favor in the sight of the "four hundred" elect on that auspicious occasion. We must urge it upon them to alter all this, and to erect the lights of Monday into a permanent institution. Shall we say as much for "La Juive?"

abstract: The letter from our Kansas correspondent which we publish this morning, throws some light upon the condition of affairs in Southern Kansas. It confirms the statements which
lead_paragraph: have been made of the movements of Capt. MONTGOMERY to a very considerable extent. It represents him as being at the head of a band of men who have usurped the functions of the Courts of Law, and undertaken the arrest, trial and punishment of persons accused or suspected of crime; and their special object is to punish the crime of "kidnapping negroes," -- by which we suppose is meant recapturing fugitive slaves. All purpose of crossing the border, or interfering with the slaves in Missouri or Arkansas, is especially repudiated. But "the moment a slave sets foot on Kansas soil," says our correspondent, "he is free, and they will protect him at all hazards. Any man convicted of having kidnapped a human being in this Territory shall die."

abstract: The most important feature of the news relating to the secession movement this morning is the message of Gov. GIST, of South Carolina, sent to the Legislature of that State, which assembled yesterday. He considers disunion a foregone con
lead_paragraph: clusion, and confidently relies upon the States of Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Florida, Texas and Arkansas, to follow the lead of South Carolina, though he has no hopes of a Confedercy of all the Southern States. In this connection, he takes Virginia to task for refusing to entertain the proposition of Col. MEMMINGER last year, and declares that it is now too late to attempt to assemble a Conference of the Slave States to consider the propriety of the pending movement. He cannot permit himself to believe that an attempt will be made by the present or the incoming Administration to coerce the State after she shall have seceded, by a refusal to surrender the harbor defences, or by interfering with the imports and exports; but if it shall prove that this view is wrong, the State must accept the issue presented, and fight her way to the best of her ability. He does not seem to consider that the establishment of new postal arrangements throughout the State, after the Federal Postmasters shall have resigned, will be a difficult matter, but in the meantime he proposes to use Adams Express for the distribution of correspondence. The reports which reach us from other Southern States present no feature of special importance. At Louisville, Ky., on Monday night, a mass meeting was held, composed of men of all parties, at which resolutions were adopted, declaring that Kentucky does not despair of justice within the Union, and appealing to the South not to desert the common cause. A letter from President MADISON, heretofore unpublished, appears in a Virginia paper, which takes strong ground against the right of secession.

abstract: AN UNGRATEFUL DAUGHTER. -- A girl named ANN TILLEY, about seventeen years of age, was taken into custody, yesterday afternoon, by Officer SLOAN, of Jersey City, on a charge of stealing $12 50 in money and several articles of wearing apparel from her mother. The poor woman gains a livelihood by selling apples at the depots, and this money she had saved from her scanty earnings to purchase flour and other necessaries for the coming Winter. The girl acknowledged her guilt and was committed for examination.

abstract: The screw steamship City of Baltimore, Capt. PETRIE, which sailed from Liverpool on the morning of the 14th, and from Queenstown on the 15th, arrived at this port yesterday. abstract: It is to be hoped that one of the first acts of Congress at its approaching session will be to admit Kansas into the Union.
lead_paragraph: It is due to her as an act of simple justice, and it is due to the whole country as healing one of the sources of mischievous and dangerous agitation. The. treatment which Kansas has received at the hands of the party now in power has been discreditable to them and highly injurious to the country at large. The only occasion on which that party has shown any disposition to admit her into the Union was when she was presented with a Constitution notoriously forced upon her against the will of her people, and stained with every mark of fraud and corruption.

abstract: Commodore  VANDERBILT has been routed from the Battery. Judge HOGEBOOM, of the Superior Court, has made the recent injunction perpetual, thus leaving the Commodore the pressing necessity of removing his incipient pier at the earliest moment.
lead_paragraph: Commodore VANDERBILT has been routed from the Battery. Judge HOGEBOOM, of the Superior Court, has made the recent injunction perpetual, thus leaving the Commodore the pressing necessity of removing his incipient pier at the earliest moment. Upon what other portions of the ground plot of the City, or its water front, he may now locate will be a matter of temporary interest and curiosity. We would suggest the peculiar aptitude of the city docks at Hammond street for vessels of the large size he is proposing to build for European traffic; with the hint that from the profits thus saved from an insatiate City Comptroller, a sumptuous town residence might be built on a portion of the Central Park, overlooking the Serpentine Lake, and of course held rent free. In the modesty which offered no defence to the petition of the Corporation, but simply questioned its solvency in point of security, we find confidence that this Sovereign of Squatters is equal to these bold conquests.

abstract: The municipal authorities of Savannah have, some way or other, become confused in their minds as to the true intent and meaning of the compound word "steerage-passenger."
lead_paragraph: -- The municipal authorities of Savannah have, some way or other, become confused in their minds as to the true intent and meaning of the compound word "steerage-passenger." In a proclamation just issued by the Mayor of that city, "the evils resulting from the importation" of this class of human beings, are described as "both manifest and alarming." The Mayor appears laboring under the misapprehension that all white men willing to work for wages must be "paupers," and that the mere fact of a man's traveling in the steerage or second cabin of a steamship is proof positive of an intention on his part to ask for admittance to the Almshouse of whatever city he may be landed at. In evidence of this strange delusion, under which the Mayor of Savannah labors, we quote the following phrases, all of which occur in a document of fifty printed lines in length:

abstract: The United States vs. Rossi Hilario. The prisoner in this case was put on trial charged with passing counterfeit coin.
lead_paragraph: The United States vs. Rossi Hilario. -- The prisoner in this case was put on trial charged with passing counterfeit coin. The evidence for the Government showed that he went with another Italian, named Sala, to several small shops, and bought cakes, beer and cigars, &c., sometimes both going in, and sometimes one alone; that at the first store he gave a quarter dollar in payment, which the man tried with acid, and finding it bad, called the men back and they gave him good money. They then went away, and he told the facts to a policeman, who followed and watched them, and saw them go into several shops and buy, and in one other shop they also passed a bad quarter; that the officer arrested them and searched them, and found some small money on Hilario's person, and some of it bad.

Among others, CARPENTER, who holds high rank among native artists, is quite busy. He has just finished a full-length portrait of CHARLES F. NEWTON, for the "Metropolitan Masonic Lodge," of which Mr. NEWTON was the founder, and is completing a life-like three-quarter picture of Mr. L.B. SHAW, whose sternly good-natured features will be easily recalled by the every-day frequenters of the Custom-house. The exquisite picture and absolute portrait of "Brooklyn's Chiefest Belle," which attracted general attention at the last exhibition, is again on the easel for a few re-touches, prior to its delivery.

abstract: A general discussion of the Southern question took place in the Cabinet yesterday, according to our Washington dispatches, though it does not appear that any conclusion was arrived at as to the proper course to be pursued in certain contingencies.
lead_paragraph: A general discussion of the Southern question took place in the Cabinet yesterday, according to our Washington dispatches, though it does not appear that any conclusion was arrived at as to the proper course to be pursued in certain contingencies. The meeting, however, is represented to have been in the main harmonious, though there were differences of opinion on the subject of secession. Secretary COBB was not present. Excitement increases at the National Capital as the time for the assembling of Congress approaches, and fears are expressed that some unwise thing may be said or done which will result in a serious collision between the members. An editorial article has made its appearance in the Kentucky Statesman, recognized as Mr. BRECKINRIDGE's home organ, which is alleged to have been written by Mr. BRECKINRIDGE himself. A strong appeal is made in it to the conservative element of the South. If Mr. BRECKINRIDGE had spoken sooner, it might have had a better effect. In Virginia, meetings in favor of and opposed to secession are held daily. There appears to be a strong disinclination among her public men to come forward at the present time and give expression to their views. Gov. HICKS, of Maryland, has peremptorily declined to convene the Legislature of that State in special session. He is ready, he says, to go as far as any man in demanding the rights of the South in the Union, but refuses to place Maryland in the position of seeming to countenance treason. The banks at Charleston, S.C., have at last succumbed under the extraordinary pressure upon them, and suspended specie payments. The St. Louis banks, with one exception, also suspended yesterday.

abstract: There can be no difference of opinion on the great importance of establishing direct trade between Charleston and Liverpool, or any other country with which we can exchange commodities.
lead_paragraph: There can be no difference of opinion on the great importance of establishing direct trade between Charleston and Liverpool, or any other country with which we can exchange commodities. In the Union, it was important and necessary to our commercial prosperity to divert a part of the commerce of the world from New-York and other Northern cities to the City of Charleston, and thus build up a great commercial emporium, with ability to supply our own and the merchants of the neighboring States, with a cheap and well-filled market; from which in turn, they could supply their customers in the interior towns and villages.
