abstract: LECTURE ON BRAZIL. Rev. J.C. FLETCHER delivered the second lecture of his very entertaining series at the Cooper Institute last evening.
lead_paragraph: LECTURE ON BRAZIL. -- Rev. J.C. FLETCHER delivered the second lecture of his very entertaining series at the Cooper Institute last evening. The attendance was large, though the gigantic proportions of the Hall naturally tended to make the audience seem smaller than it was. Mr. FLETCHER seems to have secured a parish of hearers, and he deserves one, for few better than he possess the art of instructing and amusing in the same breath. Last evening he devoted himself to drawing pictures of life in the tropics, painting the luxuriant forests, and imparting information in relation to the insects, serpents, alligators, monkeys, half-breeds and other interesting inhabitants of that section of the world. The manners and customs of the country were treated at length, and Don PEDRO Segundo, who seems to be an especial favorite of Mr. FLETCHER's, came in for an especial eulogy. The lectures will be continued as announced in our advertising columns, and three more complete the series.

abstract: The fact that all  of the Free Labor States in the Union, a fraction of the inhabitants of that purgatorial State, New-Jersey, alone excepted, have given their votes to LINCOLN, is at last ascertain  ed. California and Oregon have unquestionably gone for the Republican ticket.
lead_paragraph: -The fact that all of the Free Labor States in the Union, a fraction of the inhabitants of that purgatorial State, New-Jersey, alone excepted, have given their votes to LINCOLN, is at last ascertained. California and Oregon have unquestionably gone for the Republican ticket. We thus have seventeen and four-sevenths of the States Republican; while for the opposite parties there are fifteen and three-sevenths of the number: -- fractions for the vulgarity of which, as we have remarked, New-Jersey, is to be held answerable. It is to be hoped the three Douglas Electors of that State, timely shrinking from the singularity of their position, will go with the current by casting their votes for LINCOLN. The inutility of any other course should invite them to this; not because the victorious candidate could thus enhance his victory, but the rotund completeness of the thing would give an aesthetic finish, and perfection to the pose of the North, of which purely political results seldom admit. The effect on the future fame of New-Jersey might also have weight.

abstract: Shortly after 8 o'clock yesterday morning a great deal of excitement was occasioned in the First Ward, by the bulging outwards, and fall of a large portion of the rear wall of S.A. MELLICK'S five story brick storage warehouses, Nos. 36 and 38 Whitehall-street, causing the destruction of several hundred barrels of flour and jeopardizing the lives of many persons.
lead_paragraph: Shortly after 8 o'clock yesterday morning a great deal of excitement was occasioned in the First Ward, by the bulging outwards, and fall of a large portion of the rear wall of S.A. MELLICK's five story brick storage warehouses, Nos. 36 and 38 Whitehall-street, causing the destruction of several hundred barrels of flour and jeopardizing the lives of many persons. The structure had only recently been completed, and it had not been occupied more than a couple of months. It comprised three large stores, having a frontage of 50 feet on Whitehall street, running back a distance of 75 feet, and connecting with an extension building, 40 feet deep, forming what is called an L, fronting on Pearl-street, where it was numbered 22. The warehouses were guaranteed by the architect who superintended their construction to bear the weight of all the flour that could be packed into them -- some 20,000 barrels -- but the buildings had never been filled to their utmost capacity because of the recent date of their occupancy. However, 12,000 barrels of flour had been distributed throughout the various floors, and Mr. MELLICK, confiding in the representations of the architect as to the strengh of the building, was still receiving the merchandise as fast as it could be brought in. Yesterday morning his laborers had just commenced operations in the way of "snugging up" the barrels on the top floor, when they were startled by a crashing noise and the instantaneous disappearance of the rear end wall of the Pearl-street extension, the whole of which fell out from the eaves to the third story, and the unsupported-end of the roof settled upon the flour barrels in the form of an inclined plane. The laborers by running to the front part of the building escaped injury, and hurrying to the street an alarm was given. Capt. SILVEY, with Sergeants SNODGRASS and CHERRY, happening to be in the neighborhood with a squad of men, at once formed a cordon about the dangerous premises, which were almost concealed by the cloud of dust and flour which had been raised, and prevented persons from parsing by. An examination was men cautiously entered upon, and it was found that the wall had fallen into the yard of an old four-story tenement house, No. 20 Pearl-street, occupied by fourteen families, numbering nearly eighty persons, all of whom, excepting CATHARINE CAIN, a girl fifteen years of age, escaped with no further injury than a terrible fright. The girl CATHARINE was in the yard, and hearing the cracking of the wall, she jumped down the cellar steps, but before she had time to recover her footing some of the bricks had fallen upon her. Fortunately, however, the mortar caused the wall to adhere, and it lay across the cellar-way, forming a vault in which the girl lay concealed. As quickly as her perilous position was discovered, several Policemen and others, regardless of the danger to which they were necessarily exposed if any other part of the wall should become detached, entered upon the task of removing the rubbish, and after half an hour's careful labor, their efforts to release her were successful. She was found to have received no other injury than a few severe bruises. Orders were at once given for the removal of the families from the tenement house, as if was feared that another portion of the wall might topple over upon the roof, and jeopardize the lives of the inmates. Many of the poor people in their distress had nowhere to go for shelter, and some desired to remain and take the risk, but the Police compelled them all to leave the place in spite of their dissatisfaction. Later in the day a builder examined the premises, and gave it as his opinion that the disaster had resulted from the weakness of the wall which separated the Whitehall-street buildings from that on Pearl-street, it having been cut through in several places with arched doorways for facility of communication. The case is very similar to that which happened a year ago this month in Broad-street, when KENT, LOWBER & CO.'s warehouse fell from over-crowding, causing the death of Mr. WM. ELY, of Brooklyn, and Policeman STEWART, who were buried in the ruins. The owner of the premises is Mr. JOHN T. JOHNSTON, President of the New-Jersey Central Railroad Company, against whom a warrant of arrest has been issued on the complaint of Sergeant LORD, of the Sanitary Squad, who reports the building to be in an unsafe condition. It is said that the loss upon flour and damage to the building will amount to $60,000.

abstract: One  of the horrors with which the North has been threatened, as a fruit of the retirement of the Gulf States, is the immense addition we shall receive to our free colored population.
lead_paragraph: One of the horrors with which the North has been threatened, as a fruit of the retirement of the Gulf States, is the immense addition we shall receive to our free colored population. It is well understood that the laws for the expulsion or enslavement of this class of negroes, now pending in South Carolina, will not only be passed, but find imitation in the other States which are likely to follow the lead of that froward Commonwealth; and we are widely assured that some hundreds of thousands of paupers will thus be thrown upon the charities of the Northern States.

abstract: The theme of nearly all the Thanksgiving discourses preached yesterday in our City pulpits, was the political crisis in which the country is involved. It seems to us very proper that this should be so. Indeed, we have never favored that divorce of the Pulpit from politics which many excellent persons deem essential to the welfare of both. The object of preaching is to apply the principles of Christianity to the conduct of life, -- to bring them to bear upon personal character, and upon the general well-being and improvement of society. Why should any form of social activity be exempt from such an application? Why should any duty which men are called on to perform, be abandoned by teachers of the Christian faith, to be discharged Without regard to the motives and maxims of Christian truth?

abstract: In another, column will be found a brief review of the more prominent candidates for those vacancies in the Board of Aldermen which are to be filled at the Charter election held next month. There are many other candidates for these offices in the field, some self-nominated and without any prospect of polling more than a few dozen votes; others claiming to have been nominated by Peoples' or Independent Peoples' Conventions; aend still others who are professional candidates, only remaining in this position until they can ascertain which side will give them the higher price to withdraw. As a general rule it may safely be set down, that every stump Republican candidate has been placed on the track in order to draw off votes from the regular nominee, and help his Democratic opponent -- the same axiom applying to stump nominees on the Democratic side.

abstract: At the various benevolent institutions. Thanksgiving Day, which is always the most welcome festival of the year, was a truly joyous occasion. The still and Summer-like weather permitted every one who felt inclined to go abroad, and the charitable institutions were visited by more than the usual throng of sympathising patrons, who gave the best possible evidence of their continued interest in their favorite charities by liberal bequests in money and in articles of comfort for the beneficiaries. At the Five Points there were unusually lively times. In response to the modest appeals of the officers of the Five Points House of Industry, liberal donations were sent in from all the principal hotels in the City of provisions for furnishing the thanksgiving tables. Immense pieces of roast beef, roast turkeys and chickens, boiled tongues, with vegetables of all kinds ready cooked; besides baskets full of pies, puddings, cakes and fruits. With such tempting viands, it is not strange that the largest and most enthusiastic assemblage of poor and hungry children, as well as grown people who had no dinner at home, were seasonably on hand to partake of the annual appointed feast. At an early hour in the forenoon all the children, dressed in their neat holiday attire, were assembled in the Chapel, when they were addressed by Mr. WESONG and Mr. ROCKWELL, the exercises being interspersed with music. Mr. BARLOW, the Superintendent, also gave a narrative of scenes and incidents which he had witnessed during his visits through the neighboring localities, which were very affecting. In the afternoon dinner was served, at which eight or nine hundred children and adults sat down, or rather stood up, and this part of the ceremonies occupied the time until 2 1/2 o'clock P.M. The boys marched from their playroom at the music of the fife and drum, the drummer, a colored lad, exhibiting great skill in the art. The refreshments being concluded, the children and visitors again assembled in the Chapel, where the exercises of singing and addresses were resumed, GEORGE BRIGGS, Rev. Mr. BURTUS, Rev. Mr. FITCH and others being the speakers.

abstract: STEALING FROM AMATXUR GYMNASTS. -- For a long time past the gentlemen attending the Oriental Gymnasium, No. 48 Bayard-street, have been losers to a great extent by the operations of an adroit thief, who was in the habit of stealing watches, money and clothing from the dressing-rooms. THOMAS CORBETT, a young man who has frequently visited the place, but who had never joined the gymnasium, was suspected of being the depredator, but he managed his movements so skillfully that none of the thefts were ever fixed upon him. On Friday evening, however, a watch worth $50, was stolen from Mr. JOHN J. SHAW, one of the pupils, and it was determined to take CORBETT into custody. He was arrested by Officer GOLDEN, of the Sixth Ward, and at first he denied his guilt, but after spending some time in prison, he confessed that he had, within a few months, robbed the gymnasium students of property valued at $1,500. A large part of the money that he thus realized he expended in the purchase of presents to bestow upon a respectable young lady in Brooklyn, to whom he had engaged himself in marriage, and she, upon hearing of his roguery, made such restitution as was in her power. A quantity of pawn-tickets, representing some of the stolen watches, was found at the prisoner's boarding-house, No. 240 Broome-street, and the timepieces were recovered. Among the losers were WM.J. HUCHES, of No. 49 Wall-street, who had a watch and chain worth $70 stolen; WM.G. BELL, of No. 13 Rutgers-street, lost $130 in cash; RODNEY N. CURTIS, a clerk in the Metropolitan Bank, lost two watches worth $100, and $90 in money, and the proprietor of the gymnasium had clothing valued at $50 stolen. Justice BRENNAN yesterday held the accused for trial.

abstract: We have nothing new of importance regarding the secession movement to report this morning. Attention is now being concentrated principally at the Federal Capital, and speculation is busy with the probable action of Congress at the opening of the session, and the effect, which it will have upon the present agitation. We also have a variety of surmises as to the composition of Mr. LINCOLN's Cabinet. Gov. LETCHER, of Virginia, has written another letter to an inquiring Pennsylvanian, in which he gives his views somewhat at length on the topics of the day. It is supposed to foreshadow the tone of his message to the Virginia Legislature, at the coming extra session of that body. The principal topic discussed by him is the Fugitive Slave law, and the nullifying statutes passed by the Legislatures of Northern States. From South Carolina, we learn, that another meeting of the Bank Directors of Charleston has been held, at which it was unanimously resolved to suspend specie payments. Gov. HAMMOND, in a letter to a Georgia Secession meeting, has expressed the opinion that South Carolina will be out of the Union forever by the 18th of December.

abstract: An empty seat is always a rarity in Dr. CHAPIN's church, and, yesterday morning, in spite of the balmy beauty of the day, there was not even one to mutely invite an addition to the congregation. In spite of the beauty of the day, we say, for it is an indisputable fact, that pleasant weather crowds a church with vacant pews quite as much as unpleasant, especially when the day be not Sunday. Broadway, in its beauty, is generally quite as attractive to the majority as the narrow way, -- if anything, the balance trembles in favor of the former. But Dr. CHAPIN, yesterday morning, had a charm to stay the tide of humanity that is ceaselessly ebbing and flowing along the great mart, and it streamed through the open doors of his church, flowing up the aisles, circling round the pulpit, and filling every nook and corner of the building. The occasion was a Thanksgiving sermon, and the text was the 6th and 7th verses of the fourth chapter of Psalms:

abstract: In 1832, Mr. ALEXANDER RIVES, over the signature of "A Friend of Union and State Rights," published two communications in the Virginia (Charlottesville) Advocate. abstract: At 11 1/2 o'clock last night, PATRICK KELLY was almost instantly killed at the rear of No. 215 Front-street, by JOHN MCCAULEY. The parties had some talk together, when the wife of deceased aroused a young man named JOHN MCTAMNEY, residing at No. 217 Front-street, and asked him to quell the disturbance between her husband and MCCAULEY. MCTAMNEY went into the yard, and was passing between the combatants, when MCCAULEY stabbed him in the left thigh. He threw him to the ground. and MCCAULEY, upon rising, stabbed KELLY in the left breast. KELLY walked to the door of the house and fell a corpse. MCCAULEY escaped in his shirt sleeves and without a hat. The Police were immediately notified, and will probably arrest him during the night.
